ll of his brothers."UÑShe called the name of Yahweh who spoke to her, "You are a God who sees," for she said, "Have I even stayed alive after seeing him?"UUTherefore the well was called Beer Lahai Roi. Behold, it is between Kadesh and Bered.UWHagar bore a son for Abram. Abram called the name of his son, whom Hagar bore, Ishmael.U@Abram was eighty-six years old when Hagar bore Ishmael to Abram.t(NUÜWhen Abram was ninety-nine years old, Yahweh appeared to Abram, and said to him, "I am God Almighty. Walk before me, and be blameless.UOI will make my covenant between me and you, and will multiply you exceedingly."U4Abram fell on his face. God talked with him, saying,U^"As for me, behold, my covenant is with you. You will be the father of a multitude of nations.UâNeither will your name any more be called Abram, but your name will be Abraham; for I have made you the father of a multitude of nations.UaI will make you exceedingly fruitful, and I will make nations of you. Kings will come out of you.U∞I will establish my covenant between me and you and your seed after you throughout their generations for an everlasting covenant, to be a God to you and to your seed after you.UûI will give to you, and to your seed after you, the land where you are traveling, all the land of Canaan, for an everlasting possession. I will be their God."UvGod said to Abraham, "As for you, you will keep my covenant, you and your seed after you throughout their generations.UÅThis is my covenant, which you shall keep, between me and you and your seed after you. Every male among you shall be circumcised.UnYou shall be circumcised in the flesh of your foreskin. It will be a token of the covenant between me and you.UΩHe who is eight days old will be circumcised among you, every male throughout your generations, he who is born in the house, or bought with money from any foreigner who is not of your seed.UóHe who is born in your house, and he who is bought with your money, must be circumcised. My covenant will be in your flesh for an everlasting covenant.UìThe uncircumcised male who is not circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin, that soul shall be cut off from his people. He has broken my covenant."UlGod said to Abraham, "As for Sarai your wife, you shall not call her name Sarai, but her name will be Sarah.UûI will bless her, and moreover I will give you a son by her. Yes, I will bless her, and she will be a mother of nations. Kings of peoples will come from her."UØThen Abraham fell on his face, and laughed, and said in his heart, "Will a child be born to him who is one hundred years old? Will Sarah, who is ninety years old, give birth?"U=Abraham said to God, "Oh that Ishmael might live before you!"U≤God said, "No, but Sarah, your wife, will bear you a son. You shall call his name Isaac. I will establish my covenant with him for an everlasting covenant for his seed after him.UÕAs for Ishmael, I have heard you. Behold, I have blessed him, and will make him fruitful, and will multiply him exceedingly. He will become the father of twelve princes, and I will make him a great nation.U`But my covenant I establish with Isaac, whom Sarah will bear to you at this set time next year."U<When he finished talking with him, God went up from Abraham.UÁAbraham took Ishmael his son, all who were born in his house, and all who were bought with his money; every male among the men of Abraham's house, and circumcised the flesh of their foreskin in the same day, as God had said to him.UXAbraham was ninety-nine years old, when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin.U^Ishmael, his son, was thirteen years old when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin.UDIn the same day both Abraham and Ishmael, his son, were circumcised.UyAll the men of his house, those born in the house, and those bought with money of a foreigner, were circumcised with him.t(NU_Yahweh appeared to him by the oaks of Mamre, as he sat in the tent door in the heat of the day.U¶He lifted up his eyes and looked, and saw that three men stood opposite him. When he saw them, he ran to meet them from the tent door, and bowed himself to the earth,Udand said, "My lord, if now I have found favor in your sight, please don't go away from your servant.UVNow let a little water be fetched, wash your feet, and rest yourselves under the tree.U±I will get a morsel of bread so you can refresh your heart. After that you may go your way, now that you have come to your servant." They said, "Very well, do as you have said."U}Abraham hurried into the tent to Sarah, and said, "Quickly make ready three measures of fine meal, knead it, and make cakes."UpAbraham ran to the herd, and fetched a tender and good calf, and gave it to the servant. He hurried to dress it.UHe took butter, milk, and the calf which he had dressed, and set it before them. He stood by them under the tree, and they ate.UJThey said to him, "Where is Sarah, your wife? He said, "See, in the tent."U£He said, "I will certainly return to you when the season comes round. Behold, Sarah your wife will have a son." Sarah heard in the tent door, which was behind him.UoNow Abraham and Sarah were old, well advanced in age. It had ceased to be with Sarah after the manner of women.UlSarah laughed within herself, saying, "After I have grown old will I have pleasure, my lord being old also?"UaYahweh said to Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh, saying, 'Will I really bear a child, yet I am old?'UIs anything too hard for Yahweh? At the set time I will return to you, when the season comes round, and Sarah will have a son."UbThen Sarah denied, saying, "I didn't laugh," for she was afraid. He said, "No, but you did laugh."UeThe men rose up from there, and looked toward Sodom. Abraham went with them to see them on their way.U1Yahweh said, "Will I hide from Abraham what I do,Uyseeing that Abraham has surely become a great and mighty nation, and all the nations of the earth will be blessed in him?UÛFor I have known him, to the end that he may command his children and his household after him, that they may keep the way of Yahweh, to do righteousness and justice; to the end that Yahweh may bring on Abraham that which he has spoken of him."UeYahweh said, "Because the cry of Sodom and Gomorrah is great, and because their sin is very grievous,UvI will go down now, and see whether their deeds are as bad as the reports which have come to me. If not, I will know."UVThe men turned from there, and went toward Sodom, but Abraham stood yet before Yahweh.UMAbraham drew near, and said, "Will you consume the righteous with the wicked?UÇWhat if there are fifty righteous within the city? Will you consume and not spare the place for the fifty righteous who are in it?UÃBe it far from you to do things like that, to kill the righteous with the wicked, so that the righteous should be like the wicked. May that be far from you. Shouldn't the Judge of all the earth do right?"UrYahweh said, "If I find in Sodom fifty righteous within the city, then I will spare all the place for their sake."UfAbraham answered, "See now, I have taken it on myself to speak to the Lord, who am but dust and ashes.U£What if there will lack five of the fifty righteous? Will you destroy all the city for lack of five?" He said, "I will not destroy it, if I find forty-five there."U}He spoke to him yet again, and said, "What if there are forty found there?" He said, "I will not do it for the forty's sake."UóHe said, "Oh don't let the Lord be angry, and I will speak. What if there are thirty found there?" He said, "I will not do it, if I find thirty there."U°He said, "See now, I have taken it on myself to speak to the Lord. What if there are twenty found there?" He said, "I will not destroy it for the twenty's sake."UùHe said, "Oh don't let the Lord be angry, and I will speak just once more. What if ten are found there?" He said, "I will not destroy it for the ten's sake."UjYahweh went his way, as soon as he had finished communing with Abraham, and Abraham returned to his place.t(NUõThe two angels came to Sodom at evening. Lot sat in the gate of Sodom. Lot saw them, and rose up to meet them. He bowed himself with his face to the earth,UŸand he said, "See now, my lords, please turn aside into your servant's house, stay all night, wash your feet, and you will rise up early, and go on your way." They said, "No, but we will stay in the street all night."UçHe urged them greatly, and they came in with him, and entered into his house. He made them a feast, and baked unleavened bread, and they ate.UçBut before they lay down, the men of the city, the men of Sodom, surrounded the house, both young and old, all the people from every quarter.UçThey called to Lot, and said to him, "Where are the men who came in to you this night? Bring them out to us, that we may have sex with them."U>Lot went out to them to the door, and shut the door after him.U5He said, "Please, my brothers, don't act so wickedly.U”See now, I have two virgin daughters. Please let me bring them out to you, and you may do to them what seems good to you. Only don't do anything to these men, because they have come under the shadow of my roof."UÍThey said, "Stand back!" They said, "This one fellow came in to live as a foreigner, and he appoints himself a judge. Now will we deal worse with you, than with them!" They pressed hard on the man Lot, and drew near to break the door.U\But the men put forth their hand, and brought Lot into the house to them, and shut the door.UçThey struck the men who were at the door of the house with blindness, both small and great, so that they wearied themselves to find the door.UõThe men said to Lot, "Do you have anybody else here? Sons-in-law, your sons, your daughters, and whoever you have in the city, bring them out of the place:UÖfor we will destroy this place, because the outcry against them has grown great before Yahweh that Yahweh has sent us to destroy it."U–Lot went out, and spoke to his sons-in-law, who were pledged to marry his daughters, and said, "Get up! Get out of this place, for Yahweh will destroy the city." But he seemed to his sons-in-law to be joking.U¨When the morning came, then the angels hurried Lot, saying, "Get up! Take your wife, and your two daughters who are here, lest you be consumed in the iniquity of the city."U≥But he lingered; and the men grabbed his hand, his wife's hand, and his two daughters' hands, Yahweh being merciful to him; and they took him out, and set him outside of the city.U¿It came to pass, when they had taken them out, that he said, "Escape for your life! Don't look behind you, and don't stay anywhere in the plain. Escape to the mountains, lest you be consumed!"U'Lot said to them, "Oh, not so, my lord.U—See now, your servant has found favor in your sight, and you have magnified your loving kindness, which you have shown to me in saving my life. I can't escape to the mountain, lest evil overtake me, and I die.UáSee now, this city is near to flee to, and it is a little one. Oh let me escape there (isn't it a little one?), and my soul will live."UçHe said to him, "Behold, I have granted your request concerning this thing also, that I will not overthrow the city of which you have spoken.UrHurry, escape there, for I can't do anything until you get there." Therefore the name of the city was called Zoar.U5The sun had risen on the earth when Lot came to Zoar.UWThen Yahweh rained on Sodom and on Gomorrah sulfur and fire from Yahweh out of the sky.UoHe overthrew those cities, all the plain, all the inhabitants of the cities, and that which grew on the ground.UJBut his wife looked back from behind him, and she became a pillar of salt.URAbraham got up early in the morning to the place where he had stood before Yahweh.UúHe looked toward Sodom and Gomorrah, and toward all the land of the plain, and looked, and saw that the smoke of the land went up as the smoke of a furnace.U∑It happened, when God destroyed the cities of the plain, that God remembered Abraham, and sent Lot out of the middle of the overthrow, when he overthrew the cities in which Lot lived.U°Lot went up out of Zoar, and lived in the mountain, and his two daughters with him; for he was afraid to live in Zoar. He lived in a cave with his two daughters.UéThe firstborn said to the younger, "Our father is old, and there is not a man in the earth to come in to us after the manner of all the earth.UjCome, let's make our father drink wine, and we will lie with him, that we may preserve our father's seed."UóThey made their father drink wine that night: and the firstborn went in, and lay with her father. He didn't know when she lay down, nor when she arose.U„It came to pass on the next day, that the firstborn said to the younger, "Behold, I lay last night with my father. Let us make him drink wine again, tonight. You go in, and lie with him, that we may preserve our father's seed."UåThey made their father drink wine that night also. The younger went and lay with him. He didn't know when she lay down, nor when she got up.U=Thus both of Lot's daughters were with child by their father.U[The firstborn bore a son, and named him Moab. He is the father of the Moabites to this day.UqThe younger also bore a son, and called his name Ben Ammi. He is the father of the children of Ammon to this day.t(NU~Abraham traveled from there toward the land of the South, and lived between Kadesh and Shur. He lived as a foreigner in Gerar.UdAbraham said about Sarah his wife, "She is my sister." Abimelech king of Gerar sent, and took Sarah.U§But God came to Abimelech in a dream of the night, and said to him, "Behold, you are a dead man, because of the woman whom you have taken. For she is a man's wife."U[Now Abimelech had not come near her. He said, "Lord, will you kill even a righteous nation?U•Didn't he tell me, 'She is my sister?' She, even she herself, said, 'He is my brother.' In the integrity of my heart and the innocence of my hands have I done this."UæGod said to him in the dream, "Yes, I know that in the integrity of your heart you have done this, and I also withheld you from sinning against me. Therefore I didn't allow you to touch her.U¿Now therefore, restore the man's wife. For he is a prophet, and he will pray for you, and you will live. If you don't restore her, know for sure that you will die, you, and all who are yours."UÉAbimelech rose early in the morning, and called all his servants, and told all these things in their ear. The men were very scared.U⁄Then Abimelech called Abraham, and said to him, "What have you done to us? How have I sinned against you, that you have brought on me and on my kingdom a great sin? You have done deeds to me that ought not to be done!"UMAbimelech said to Abraham, "What did you see, that you have done this thing?"UvAbraham said, "Because I thought, 'Surely the fear of God is not in this place. They will kill me for my wife's sake.'UwBesides, she is indeed my sister, the daughter of my father, but not the daughter of my mother; and she became my wife.U¿It happened, when God caused me to wander from my father's house, that I said to her, 'This is your kindness which you shall show to me. Everywhere that we go, say of me, "He is my brother."'"UÉAbimelech took sheep and cattle, male servants and female servants, and gave them to Abraham, and restored Sarah, his wife, to him.ULAbimelech said, "Behold, my land is before you. Dwell where it pleases you."UΩTo Sarah he said, "Behold, I have given your brother a thousand pieces of silver. Behold, it is for you a covering of the eyes to all that are with you. In front of all you are vindicated."UkAbraham prayed to God. God healed Abimelech, and his wife, and his female servants, and they bore children.UiFor Yahweh had closed up tight all the wombs of the house of Abimelech, because of Sarah, Abraham's wife.t(NUNYahweh visited Sarah as he had said, and Yahweh did to Sarah as he had spoken.UgSarah conceived, and bore Abraham a son in his old age, at the set time of which God had spoken to him.UJAbraham called his son who was born to him, whom Sarah bore to him, Isaac.UYAbraham circumcised his son, Isaac, when he was eight days old, as God had commanded him.UGAbraham was one hundred years old when his son, Isaac, was born to him.UKSarah said, "God has made me laugh. Everyone who hears will laugh with me."UwShe said, "Who would have said to Abraham, that Sarah would nurse children? For I have borne him a son in his old age."U\The child grew, and was weaned. Abraham made a great feast on the day that Isaac was weaned.UPSarah saw the son of Hagar the Egyptian, whom she had borne to Abraham, mocking.UÜTherefore she said to Abraham, "Cast out this handmaid and her son! For the son of this handmaid will not be heir with my son, Isaac."UEThe thing was very grievous in Abraham's sight on account of his son.UÀGod said to Abraham, "Don't let it be grievous in your sight because of the boy, and because of your handmaid. In all that Sarah says to you, listen to her voice. For from Isaac will your seed be called.UOI will also make a nation of the son of the handmaid, because he is your seed."U„Abraham rose up early in the morning, and took bread and a bottle of water, and gave it to Hagar, putting it on her shoulder; and gave her the child, and sent her away. She departed, and wandered in the wilderness of Beersheba.URThe water in the bottle was spent, and she cast the child under one of the shrubs.U¿She went and sat down opposite him, a good way off, about a bow shot away. For she said, "Don't let me see the death of the child." She sat over against him, and lifted up her voice, and wept.UΩGod heard the voice of the boy. The angel of God called to Hagar out of the sky, and said to her, "What ails you, Hagar? Don't be afraid. For God has heard the voice of the boy where he is.UXGet up, lift up the boy, and hold him in your hand. For I will make him a great nation."UqGod opened her eyes, and she saw a well of water. She went, filled the bottle with water, and gave the boy drink.UdGod was with the boy, and he grew. He lived in the wilderness, and became, as he grew up, an archer.U]He lived in the wilderness of Paran. His mother took a wife for him out of the land of Egypt.UäIt happened at that time, that Abimelech and Phicol the captain of his army spoke to Abraham, saying, "God is with you in all that you do.U˚Now, therefore, swear to me here by God that you will not deal falsely with me, nor with my son, nor with my son's son. But according to the kindness that I have done to you, you shall do to me, and to the land in which you have lived as a foreigner."UAbraham said, "I will swear."UmAbraham complained to Abimelech because of a water well, which Abimelech's servants had violently taken away.UwAbimelech said, "I don't know who has done this thing. Neither did you tell me, neither did I hear of it, until today."UUAbraham took sheep and cattle, and gave them to Abimelech. Those two made a covenant.U7Abraham set seven ewe lambs of the flock by themselves.UaAbimelech said to Abraham, "What do these seven ewe lambs which you have set by themselves mean?"UxHe said, "You shall take these seven ewe lambs from my hand, that it may be a witness to me, that I have dug this well."UHTherefore he called that place Beersheba, because they both swore there.UëSo they made a covenant at Beersheba. Abimelech rose up with Phicol, the captain of his army, and they returned into the land of the Philistines.UjAbraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beersheba, and called there on the name of Yahweh, the Everlasting God.UFAbraham lived as a foreigner in the land of the Philistines many days.t(NUjIt happened after these things, that God tested Abraham, and said to him, "Abraham!" He said, "Here I am."UæHe said, "Now take your son, your only son, whom you love, even Isaac, and go into the land of Moriah. Offer him there for a burnt offering on one of the mountains which I will tell you of."U›Abraham rose early in the morning, and saddled his donk