el answered, "The thing proceeds from Yahweh. We can't speak to you bad or good.UpBehold, Rebekah is before you. Take her, and go, and let her be your master's son's wife, as Yahweh has spoken."UhIt happened that when Abraham's servant heard their words, he bowed himself down to the earth to Yahweh.U£The servant brought forth jewels of silver, and jewels of gold, and clothing, and gave them to Rebekah. He also gave precious things to her brother and her mother.UíThey ate and drank, he and the men who were with him, and stayed all night. They rose up in the morning, and he said, "Send me away to my master."UtHer brother and her mother said, "Let the young lady stay with us a few days, at least ten. After that she will go."UpHe said to them, "Don't hinder me, seeing Yahweh has prospered my way. Send me away that I may go to my master."U6They said, "We will call the young lady, and ask her."UYThey called Rebekah, and said to her, "Will you go with this man?" She said, "I will go."UUThey sent away Rebekah, their sister, with her nurse, Abraham's servant, and his men.U§They blessed Rebekah, and said to her, "Our sister, may you be the mother of thousands of ten thousands, and let your seed possess the gate of those who hate them."UyRebekah arose with her ladies. They rode on the camels, and followed the man. The servant took Rebekah, and went his way.UQIsaac came from the way of Beer Lahai Roi, for he lived in the land of the South.U~Isaac went out to meditate in the field at the evening. He lifted up his eyes, and saw, and, behold, there were camels coming.URRebekah lifted up her eyes, and when she saw Isaac, she dismounted from the camel.UûShe said to the servant, "Who is the man who is walking in the field to meet us?" The servant said, "It is my master." She took her veil, and covered herself.U7The servant told Isaac all the things that he had done.UñIsaac brought her into his mother Sarah's tent, and took Rebekah, and she became his wife. He loved her. Isaac was comforted after his mother's death.t(NU4Abraham took another wife, and her name was Keturah.U?She bore him Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.UfJokshan became the father of Sheba, and Dedan. The sons of Dedan were Asshurim, Letushim, and Leummim.UdThe sons of Midian: Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah. All these were the children of Keturah.U&Abraham gave all that he had to Isaac,Uïbut to the sons of Abraham's concubines, Abraham gave gifts. He sent them away from Isaac his son, while he yet lived, eastward, to the east country.UaThese are the days of the years of Abraham's life which he lived: one hundred seventy-five years.UvAbraham gave up the spirit, and died in a good old age, an old man, and full of years, and was gathered to his people.UéIsaac and Ishmael, his sons, buried him in the cave of Machpelah, in the field of Ephron, the son of Zohar the Hittite, which is before Mamre,Uithe field which Abraham purchased of the children of Heth. Abraham was buried there with Sarah, his wife.UfIt happened after the death of Abraham that God blessed Isaac, his son. Isaac lived by Beer Lahai Roi.UÅNow this is the history of the generations of Ishmael, Abraham's son, whom Hagar the Egyptian, Sarah's handmaid, bore to Abraham.U¢These are the names of the sons of Ishmael, by their names, according to the order of their birth: the firstborn of Ishmael, Nebaioth, then Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,UMishma, Dumah, Massa,U)Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah.UíThese are the sons of Ishmael, and these are their names, by their villages, and by their encampments: twelve princes, according to their nations.UãThese are the years of the life of Ishmael: one hundred thirty-seven years. He gave up the spirit and died, and was gathered to his people.UtThey lived from Havilah to Shur that is before Egypt, as you go toward Assyria. He lived opposite all his relatives.UcThis is the history of the generations of Isaac, Abraham's son. Abraham became the father of Isaac.UíIsaa