ur soul may bless me."UÅIsaac said to his son, "How is it that you have found it so quickly, my son?" He said, "Because Yahweh your God gave me success."UpIsaac said to Jacob, "Please come near, that I may feel you, my son, whether you are really my son Esau or not."U~Jacob went near to Isaac his father. He felt him, and said, "The voice is Jacob's voice, but the hands are the hands of Esau."UiHe didn't recognize him, because his hands were hairy, like his brother, Esau's hands. So he blessed him.U7He said, "Are you really my son Esau?" He said, "I am."U©He said, "Bring it near to me, and I will eat of my son's venison, that my soul may bless you." He brought it near to him, and he ate. He brought him wine, and he drank.UCHis father Isaac said to him, "Come near now, and kiss me, my son."U∞He came near, and kissed him. He smelled the smell of his clothing, and blessed him, and said, "Behold, the smell of my son is as the smell of a field which Yahweh has blessed.UbGod give you of the dew of the sky, of the fatness of the earth, and plenty of grain and new wine.U¿Let peoples serve you, and nations bow down to you. Be lord over your brothers. Let your mother's sons bow down to you. Cursed be everyone who curses you. Blessed be everyone who blesses you."U≥It happened, as soon as Isaac had made an end of blessing Jacob, and Jacob had just gone out from the presence of Isaac his father, that Esau his brother came in from his hunting.U†He also made savory food, and brought it to his father. He said to his father, "Let my father arise, and eat of his son's venison, that your soul may bless me."U\Isaac his father said to him, "Who are you?" He said, "I am your son, your firstborn, Esau."U∏Isaac trembled violently, and said, "Who, then, is he who has taken venison, and brought it me, and I have eaten of all before you came, and have blessed him? Yes, he will be blessed."UñWhen Esau heard the words of his father, he cried with an exceeding great and bitter cry, and said to his father, "Bless me, even me also, my father."UKHe said, "Your brother came with deceit, and has taken away your blessing."U…He said, "Isn't he rightly named Jacob? For he has supplanted me these two times. He took away my birthright. See, now he has taken away my blessing." He said, "Haven't you reserved a blessing for me?"U√Isaac answered Esau, "Behold, I have made him your lord, and all his brothers have I given to him for servants. With grain and new wine have I sustained him. What then will I do for you, my son?"UáEsau said to his father, "Have you but one blessing, my father? Bless me, even me also, my father." Esau lifted up his voice, and wept.UÄIsaac his father answered him, "Behold, of the fatness of the earth will be your dwelling, and of the dew of the sky from above.UõBy your sword will you live, and you will serve your brother. It will happen, when you will break loose, that you shall shake his yoke from off your neck."U∏Esau hated Jacob because of the blessing with which his father blessed him. Esau said in his heart, "The days of mourning for my father are at hand. Then I will kill my brother Jacob."U√The words of Esau, her elder son, were told to Rebekah. She sent and called Jacob, her younger son, and said to him, "Behold, your brother Esau comforts himself about you by planning to kill you.UQNow therefore, my son, obey my voice. Arise, flee to Laban, my brother, in Haran.U?Stay with him a few days, until your brother's fury turns away;U¥until your brother's anger turn away from you, and he forgets what you have done to him. Then I will send, and get you from there. Why should I be bereaved of you both in one day?"UÀRebekah said to Isaac, "I am weary of my life because of the daughters of Heth. If Jacob takes a wife of the daughters of Heth, such as these, of the daughters of the land, what good will my life do me?"t(NUjIsaac called Jacob, blessed him, and commanded him, "You shall not take a wife of the daughters of Canaan.UíArise, go to Paddan Aram, to the house of Bethuel your mother's father. Take a wife from there from the daughters of Laban, your mother's brother.UjMay God Almighty bless you, and make you fruitful, and multiply you, that you may be a company of peoples,Uîand give you the blessing of Abraham, to you, and to your seed with you, that you may inherit the land where you travel, which God gave to Abraham."UÄIsaac sent Jacob away. He went to Paddan Aram to Laban, son of Bethuel the Syrian, Rebekah's brother, Jacob's and Esau's mother.U‹Now Esau saw that Isaac had blessed Jacob and sent him away to Paddan Aram, to take him a wife from there, and that as he blessed him he gave him a command, saying, "You shall not take a wife of the daughters of Canaan,"UMand that Jacob obeyed his father and his mother, and was gone to Paddan Aram.UFEsau saw that the daughters of Canaan didn't please Isaac, his father.UóEsau went to Ishmael, and took, besides the wives that he had, Mahalath the daughter of Ishmael, Abraham's son, the sister of Nebaioth, to be his wife.U5Jacob went out from Beersheba, and went toward Haran.U∏He came to a certain place, and stayed there all night, because the sun had set. He took one of the stones of the place, and put it under his head, and lay down in that place to sleep.UãHe dreamed. Behold, a stairway set upon the earth, and its top reached to heaven. Behold, the angels of God ascending and descending on it.UØBehold, Yahweh stood above it, and said, "I am Yahweh, the God of Abraham your father, and the God of Isaac. The land whereon you lie, to you will I give it, and to your seed.UœYour seed will be as the dust of the earth, and you will spread abroad to the west, and to the east, and to the north, and to the south. In you and in your seed will all the families of the earth be blessed.U¥Behold, I am with you, and will keep you, wherever you go, and will bring you again into this land. For I will not leave you, until I have done that which I have spoken of to you."UeJacob awakened out of his sleep, and he said, "Surely Yahweh is in this place, and I didn't know it."U{He was afraid, and said, "How dreadful is this place! This is none other than God's house, and this is the gate of heaven."UçJacob rose up early in the morning, and took the stone that he had put under his head, and set it up for a pillar, and poured oil on its top.UWHe called the name of that place Bethel, but the name of the city was Luz at the first.UíJacob vowed a vow, saying, "If God will be with me, and will keep me in this way that I go, and will give me bread to eat, and clothing to put on,UNso that I come again to my father's house in peace, and Yahweh will be my God,Uäthen this stone, which I have set up for a pillar, will be God's house. Of all that you will give me I will surely give the tenth to you."t(NUQThen Jacob went on his journey, and came to the land of the children of the east.U∏He looked, and behold, a well in the field, and, behold, three flocks of sheep lying there by it. For out of that well they watered the flocks. The stone on the well's mouth was large.U°There all the flocks were gathered. They rolled the stone from the well's mouth, and watered the sheep, and put the stone again on the well's mouth in its place.UWJacob said to them, "My relatives, where are you from?" They said, "We are from Haran."UQHe said to them, "Do you know Laban, the son of Nahor?" They said, "We know him."UuHe said to them, "Is it well with him?" They said, "It is well. See, Rachel, his daughter, is coming with the sheep."UáHe said, "Behold, it is still the middle of the day, not time to gather the livestock together. Water the sheep, and go and feed them."UäThey said, "We can't, until all the flocks are gathered together, and they roll the stone from the well's mouth. Then we water the sheep."U\While he was yet speaking with them, Rachel came with her father's sheep, for she kept them.UÙIt happened, when Jacob saw Rachel the daughter of Laban, his mother's brother, and t