aid to his father-in-law, "Because the people come to me to inquire of God.UéWhen they have a matter, they come to me, and I judge between a man and his neighbor, and I make them know the statutes of God, and his laws."UEMoses' father-in-law said to him, "The thing that you do is not good.UôYou will surely wear away, both you, and this people that is with you; for the thing is too heavy for you. You are not able to perform it yourself alone.UáListen now to my voice. I will give you counsel, and God be with you. You represent the people before God, and bring the causes to God.UÑYou shall teach them the statutes and the laws, and shall show them the way in which they must walk, and the work that they must do.UﬁMoreover you shall provide out of all the people able men, such as fear God: men of truth, hating unjust gain; and place such over them, to be rulers of thousands, rulers of hundreds, rulers of fifties, and rulers of tens.UﬂLet them judge the people at all times. It shall be that every great matter they shall bring to you, but every small matter they shall judge themselves. So shall it be easier for you, and they shall share the load with you.UìIf you will do this thing, and God commands you so, then you will be able to endure, and all of these people also will go to their place in peace."URSo Moses listened to the voice of his father-in-law, and did all that he had said.UúMoses chose able men out of all Israel, and made them heads over the people, rulers of thousands, rulers of hundreds, rulers of fifties, and rulers of tens.UzThey judged the people at all times. They brought the hard causes to Moses, but every small matter they judged themselves.UJMoses let his father-in-law depart, and he went his way into his own land.t(NUëIn the third month after the children of Israel had gone forth out of the land of Egypt, on that same day they came into the wilderness of Sinai.UûWhen they had departed from Rephidim, and had come to the wilderness of Sinai, they encamped in the wilderness; and there Israel encamped before the mountain.UùMoses went up to God, and Yahweh called to him out of the mountain, saying, "This is what you shall tell the house of Jacob, and tell the children of Israel:Uk'You have seen what I did to the Egyptians, and how I bore you on eagles' wings, and brought you to myself.UùNow therefore, if you will indeed obey my voice, and keep my covenant, then you shall be my own possession from among all peoples; for all the earth is mine;UÜand you shall be to me a kingdom of priests, and a holy nation.' These are the words which you shall speak to the children of Israel."UsMoses came and called for the elders of the people, and set before them all these words which Yahweh commanded him.UÜAll the people answered together, and said, "All that Yahweh has spoken we will do." Moses reported the words of the people to Yahweh.UøYahweh said to Moses, "Behold, I come to you in a thick cloud, that the people may hear when I speak with you, and may also believe you forever." Moses told the words of the people to Yahweh.UpYahweh said to Moses, "Go to the people, and sanctify them today and tomorrow, and let them wash their garments,U}and be ready against the third day; for on the third day Yahweh will come down in the sight of all the people on Mount Sinai.U∫You shall set bounds to the people all around, saying, 'Be careful that you don't go up onto the mountain, or touch its border. Whoever touches the mountain shall be surely put to death.UªNo hand shall touch him, but he shall surely be stoned or shot through; whether it is animal or man, he shall not live.' When the trumpet sounds long, they shall come up to the mountain."UjMoses went down from the mountain to the people, and sanctified the people; and they washed their clothes.U]He said to the people, "Be ready by the third day. Don't have sexual relations with a woman."UﬁIt happened on the third day, when it was morning, that there were thunders and lightnings, and a thick cloud on the mountain, and the sound of an exceedingly loud trumpet; and all the people who were in the camp trembled.UcMoses led the people out of the camp to meet God; and they stood at the lower part of the mountain.UüMount Sinai, all it, smoked, because Yahweh descended on it in fire; and its smoke ascended like the smoke of a furnace, and the whole mountain quaked greatly.UcWhen the sound of the trumpet grew louder and louder, Moses spoke, and God answered him by a voice.UYahweh came down on Mount Sinai, to the top of the mountain. Yahweh called Moses to the top of the mountain, and Moses went up.UtYahweh said to Moses, "Go down, warn the people, lest they break through to Yahweh to gaze, and many of them perish.UeLet the priests also, who come near to Yahweh, sanctify themselves, lest Yahweh break forth on them."UéMoses said to Yahweh, "The people can't come up to Mount Sinai, for you warned us, saying, 'Set bounds around the mountain, and sanctify it.'"UÆYahweh said to him, "Go down and you shall bring Aaron up with you, but don't let the priests and the people break through to come up to Yahweh, lest he break forth on them."U0So Moses went down to the people, and told them.t(NU"God spoke all these words, saying,U]"I am Yahweh your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage.U'You shall have no other gods before me.U≠"You shall not make for yourselves an idol, nor any image of anything that is in the heavens above, or that is in the earth beneath, or that is in the water under the earth:Uÿyou shall not bow yourself down to them, nor serve them, for I, Yahweh your God, am a jealous God, visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children, on the third and on the fourth generation of those who hate me,UWand showing loving kindness to thousands of those who love me and keep my commandments.U{"You shall not take the name of Yahweh your God in vain, for Yahweh will not hold him guiltless who takes his name in vain.U+"Remember the Sabbath day, to keep it holy.U/You shall labor six days, and do all your work,UÁbut the seventh day is a Sabbath to Yahweh your God. You shall not do any work in it, you, nor your son, nor your daughter, your male servant, nor your female servant, nor your livestock, nor your stranger who is within your gates;Ußfor in six days Yahweh made heaven and earth, the sea, and all that is in them, and rested the seventh day; therefore Yahweh blessed the Sabbath day, and made it holy.Uk"Honor your father and your mother, that your days may be long in the land which Yahweh your God gives you.U"You shall not murder.U"You shall not commit adultery.U"You shall not steal.U:"You shall not give false testimony against your neighbor.U∆"You shall not covet your neighbor's house. You shall not covet your neighbor's wife, nor his male servant, nor his female servant, nor his ox, nor his donkey, nor anything that is your neighbor's."UÆAll the people perceived the thunderings, the lightnings, the sound of the trumpet, and the mountain smoking. When the people saw it, they trembled, and stayed at a distance.UoThey said to Moses, "Speak with us yourself, and we will listen; but don't let God speak with us, lest we die."UÉMoses said to the people, "Don't be afraid, for God has come to test you, and that his fear may be before you, that you won't sin."UYThe people stayed at a distance, and Moses drew near to the thick darkness where God was.UçYahweh said to Moses, "This is what you shall tell the children of Israel: 'You yourselves have seen that I have talked with you from heaven.UaYou shall most certainly not make alongside of me gods of silver, or gods of gold for yourselves.U‹You shall make an altar of earth for me, and shall sacrifice on it your burnt offerings and your peace offerings, your sheep and your cattle. In every place where I record my name I will come to you and I will bless you.UÅIf you make me an altar of stone, you shall not build it of cut stones; for if you lift up your tool on it, you have polluted it.U\Neither shall you go up by steps to my altar, that your nakedness may not be exposed to it.'t(NU>"Now these are the ordinances which you shall set before them.Uw"If you buy a Hebrew servant, he shall serve six years and in the seventh he shall go out free without paying anything.UmIf he comes in by himself, he shall go out by himself. If he is married, then his wife shall go out with him.UîIf his master gives him a wife and she bears him sons or daughters, the wife and her children shall be her master's, and he shall go out by himself.UkBut if the servant shall plainly say, 'I love my master, my wife, and my children. I will not go out free;'U≥then his master shall bring him to God, and shall bring him to the door or to the doorpost, and his master shall bore his ear through with an awl, and he shall serve him for ever.Ub"If a man sells his daughter to be a female servant, she shall not go out as the male servants do.U∆If she doesn't please her master, who has married her to himself, then he shall let her be redeemed. He shall have no right to sell her to a foreign people, seeing he has dealt deceitfully with her.USIf he marries her to his son, he shall deal with her after the manner of daughters.UjIf he takes another wife to himself, he shall not diminish her food, her clothing, and her marital rights.UVIf he doesn't do these three things for her, she may go free without paying any money.UD"One who strikes a man so that he dies shall surely be put to death,Uqbut not if it is unintentional, but God allows it to happen: then I will appoint you a place where he shall flee.UyIf a man schemes and comes presumptuously on his neighbor to kill him, you shall take him from my altar, that he may die.UJ"Anyone who attacks his father or his mother shall be surely put to death.Uj"Anyone who kidnaps someone and sells him, or if he is found in his hand, he shall surely be put to death.UI"Anyone who curses his father or his mother shall surely be put to death.Uu"If men quarrel and one strikes the other with a stone, or with his fist, and he doesn't die, but is confined to bed;U»if he rises again and walks around with his staff, then he who struck him shall be cleared: only he shall pay for the loss of his time, and shall provide for his healing until he is thoroughly healed.Un"If a man strikes his servant or his maid with a rod, and he dies under his hand, he shall surely be punished.UdNotwithstanding, if he gets up after a day or two, he shall not be punished, for he is his property.Uª"If men fight and hurt a pregnant woman so that she gives birth prematurely, and yet no harm follows, he shall be surely fined as much as the woman's husband demands and the judges allow.U:But if any harm follows, then you must take life for life,U;eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot,U<burning for burning, wound for wound, and bruise for bruise.Uu"If a man strikes his servant's eye, or his maid's eye, and destroys it, he shall let him go free for his eye's sake.UyIf he strikes out his male servant's tooth, or his female servant's tooth, he shall let him go free for his tooth's sake.Uß"If a bull gores a man or a woman to death, the bull shall surely be stoned, and its flesh shall not be eaten; but the owner of the bull shall not be held responsible.U›But if the bull had a habit of goring in the past, and it has been testified to its owner, and he has not kept it in, but it has killed a man or a woman, the bull shall be stoned, and its owner shall also be put to death.UfIf a ransom is laid on him, then he shall give for the redemption of his life whatever is laid on him.UgWhether it has gored a son or has gored a daughter, according to this judgment it shall be done to him.UäIf the bull gores a male servant or a female servant, thirty shekels of silver shall be given to their master, and the ox shall be stoned.Ui"If a man opens a pit, or if a man digs a pit and doesn't cover it, and a bull or a donkey falls into it,Ulthe owner of the pit shall make it good. He shall give money to its owner, and the dead animal shall be his.Uú"If one man's bull injures another's, so that it dies, then they shall sell the live bull, and divide its price; and they shall also divide the dead animal.U≤Or if it is known that the bull was in the habit of goring in the past, and its owner has not kept it in, he shall surely pay bull for bull, and the dead animal shall be his own.t(NU{"If a man steals an ox or a sheep, and kills it, or sells it; he shall pay five oxen for an ox, and four sheep for a sheep.UoIf the thief is found breaking in, and is struck so that he dies, there shall be no guilt of bloodshed for him.UöIf the sun has risen on him, there shall be guilt of bloodshed for him; he shall make restitution. If he has nothing, then he shall be sold for his theft.UkIf the stolen property is found in his hand alive, whether it is ox, donkey, or sheep, he shall pay double.U”"If a man causes a field or vineyard to be eaten, and lets his animal loose, and it grazes in another man's field, he shall make restitution from the best of his own field, and from the best of his own vineyard.U∞"If fire breaks out, and catches in thorns so that the shocks of grain, or the standing grain, or the field are consumed; he who kindled the fire shall surely make restitution.Uè"If a man delivers to his neighbor money or stuff to keep, and it is stolen out of the man's house; if the thief is found, he shall pay double.UçIf the thief isn't found, then the master of the house shall come near to God, to find out if he hasn't put his hand to his neighbor's goods.T␀␀For every matter of trespass, whether it be for ox, for donkey, for sheep, for clothing, or for any kind of lost thing, about which one says, 'This is mine,' the cause of both parties shall come before God. He whom God condemns shall pay double to his neighbor.Uê"If a man delivers to his neighbor a donkey, an ox, a sheep, or any animal to keep, and it dies or is injured, or driven away, no man seeing it;U®the oath of Yahweh shall be between them both, whether he hasn't put his hand to his neighbor's goods; and its owner shall accept it, and he shall not make restitution.UEBut if it is stolen from him, he shall make restitution to its owner.UcIf it is torn in pieces, let him bring it for evidence. He shall not make good that which was torn.Uà"If a man borrows anything of his neighbor's, and it is injured, or dies, its owner not being with it, he shall surely make restitution.UcIf its owner is with it, he shall not make it good. If it is a leased thing, it came for its lease.UÇ"If a man entices a virgin who isn't pledged to be married, and lies with her, he shall surely pay a dowry for her to be his wife.UgIf her father utterly refuses to give her to him, he shall pay money according to the dowry of virgins.U)"You shall not allow a sorceress to live.U="Whoever has sex with an animal shall surely be put to death.UQ"He who sacrifices to any god, except to Yahweh only, shall be utterly destroyed.Ug"You shall not wrong an alien, neither shall you oppress him, for you were aliens in the land of Egypt.U?"You shall not take advantage of any widow or fatherless child.U^If you take advantage of them at all, and they cry at all to me, I will surely hear their cry;U}and my wrath will grow hot, and I will kill you with the sword; and your wives shall be widows, and your children fatherless.Uä"If you lend money to any of my people with you who is poor, you shall not be to him as a creditor; neither shall you charge him interest.UhIf you take your neighbor's garment as collateral, you shall restore it to him before the sun goes down,U†for that is his only covering, it is his garment for his skin. What would he sleep in? It will happen, when he cries to me, that I will hear, for I am gracious.U?"You shall not blaspheme God, nor curse a ruler of your people.Uá"You shall not delay to offer from your harvest and from the outflow of your presses. "You shall give the firstborn of your sons to me.UìYou shall do likewise with your cattle and with your sheep. Seven days it shall be with its mother, then on the eighth day you shall give it to me.Uà"You shall be holy men to me, therefore you shall not eat any flesh that is torn by animals in the field. You shall cast it to the dogs.t(NUe"You shall not spread a false report. Don't join your hand with the wicked to be a malicious witness.UxYou shall not follow a crowd to do evil; neither shall you testify in court to side with a multitude to pervert justice;U0neither shall you favor a poor man in his cause.Ue"If you meet your enemy's ox or his donkey going astray, you shall surely bring it back to him again.U|If you see the donkey of him who hates you fallen down under his burden, don't leave him, you shall surely help him with it.UB"You shall not deny justice to your poor people in their lawsuits.Ul"Keep far from a false charge, and don't kill the innocent and righteous: for I will not justify the wicked.Uj"You shall take no bribe, for a bribe blinds those who have sight and perverts the words of the righteous.Uq"You shall not oppress an alien, for you know the heart of an alien, seeing you were aliens in the land of Egypt.UI"For six years you shall sow your land, and shall gather in its increase,U„but the seventh year you shall let it rest and lie fallow, that the poor of your people may eat; and what they leave the animal of the field shall eat. In like manner you shall deal with your vineyard and with your olive grove.U≤"Six days you shall do your work, and on the seventh day you shall rest, that your ox and your donkey may have rest, and the son of your handmaid, and the alien may be refreshed.Uã"Be careful to do all things that I have said to you; and don't invoke the name of other gods, neither let them be heard out of your mouth.U4"You shall observe a feast to me three times a year.UÂYou shall observe the feast of unleavened bread. Seven days you shall eat unleavened bread, as I commanded you, at the time appointed in the month Abib (for in it you came out from Egypt), and no one shall appear before me empty.UπAnd the feast of harvest, the first fruits of your labors, which you sow in the field: and the feast of harvest, at the end of the year, when you gather in your labors out of the field.UKThree times in the year all your males shall appear before the Lord Yahweh.Uâ"You shall not offer the blood of my sacrifice with leavened bread, neither shall the fat of my feast remain all night until the morning.UèThe first of the first fruits of your ground you shall bring into the house of Yahweh your God. "You shall not boil a kid in its mother's milk.Us"Behold, I send an angel before you, to keep you by the way, and to bring you into the place which I have prepared.UÇPay attention to him, and listen to his voice. Don't provoke him, for he will not pardon your disobedience, for my name is in him.UéBut if you indeed listen to his voice, and do all that I speak, then I will be an enemy to your enemies, and an adversary to your adversaries.U§For my angel shall go before you, and bring you in to the Amorite, the Hittite, the Perizzite, the Canaanite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite; and I will cut them off.UíYou shall not bow down to their gods, nor serve them, nor follow their practices, but you shall utterly overthrow them and demolish their pillars.U|You shall serve Yahweh your God, and he will bless your bread and your water, and I will take sickness away from your midst.UWNo one will miscarry or be barren in your land. I will fulfill the number of your days.UçI will send my terror before you, and will confuse all the people to whom you come, and I will make all your enemies turn their backs to you.UtI will send the hornet before you, which will drive out the Hivite, the Canaanite, and the Hittite, from before you.UàI will not drive them out from before you in one year, lest the land become desolate, and the animals of the field multiply against you.UfLittle by little I will drive them out from before you, until you have increased and inherit the land.UŸI will set your border from the Red Sea even to the sea of the Philistines, and from the wilderness to the River; for I will deliver the inhabitants of the land into your hand, and you shall drive them out before you.U:You shall make no covenant with them, nor with their gods.UÖThey shall not dwell in your land, lest they make you sin against me, for if you serve their gods, it will surely be a snare to you."t(NUâHe said to Moses, "Come up to Yahweh, you, and Aaron, Nadab, and Abihu, and seventy of the elders of Israel; and worship from a distance.UnMoses alone shall come near to Yahweh, but they shall not come near, neither shall the people go up with him."UπMoses came and told the people all the words of Yahweh, and all the ordinances; and all the people answered with one voice, and said, "All the words which Yahweh has spoken will we do."U°Moses wrote all the words of Yahweh, and rose up early in the morning, and built an altar under the mountain, and twelve pillars for the twelve tribes of Israel.U|He sent young men of the children of Israel, who offered burnt offerings and sacrificed peace offerings of cattle to Yahweh.UcMoses took half of the blood and put it in basins, and half of the blood he sprinkled on the altar.UìHe took the book of the covenant and read it in the hearing of the people, and they said, "All that Yahweh has spoken will we do, and be obedient."U•Moses took the blood, and sprinkled it on the people, and said, "Look, this is the blood of the covenant, which Yahweh has made with you concerning all these words."UMThen Moses, Aaron, Nadab, Abihu, and seventy of the elders of Israel went up.UqThey saw the God of Israel. Under his feet was like a paved work of sapphire stone, like the skies for clearness.U`He didn't lay his hand on the nobles of the children of Israel. They saw God, and ate and drank.UπYahweh said to Moses, "Come up to me on the mountain, and stay here, and I will give you the tables of stone with the law and the commands that I have written, that you may teach them."UNMoses rose up with Joshua, his servant, and Moses went up onto God's Mountain.UõHe said to the elders, "Wait here for us, until we come again to you. Behold, Aaron and Hur are with you. Whoever is involved in a dispute can go to them."UBMoses went up on the mountain, and the cloud covered the mountain.UêThe glory of Yahweh settled on Mount Sinai, and the cloud covered it six days. The seventh day he called to Moses out of the midst of the cloud.UThe appearance of the glory of Yahweh was like devouring fire on the top of the mountain in the eyes of the children of Israel.UÇMoses entered into the midst of the cloud, and went up on the mountain; and Moses was on the mountain forty days and forty nights.t(NUYahweh spoke to Moses, saying,Uå"Speak to the children of Israel, that they take an offering for me. From everyone whose heart makes him willing you shall take my offering.UIThis is the offering which you shall take from them: gold, silver, brass,U/blue, purple, scarlet, fine linen, goats' hair,U1rams' skins dyed red, sea cow hides, acacia wood,UJoil for the light, spices for the anointing oil and for the sweet incense,UHonyx stones, and stones to be set for the ephod and for the breastplate.U:Let them make me a sanctuary, that I may dwell among them.UÑAccording to all that I show you, the pattern of the tabernacle, and the pattern of all of its furniture, even so you shall make it.Uï"They shall make an ark of acacia wood. Its length shall be two and a half cubits, its breadth a cubit and a half, and a cubit and a half its height.UzYou shall overlay it with pure gold. You shall overlay it inside and outside, and you shall make a gold molding around it.UôYou shall cast four rings of gold for it, and put them in its four feet. Two rings shall be on the one side of it, and two rings on the other side of it.U@You shall make poles of acacia wood, and overlay them with gold.UPYou shall put the poles into the rings on the sides of the ark to carry the ark.ULThe poles shall be in the rings of the ark. They shall not be taken from it.U@You shall put the testimony which I shall give you into the ark.UxYou shall make a mercy seat of pure gold. Two and a half cubits shall be its length, and a cubit and a half its breadth.UdYou shall make two cherubim of hammered gold. You shall make them at the two ends of the mercy seat.UéMake one cherub at the one end, and one cherub at the other end. You shall make the cherubim on its two ends of one piece with the mercy seat.U∫The cherubim shall spread out their wings upward, covering the mercy seat with their wings, with their faces toward one another. The faces of the cherubim shall be toward the mercy seat.UpYou shall put the mercy seat on top of the ark, and in the ark you shall put the testimony that I will give you.U¬There I will meet with you, and I will tell you from above the mercy seat, from between the two cherubim which are on the ark of the testimony, all that I command you for the children of Israel.UÜ"You shall make a table of acacia wood. Two cubits shall be its length, and a cubit its breadth, and one and a half cubits its height.UGYou shall overlay it with pure gold, and make a gold molding around it.UfYou shall make a rim of a handbreadth around it. You shall make a golden molding on its rim around it.UjYou shall make four rings of gold for it, and put the rings in the four corners that are on its four feet.UQthe rings shall be close to the rim, for places for the poles to carry the table.UmYou shall make the poles of acacia wood, and overlay them with gold, that the table may be carried with them.U~You shall make its dishes, its spoons, its ladles, and its bowls to pour out offerings with. You shall make them of pure gold.UBYou shall set bread of the presence on the table before me always.Uµ"You shall make a lampstand of pure gold. Of hammered work shall the lampstand be made, even its base, its shaft, its cups, its buds, and its flowers, shall be of one piece with it.U£There shall be six branches going out of its sides: three branches of the lampstand out of its one side, and three branches of the lampstand out of its other side;UÕthree cups made like almond blossoms in one branch, a bud and a flower; and three cups made like almond blossoms in the other branch, a bud and a flower, so for the six branches going out of the lampstand;USand in the lampstand four cups made like almond blossoms, its buds and its flowers;U…and a bud under two branches of one piece with it, and a bud under two branches of one piece with it, and a bud under two branches of one piece with it, for the six branches going out of the lampstand.UdTheir buds and their branches shall be of one piece with it, all of it one beaten work of pure gold.UiYou shall make its lamps seven, and they shall light its lamps to give light to the space in front of it.U8Its snuffers and its snuff dishes shall be of pure gold.UFIt shall be made of a talent of pure gold, with all these accessories.UXSee that you make them after their pattern, which has been shown to you on the mountain.t(NU∏"Moreover you shall make the tabernacle with ten curtains; of fine twined linen, and blue, and purple, and scarlet, with cherubim. The work of the skillful workman you shall make them.UéThe length of each curtain shall be twenty-eight cubits, and the breadth of each curtain four cubits: all the curtains shall have one measure.UtFive curtains shall be coupled together one to another; and the other five curtains shall be coupled one to another.UπYou shall make loops of blue on the edge of the one curtain from the edge in the coupling; and likewise you shall make in the edge of the curtain that is outmost in the second coupling.U¥You shall make fifty loops in the one curtain, and you shall make fifty loops in the edge of