e ambush arose quickly out of their place, and they ran as soon as he had stretched out his hand, and entered into the city, and took it. They hurried and set the city on fire.U‡When the men of Ai looked behind them, they saw, and behold, the smoke of the city ascended up to heaven, and they had no power to flee this way or that way. The people who fled to the wilderness turned back on the pursuers.UùWhen Joshua and all Israel saw that the ambush had taken the city, and that the smoke of the city ascended, then they turned again, and killed the men of Ai.UæThe others came out of the city against them, so they were in the midst of Israel, some on this side, and some on that side. They struck them, so that they let none of them remain or escape.U>They captured the king of Ai alive, and brought him to Joshua.T␀␀It happened, when Israel had made an end of killing all the inhabitants of Ai in the field, in the wilderness in which they pursued them, and they had all fallen by the edge of the sword, until they were consumed, that all Israel returned to Ai, and struck it with the edge of the sword.U\All that fell that day, both of men and women, were twelve thousand, even all the men of Ai.UàFor Joshua didn't draw back his hand, with which he stretched out the javelin, until he had utterly destroyed all the inhabitants of Ai.UåOnly the livestock and the spoil of that city Israel took for prey to themselves, according to the word of Yahweh which he commanded Joshua.UOSo Joshua burnt Ai, and made it a heap forever, even a desolation, to this day.U˝He hanged the king of Ai on a tree until the evening, and at the sundown Joshua commanded, and they took his body down from the tree, and threw it at the entrance of the gate of the city, and raised a great heap of stones on it that remains to this day.UGThen Joshua built an altar to Yahweh, the God of Israel, in Mount Ebal,T␀␀as Moses the servant of Yahweh commanded the children of Israel, as it is written in the book of the law of Moses, an altar of uncut stones, on which no man had lifted up any iron. They offered burnt offerings on it to Yahweh, and sacrificed peace offerings.UrHe wrote there on the stones a copy of the law of Moses, which he wrote in the presence of the children of Israel.Tì␀␀All Israel, and their elders and officers, and their judges, stood on this side of the ark and on that side before the priests the Levites, who carried the ark of Yahweh's covenant, the foreigner as well as the native; half of them in front of Mount Gerizim, and half of them in front of Mount Ebal, as Moses the servant of Yahweh had commanded at the first, that they should bless the people of Israel.UÄAfterward he read all the words of the law, the blessing and the curse, according to all that is written in the book of the law.U∂There was not a word of all that Moses commanded, which Joshua didn't read before all the assembly of Israel, with the women, the little ones, and the foreigners who were among them.t(NT␀␀It happened, when all the kings who were beyond the Jordan, in the hill country, and in the lowland, and on all the shore of the great sea in front of Lebanon, the Hittite, the Amorite, the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite, heard of itU]that they gathered themselves together to fight with Joshua and with Israel, with one accord.USBut when the inhabitants of Gibeon heard what Joshua had done to Jericho and to Ai,Uüthey also resorted to a ruse, and went and made as if they had been ambassadors, and took old sacks on their donkeys, and wineskins, old and torn and bound up,Usand old and patched shoes on their feet, and wore old garments. All the bread of their provision was dry and moldy.UüThey went to Joshua to the camp at Gilgal, and said to him, and to the men of Israel, "We have come from a far country. Now therefore make a covenant with us."UjThe men of Israel said to the Hivites, "What if you live among us. How could we make a covenant with you?"UhThey said to 