l be, if he call you, that you shall say, Speak, Yahweh; for your servant hears. So Samuel went and lay down in his place.UvYahweh came, and stood, and called as at other times, Samuel, Samuel. Then Samuel said, Speak; for your servant hears.UyYahweh said to Samuel, Behold, I will do a thing in Israel, at which both the ears of everyone who hears it shall tingle.UwIn that day I will perform against Eli all that I have spoken concerning his house, from the beginning even to the end.UßFor I have told him that I will judge his house forever, for the iniquity which he knew, because his sons did bring a curse on themselves, and he didn't restrain them.UáTherefore I have sworn to the house of Eli, that the iniquity of Eli's house shall not be expiated with sacrifice nor offering forever.UpSamuel lay until the morning, and opened the doors of the house of Yahweh. Samuel feared to show Eli the vision.UEThen Eli called Samuel, and said, Samuel, my son. He said, Here am I.U¡He said, "What is the thing that [Yahweh] has spoken to you? Please don't hide it from me. God do so to you, and more also, if you hide anything from me of all the things that he spoke to you."UlSamuel told him every whit, and hid nothing from him. He said, It is Yahweh: let him do what seems him good.UWSamuel grew, and Yahweh was with him, and did let none of his words fall to the ground.UaAll Israel from Dan even to Beersheba knew that Samuel was established to be a prophet of Yahweh.UgYahweh appeared again in Shiloh; for Yahweh revealed himself to Samuel in Shiloh by the word of Yahweh.t(NU¢The word of Samuel came to all Israel. Now Israel went out against the Philistines to battle, and encamped beside Ebenezer: and the Philistines encamped in Aphek.U¿The Philistines put themselves in array against Israel: and when they joined battle, Israel was struck before the Philistines; and they killed of the army in the field about four thousand men.T␀␀When the people were come into the camp, the elders of Israel said, Why has Yahweh struck us today before the Philistines? Let us get the ark of the covenant of Yahweh out of Shiloh to us, that it may come among us, and save us out of the hand of our enemies.U„So the people sent to Shiloh; and they brought from there the ark of the covenant of Yahweh of Armies, who sits [above] the cherubim: and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, were there with the ark of the covenant of God.UWhen the ark of the covenant of Yahweh came into the camp, all Israel shouted with a great shout, so that the earth rang again.U¡When the Philistines heard the noise of the shout, they said, What means the noise of this great shout in the camp of the Hebrews? They understood that the ark of Yahweh was come into the camp.UåThe Philistines were afraid, for they said, God is come into the camp. They said, Woe to us! for there has not been such a thing heretofore.U†Woe to us! who shall deliver us out of the hand of these mighty gods? these are the gods that struck the Egyptians with all manner of plagues in the wilderness.U•Be strong, and behave yourselves like men, O you Philistines, that you not be servants to the Hebrews, as they have been to you: quit yourselves like men, and fight.U´The Philistines fought, and Israel was struck, and they fled every man to his tent: and there was a very great slaughter; for there fell of Israel thirty thousand footmen.USThe ark of God was taken; and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, were slain.UÄThere ran a man of Benjamin out of the army, and came to Shiloh the same day, with his clothes torn, and with earth on his head.U∏When he came, behold, Eli was sitting on his seat by the road watching; for his heart trembled for the ark of God. When the man came into the city, and told it, all the city cried out.U}When Eli heard the noise of the crying, he said, What means the noise of this tumult? The man hurried, and came and told Eli.UTNow Eli was ninety-eight years old; and his eyes were set, so that he could not see.U~The man said to Eli, I am he who came out of the army, and I fled today out of the army. He said, How went the matter, my son?UÿHe who brought the news answered, Israel is fled before the Philistines, and there has been also a great slaughter among the people, and your two sons also, Hophni and Phinehas, are dead, and the ark of God is taken.U›It happened, when he made mention of the ark of God, that [Eli] fell from off his seat backward by the side of the gate; and his neck broke, and he died: for he was an old man, and heavy. He had judged Israel forty years.U˚His daughter-in-law, Phinehas' wife, was with child, near to be delivered: and when she heard the news that the ark of God was taken, and that her father-in-law and her husband were dead, she bowed herself and brought forth; for her pains came on her.U®About the time of her death the women who stood by her said to her, Don't be afraid; for you have brought forth a son. But she didn't answer, neither did she regard it.UõShe named the child Ichabod, saying, The glory is departed from Israel; because the ark of God was taken, and because of her father-in-law and her husband.UIShe said, The glory is departed from Israel; for the ark of God is taken.t(NUZNow the Philistines had taken the ark of God, and they brought it from Ebenezer to Ashdod.UaThe Philistines took the ark of God, and brought it into the house of Dagon, and set it by Dagon.UÆWhen they of Ashdod arose early on the next day, behold, Dagon was fallen on his face to the ground before the ark of Yahweh. They took Dagon, and set him in his place again.U¸When they arose early on the next day morning, behold, Dagon was fallen on his face to the ground before the ark of Yahweh; and the head of Dagon and both the palms of his hands [lay] cut off on the threshold; only [the stump of] Dagon was left to him.UÑTherefore neither the priests of Dagon, nor any who come into Dagon's house, tread on the threshold of Dagon in Ashdod, to this day.UÑBut t