 of Samaria, and in the rest [of the country] beyond the River, and so forth.U{This is the copy of the letter that they sent to Artaxerxes the king: Your servants the men beyond the River, and so forth.U∆Be it known to the king, that the Jews who came up from you are come to us to Jerusalem; they are building the rebellious and the bad city, and have finished the walls, and repaired the foundations.U´Be it known now to the king that if this city is built, and the walls finished, they will not pay tribute, custom, or toll, and in the end it will be hurtful to the kings.UïNow because we eat the salt of the palace, and it is not appropriate for us to see the king's dishonor, therefore have we sent and informed the king;T,␀␀that search may be made in the book of the records of your fathers: so you shall find in the book of the records, and know that this city is a rebellious city, and hurtful to kings and provinces, and that they have moved sedition within the same of old time; for which cause was this city laid waste.UÅWe inform the king that, if this city be built, and the walls finished, by this means you shall have no portion beyond the River.U’[Then] sent the king an answer to Rehum the chancellor, and to Shimshai the scribe, and to the rest of their companions who dwell in Samaria, and in the rest [of the country] beyond the River: Peace, and so forth.U@The letter which you sent to us has been plainly read before me.U¨I decreed, and search has been made, and it is found that this city of old time has made insurrection against kings, and that rebellion and sedition have been made therein.UöThere have been mighty kings also over Jerusalem, who have ruled over all [the country] beyond the River; and tribute, custom, and toll, was paid to them.UwMake you now a decree to cause these men to cease, and that this city not be built, until a decree shall be made by me.UXTake heed that you not be slack herein: why should damage grow to the hurt of the kings?UÀThen when the 