uldn't discern its appearance. A form was before my eyes. Silence, then I heard a voice, saying,UQ'Shall mortal man be more just than God? Shall a man be more pure than his Maker?UKBehold, he puts no trust in his servants. He charges his angels with error.UsHow much more, those who dwell in houses of clay, whose foundation is in the dust, who are crushed before the moth!U]Between morning and evening they are destroyed. They perish forever without any regarding it.UQIsn't their tent cord plucked up within them? They die, and that without wisdom.'t(NUU"Call now; is there any who will answer you? To which of the holy ones will you turn?UDFor resentment kills the foolish man, and jealousy kills the simple.UJI have seen the foolish taking root, but suddenly I cursed his habitation.UeHis children are far from safety. They are crushed in the gate. Neither is there any to deliver them,Ujwhose harvest the hungry eats up, and take it even out of the thorns. The snare gapes for their substance.U_For affliction doesn't come forth from the dust, neither does trouble spring out of the ground;U5but man is born to trouble, as the sparks fly upward.UA"But as for me, I would seek God. I would commit my cause to God,UNwho does great things that can't be fathomed, marvelous things without number;U<who gives rain on the earth, and sends waters on the fields;UTso that he sets up on high those who are low, those who mourn are exalted to safety.U\He frustrates the devices of the crafty, So that their hands can't perform their enterprise.UZHe takes the wise in their own craftiness; the counsel of the cunning is carried headlong.UNThey meet with darkness in the day time, and grope at noonday as in the night.UWBut he saves from the sword of their mouth, even the needy from the hand of the mighty.U4So the poor has hope, and injustice shuts her mouth.Ue"Behold, happy is the man whom God corrects. Therefore do not despise the chastening of the Almighty.UBFor he wounds, and binds up. He injures, 