ood to you that you should oppress, that you should despise the work of your hands, and smile on the counsel of the wicked?U5Do you have eyes of flesh? Or do you see as man sees?UCAre your days as the days of mortals, or your years as man's years,U<that you inquire after my iniquity, and search after my sin?UYAlthough you know that I am not wicked, there is no one who can deliver out of your hand.UL"'Your hands have framed me and fashioned me altogether, yet you destroy me.U[Remember, I beg you, that you have fashioned me as clay. Will you bring me into dust again?U@Haven't you poured me out like milk, and curdled me like cheese?UTYou have clothed me with skin and flesh, and knit me together with bones and sinews.UVYou have granted me life and loving kindness. Your visitation has preserved my spirit.UEYet you hid these things in your heart. I know that this is with you:UDif I sin, then you mark me. You will not acquit me from my iniquity.UåIf I am wicked, woe to me. If I am righteous, I still shall not lift up my head, being filled with disgrace, and conscious of my affliction.UYIf my head is held high, you hunt me like a lion. Again you show yourself powerful to me.UjYou renew your witnesses against me, and increase your indignation on me. Changes and warfare are with me.Uq"'Why, then, have you brought me forth out of the womb? I wish I had given up the spirit, and no eye had seen me.UcI should have been as though I had not been. I should have been carried from the womb to the grave.UQAren't my days few? Cease then. Leave me alone, that I may find a little comfort,U^before I go where I shall not return from, to the land of darkness and of the shadow of death;Ugthe land dark as midnight, of the shadow of death, without any order, where the light is as midnight.'"t(NU&Then Zophar, the Naamathite, answered,UV"Shouldn't the multitude of words be answered? Should a man full of talk be justified?U^Should your boastings make men hold their peace? When you mock, shall no m