n the wilderness, and grieved him in the desert!UGThey turned again and tempted God, and provoked the Holy One of Israel.UTThey didn't remember his hand, nor the day when he redeemed them from the adversary;U@how he set his signs in Egypt, his wonders in the field of Zoan,UShe turned their rivers into blood, and their streams, so that they could not drink.UYHe sent among them swarms of flies, which devoured them; and frogs, which destroyed them.UNHe gave also their increase to the caterpillar, and their labor to the locust.UHHe destroyed their vines with hail, their sycamore fig trees with frost.UTHe gave over their livestock also to the hail, and their flocks to hot thunderbolts.UlHe threw on them the fierceness of his anger, wrath, indignation, and trouble, and a band of angels of evil.UpHe made a path for his anger. He didn't spare their soul from death, but gave their life over to the pestilence,UWand struck all the firstborn in Egypt, the chief of their strength in the tents of Ham.U[But he led forth his own people like sheep, and guided them in the wilderness like a flock.UWHe led them safely, so that they weren't afraid, but the sea overwhelmed their enemies.UaHe brought them to the border of his sanctuary, to this mountain, which his right hand had taken.UãHe also drove out the nations before them, allotted them for an inheritance by line, and made the tribes of Israel to dwell in their tents.UYYet they tempted and rebelled against the Most High God, and didn't keep his testimonies;Uibut turned back, and dealt treacherously like their fathers. They were turned aside like a deceitful bow.UlFor they provoked him to anger with their high places, and moved him to jealousy with their engraved images.U?When God heard this, he was angry, and greatly abhorred Israel;UJSo that he forsook the tent of Shiloh, the tent which he placed among men;UOand delivered his strength into captivity, his glory into the adversary's hand.UNHe also gave his people over to the sword, a