yself gardens and parks, and I planted trees in them of all kinds of fruit.URI made myself pools of water, to water from it the forest where trees were reared.U´I bought male servants and female servants, and had servants born in my house. I also had great possessions of herds and flocks, above all who were before me in Jerusalem;U“I also gathered silver and gold for myself, and the treasure of kings and of the provinces. I got myself male and female singers, and the delights of the sons of men--musical instruments, and that of all sorts.UmSo I was great, and increased more than all who were before me in Jerusalem. My wisdom also remained with me.UµWhatever my eyes desired, I didn't keep from them. I didn't withhold my heart from any joy, for my heart rejoiced because of all my labor, and this was my portion from all my labor.UøThen I looked at all the works that my hands had worked, and at the labor that I had labored to do; and behold, all was vanity and a chasing after wind, and there was no profit under the sun.UÖI turned myself to consider wisdom, madness, and folly: for what can the king's successor do? Just that which has been done long ago.UEThen I saw that wisdom excels folly, as far as light excels darkness.U|The wise man's eyes are in his head, and the fool walks in darkness--and yet I perceived that one event happens to them all.U£Then said I in my heart, "As it happens to the fool, so will it happen even to me; and why was I then more wise?" Then said I in my heart that this also is vanity.UªFor of the wise man, even as of the fool, there is no memory for ever, seeing that in the days to come all will have been long forgotten. Indeed, the wise man must die just like the fool!U~So I hated life, because the work that is worked under the sun was grievous to me; for all is vanity and a chasing after wind.UqI hated all my labor in which I labored under the sun, seeing that I must leave it to the man who comes after me.U¿Who knows whether he will be a wise ma