thing beautiful in its time. He has also set eternity in their hearts, yet so that man can't find out the work that God has done from the beginning even to the end.UbI know that there is nothing better for them than to rejoice, and to do good as long as they live.U^Also that every man should eat and drink, and enjoy good in all his labor, is the gift of God.U°I know that whatever God does, it shall be forever. Nothing can be added to it, nor anything taken from it; and God has done it, that men should fear before him.UzThat which is has been long ago, and that which is to be has been long ago: and God seeks again that which is passed away.UèMoreover I saw under the sun, in the place of justice, that wickedness was there; and in the place of righteousness, that wickedness was there.UÇI said in my heart, "God will judge the righteous and the wicked; for there is a time there for every purpose and for every work."UxI said in my heart, "As for the sons of men, God tests them, so that they may see that they themselves are like animals.UﬁFor that which happens to the sons of men happens to animals. Even one thing happens to them. As the one dies, so the other dies. Yes, they have all one breath; and man has no advantage over the animals: for all is vanity.UGAll go to one place. All are from the dust, and all turn to dust again.UzWho knows the spirit of man, whether it goes upward, and the spirit of the animal, whether it goes downward to the earth?"U®Therefore I saw that there is nothing better, than that a man should rejoice in his works; for that is his portion: for who can bring him to see what will be after him?t(NUÊThen I returned and saw all the oppressions that are done under the sun: and behold, the tears of those who were oppressed, and they had no comforter; and on the side of their oppressors there was power; but they had no comforter.U\Therefore I praised the dead who have been long dead more than the living who are yet alive.UrYes, better than them both is him who has not yet been, who has not seen the evil work that is done under the sun.U}Then I saw all the labor and achievement that is the envy of a man's neighbor. This also is vanity and a striving after wind.U4The fool folds his hands together and ruins himself.UYBetter is a handful, with quietness, than two handfuls with labor and chasing after wind.U-Then I returned and saw vanity under the sun.T␀␀There is one who is alone, and he has neither son nor brother. There is no end to all of his labor, neither are his eyes satisfied with wealth. For whom then, do I labor, and deprive my soul of enjoyment? This also is vanity, yes, it is a miserable business.UITwo are better than one, because they have a good reward for their labor.UÜFor if they fall, the one will lift up his fellow; but woe to him who is alone when he falls, and doesn't have another to lift him up.USAgain, if two lie together, then they have warmth; but how can one keep warm alone?UpIf a man prevails against one who is alone, two shall withstand him; and a threefold cord is not quickly broken.UqBetter is a poor and wise youth than an old and foolish king who doesn't know how to receive admonition any more.UVFor out of prison he came forth to be king; yes, even in his kingdom he was born poor.UiI saw all the living who walk under the sun, that they were with the youth, the other, who succeeded him.UÆThere was no end of all the people, even of all them over whom he was--yet those who come after shall not rejoice in him. Surely this also is vanity and a chasing after wind.t(NUùGuard your steps when you go to God's house; for to draw near to listen is better than to give the sacrifice of fools, for they don't know that they do evil.UßDon't be rash with your mouth, and don't let your heart be hasty to utter anything before God; for God is in heaven, and you on earth. Therefore let your words be few.U]For as a dream comes with a multitude of cares, so a fool's speech with a multitude of words.UjWhen you vow