ursed others.USAll this have I proved in wisdom. I said, "I will be wise;" but it was far from me.UDThat which is, is far off and exceedingly deep. Who can find it out?U∑I turned around, and my heart sought to know and to search out, and to seek wisdom and the scheme of things, and to know that wickedness is stupidity, and that foolishness is madness.U≥I find more bitter than death the woman whose heart is snares and traps, whose hands are chains. Whoever pleases God shall escape from her; but the sinner will be ensnared by her.UUBehold, this have I found, says the Preacher, one to another, to find out the scheme;UÖwhich my soul still seeks; but I have not found: one man among a thousand have I found; but a woman among all those have I not found.U\Behold, this only have I found: that God made man upright; but they search for many schemes.t(NUîWho is like the wise man? And who knows the interpretation of a thing? A man's wisdom makes his face shine, and the hardness of his face is changed.U=I say, "Keep the king's command!" because of the oath to God.UkDon't be hasty to go out of his presence. Don't persist in an evil thing, for he does whatever pleases him,UIfor the king's word is supreme. Who can say to him, "What are you doing?"UjWhoever keeps the commandment shall not come to harm, and his wise heart will know the time and procedure.U`For there is a time and procedure for every purpose, although the misery of man is heavy on him.ULFor he doesn't know that which will be; for who can tell him how it will be?UÃThere is no man who has power over the spirit to contain the spirit; neither does he have power over the day of death. There is no discharge in war; neither shall wickedness deliver those who practice it.UòAll this have I seen, and applied my mind to every work that is done under the sun. There is a time in which one man has power over another to his hurt.UìSo I saw the wicked buried. Indeed they came also from holiness. They went and were forgotten in the cit