gypt will fail in its midst. I will destroy its counsel. They will seek the idols, the charmers, those who have familiar spirits, and the wizards.UÇI will give over the Egyptians into the hand of a cruel lord. A fierce king will rule over them," says the Lord, Yahweh of Armies.UOThe waters will fail from the sea, and the river will be wasted and become dry.UxThe rivers will become foul. The streams of Egypt will be diminished and dried up. The reeds and flags will wither away.UàThe meadows by the Nile, by the brink of the Nile, and all the sown fields of the Nile, will become dry, be driven away, and be no more.UÄThe fishermen will lament, and all those who fish in the Nile will mourn, and those who spread nets on the waters will languish.U\Moreover those who work in combed flax, and those who weave white cloth, will be confounded.UZThe pillars will be broken in pieces. All those who work for hire will be grieved in soul.UºThe princes of Zoan are utterly foolish. The counsel of the wisest counselors of Pharaoh has become stupid. How do you say to Pharaoh, "I am the son of the wise, the son of ancient kings?"U{Where then are your wise men? Let them tell you now; and let them know what Yahweh of Armies has purposed concerning Egypt.UóThe princes of Zoan have become fools. The princes of Memphis are deceived. They have caused Egypt to go astray, who are the cornerstone of her tribes.U•Yahweh has mixed a spirit of perverseness in the midst of her; and they have caused Egypt to go astray in all of its works, like a drunken man staggers in his vomit.U[Neither shall there be for Egypt any work, which head or tail, palm branch or rush, may do.UõIn that day the Egyptians will be like women. They will tremble and fear because of the shaking of the hand of Yahweh of Armies, which he shakes over them.U±The land of Judah will become a terror to Egypt. Everyone to whom mention is made of it will be afraid, because of the plans of Yahweh of Armies, which he determines against it.U´In that day, there will be five cities in the land of Egypt that speak the language of Canaan, and swear to Yahweh of Armies. One will be called "The city of destruction."UvIn that day, there will be an altar to Yahweh in the midst of the land of Egypt, and a pillar to Yahweh at its border.UÕIt will be for a sign and for a witness to Yahweh of Armies in the land of Egypt; for they will cry to Yahweh because of oppressors, and he will send them a savior and a defender, and he will deliver them.UµYahweh will be known to Egypt, and the Egyptians will know Yahweh in that day. Yes, they will worship with sacrifice and offering, and will vow a vow to Yahweh, and will perform it.UÅYahweh will strike Egypt, striking and healing. They will return to Yahweh, and he will be entreated by them, and will heal them.U∂In that day there will be a highway out of Egypt to Assyria, and the Assyrian shall come into Egypt, and the Egyptian into Assyria; and the Egyptians will worship with the Assyrians.UhIn that day, Israel will be the third with Egypt and with Assyria, a blessing in the midst of the earth;Uâbecause Yahweh of Armies has blessed them, saying, "Blessed be Egypt my people, Assyria the work of my hands, and Israel my inheritance."t(NU{In the year that Tartan came to Ashdod, when Sargon the king of Assyria sent him, and he fought against Ashdod and took it;Uøat that time Yahweh spoke by Isaiah the son of Amoz, saying, "Go, and loosen the sackcloth from off your waist, and take your shoes from off your feet." He did so, walking naked and barefoot.UéYahweh said, "As my servant Isaiah has walked naked and barefoot three years for a sign and a wonder concerning Egypt and concerning Ethiopia,UÆso the king of Assyria will lead away the captives of Egypt and the exiles of Ethiopia, young and old, naked and barefoot, and with buttocks uncovered, to the shame of Egypt.UfThey will be dismayed and confounded, because of Ethiopia their expectation, and of Egypt their glory.UπThe inhabitants of this coast land will say in that day, 'Behold, this is our expectation, where we fled for help to be delivered from the king of Assyria. And we, how will we escape?'"t(NUÜThe burden of the wilderness of the sea. As whirlwinds in the South sweep through, it comes from the wilderness, from an awesome land.U•A grievous vision is declared to me. The treacherous man deals treacherously, and the destroyer destroys. Go up, Elam; attack! I have stopped all of Media's sighing.U∏Therefore my thighs are filled with anguish. Pains have taken hold on me, like the pains of a woman in labor. I am in so much pain that I can't hear. I so am dismayed that I can't see.UoMy heart flutters. Horror has frightened me. The twilight that I desired has been turned into trembling for me.UgThey prepare the table. They set the watch. They eat. They drink. Rise up, you princes, oil the shield!UKFor the Lord said to me, "Go, set a watchman. Let him declare what he sees.UÖWhen he sees a troop, horsemen in pairs, a troop of donkeys, a troop of camels, he shall listen diligently with great attentiveness."UuHe cried like a lion: "Lord, I stand continually on the watchtower in the daytime, and every night I stay at my post.U°Behold, here comes a troop of men, horsemen in pairs." He answered, "Fallen, fallen is Babylon; and all the engraved images of her gods are broken to the ground.UãYou are my threshing, and the grain of my floor!" That which I have heard from Yahweh of Armies, the God of Israel, I have declared to you.UmThe burden of Dumah. One calls to me out of Seir, "Watchman, what of the night? Watchman, what of the night?"UjThe watchman said, "The morning comes, and also the night. If you will inquire, inquire. Come back again."UXThe burden on Arabia. In the forest in Arabia you will lodge, you caravans of Dedanites.UrThey brought water to him who was thirsty. The inhabitants of the land of Tema met the fugitives with their bread.UiFor they fled away from the swords, from the drawn sword, from the bent bow, and from the heat of battle.UxFor the Lord said to me, "Within a year, as a worker bound by contract would count it, all the glory of Kedar will fail,Uíand the residue of the number of the archers, the mighty men of the children of Kedar, will be few; for Yahweh, the God of Israel, has spoken it."t(NUbThe burden of the valley of vision. What ails you now, that you have all gone up to the housetops?UäYou that are full of shouting, a tumultuous city, a joyous town; your slain are not slain with the sword, neither are they dead in battle.UÜAll your rulers fled away together. They were bound by the archers. All who were found by you were bound together. They fled far away.UáTherefore I said, "Look away from me. I will weep bitterly. Don't labor to comfort me for the destruction of the daughter of my people.UæFor it is a day of confusion, and of treading down, and of perplexity, from the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, in the valley of vision; a breaking down of the walls, and a crying to the mountains."UYElam carried his quiver, with chariots of men and horsemen; and Kir uncovered the shield.UsIt happened that your choicest valleys were full of chariots, and the horsemen set themselves in array at the gate.UgHe took away the covering of Judah; and you looked in that day to the armor in the house of the forest.UwYou saw the breaches of the city of David, that they were many; and you gathered together the waters of the lower pool.UXYou numbered the houses of Jerusalem, and you broke down the houses to fortify the wall.UªYou also made a reservoir between the two walls for the water of the old pool. But you didn't look to him who had done this, neither did you have respect for him who purposed it long ago.U{In that day, the Lord, Yahweh of Armies, called to weeping, and to mourning, and to baldness, and to dressing in sackcloth:Uëand behold, joy and gladness, killing cattle and killing sheep, eating flesh and drinking wine: "Let us eat and drink, for tomorrow