orgiven him, neither in this age, nor in that which is to come.UÑ"Either make the tree good, and its fruit good, or make the tree corrupt, and its fruit corrupt; for the tree is known by its fruit.U}You offspring of vipers, how can you, being evil, speak good things? For out of the abundance of the heart, the mouth speaks.UThe good man out of his good treasure brings out good things, and the evil man out of his evil treasure brings out evil things.UdI tell you that every idle word that men speak, they will give account of it in the day of judgment.URFor by your words you will be justified, and by your words you will be condemned."U^Then certain of the scribes and Pharisees answered, "Teacher, we want to see a sign from you."UåBut he answered them, "An evil and adulterous generation seeks after a sign, but no sign will be given it but the sign of Jonah the prophet.UòFor as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of the whale, so will the Son of Man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth.U∏The men of Nineveh will stand up in the judgment with this generation, and will condemn it, for they repented at the preaching of Jonah; and behold, someone greater than Jonah is here.U◊The queen of the south will rise up in the judgment with this generation, and will condemn it, for she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon; and behold, someone greater than Solomon is here.U{But the unclean spirit, when he is gone out of the man, passes through waterless places, seeking rest, and doesn't find it.UâThen he says, 'I will return into my house from which I came out,' and when he has come back, he finds it empty, swept, and put in order.U‹Then he goes, and takes with himself seven other spirits more evil than he is, and they enter in and dwell there. The last state of that man becomes worse than the first. Even so will it be also to this evil generation."UxWhile he was yet speaking to the multitudes, behold, his mother and his brothers stood outside, seeking to speak to him.U`One said to him, "Behold, your mother and your brothers stand outside, seeking to speak to you."UNBut he answered him who spoke to him, "Who is my mother? Who are my brothers?"U^He stretched out his hand towards his disciples, and said, "Behold, my mother and my brothers!UcFor whoever does the will of my Father who is in heaven, he is my brother, and sister, and mother."t(NU@On that day Jesus went out of the house, and sat by the seaside.UtGreat multitudes gathered to him, so that he entered into a boat, and sat, and all the multitude stood on the beach.UTHe spoke to them many things in parables, saying, "Behold, a farmer went out to sow.USAs he sowed, some seeds fell by the roadside, and the birds came and devoured them.UÇOthers fell on rocky ground, where they didn't have much soil, and immediately they sprang up, because they had no depth of earth.UYWhen the sun had risen, they were scorched. Because they had no root, they withered away.U=Others fell among thorns. The thorns grew up and choked them.UiOthers fell on good soil, and yielded fruit: some one hundred times as much, some sixty, and some thirty.U'He who has ears to hear, let him hear."ULThe disciples came, and said to him, "Why do you speak to them in parables?"UrHe answered them, "To you it is given to know the mysteries of the Kingdom of Heaven, but it is not given to them.UêFor whoever has, to him will be given, and he will have abundance, but whoever doesn't have, from him will be taken away even that which he has.UTherefore I speak to them in parables, because seeing they don't see, and hearing, they don't hear, neither do they understand.U•In them the prophecy of Isaiah is fulfilled, which says,  'By hearing you will hear, and will in no way understand; Seeing you will see, and will in no way perceive:U˛for this people's heart has grown callous, their ears are dull of hearing, they have closed their eyes; or else perhaps they might perceive with their ey