ich he was laying on, and departed to his house, glorifying God.U|Amazement took hold on all, and they glorified God. They were filled with fear, saying, "We have seen strange things today."U{After these things he went out, and saw a tax collector named Levi sitting at the tax office, and said to him, "Follow me!"U1He left everything, and rose up and followed him.UÄLevi made a great feast for him in his house. There was a great crowd of tax collectors and others who were reclining with them.UáTheir scribes and the Pharisees murmured against his disciples, saying, "Why do you eat and drink with the tax collectors and sinners?"UdJesus answered them, "Those who are healthy have no need for a physician, but those who are sick do.UBI have not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance."UáThey said to him, "Why do John's disciples often fast and pray, likewise also the disciples of the Pharisees, but yours eat and drink?"UeHe said to them, "Can you make the friends of the bridegroom fast, while the bridegroom is with them?UlBut the days will come when the bridegroom will be taken away from them. Then they will fast in those days."U∞He also told a parable to them. "No one puts a piece from a new garment on an old garment, or else he will tear the new, and also the piece from the new will not match the old.UåNo one puts new wine into old wineskins, or else the new wine will burst the skins, and it will be spilled, and the skins will be destroyed.UFBut new wine must be put into fresh wineskins, and both are preserved.UXNo man having drunk old wine immediately desires new, for he says, 'The old is better.'"t(NU≤Now it happened on the second Sabbath after the first, that he was going through the grain fields. His disciples plucked the heads of grain, and ate, rubbing them in their hands.UjBut some of the Pharisees said to them, "Why do you do that which is not lawful to do on the Sabbath day?"UrJesus, answering them, said, "Haven't you read what David did when he was hungry, he, and those who were with him;U™how he entered into the house of God, and took and ate the show bread, and gave also to those who were with him, which is not lawful to eat except for the priests alone?"U9He said to them, "The Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath."UäIt also happened on another Sabbath that he entered into the synagogue and taught. There was a man there, and his right hand was withered.UáThe scribes and the Pharisees watched him, to see whether he would heal on the Sabbath, that they might find an accusation against him.UÖBut he knew their thoughts; and he said to the man who had the withered hand, "Rise up, and stand in the middle." He arose and stood.UáThen Jesus said to them, "I will ask you something: Is it lawful on the Sabbath to do good, or to do harm? To save a life, or to kill?"UÑHe looked around at them all, and said to the man, "Stretch out your hand." He did, and his hand was restored as sound as the other.U^But they were filled with rage, and talked with one another about what they might do to Jesus.UqIt happened in these days, that he went out to the mountain to pray, and he continued all night in prayer to God.UeWhen it was day, he called his disciples, and from them he chose twelve, whom he also named apostles:UWSimon, whom he also named Peter; Andrew, his brother; James; John; Philip; Bartholomew;UNMatthew; Thomas; James, the son of Alphaeus; Simon, who was called the Zealot;UFJudas the son of James; and Judas Iscariot, who also became a traitor.UÔHe came down with them, and stood on a level place, with a crowd of his disciples, and a great number of the people from all Judea and Jerusalem, and the sea coast of Tyre and Sidon, who came to hear him and to be healed of their diseases;URas well as those who were troubled by unclean spirits, and they were being healed.UWAll the multitude sought to touch him, for power came out from him and healed them all.UqHe lifted up his eyes to his disciples, and said, "Blessed are you who are poor, for yours is the Kingdom of God.UiBlessed are you who hunger now, for you will be filled. Blessed are you who weep now, for you will laugh.UéBlessed are you when men shall hate you, and when they shall exclude and mock you, and throw out your name as evil, for the Son of Man's sake.UàRejoice in that day, and leap for joy, for behold, your reward is great in heaven, for their fathers did the same thing to the prophets.UE"But woe to you who are rich! For you have received your consolation.UpWoe to you, you who are full now, for you will be hungry. Woe to you who laugh now, for you will mourn and weep.U\Woe, when men speak well of you, for their fathers did the same thing to the false prophets.UK"But I tell you who hear: love your enemies, do good to those who hate you,U?bless those who curse you, and pray for those who mistreat you.UÅTo him who strikes you on the cheek, offer also the other; and from him who takes away your cloak, don't withhold your coat also.UcGive to everyone who asks you, and don't ask him who takes away your goods to give them back again.U>"As you would like people to do to you, do exactly so to them.UfIf you love those who love you, what credit is that to you? For even sinners love those who love them.UeIf you do good to those who do good to you, what credit is that to you? For even sinners do the same.UÜIf you lend to those from whom you hope to receive, what credit is that to you? Even sinners lend to sinners, to receive back as much.UæBut love your enemies, and do good, and lend, expecting nothing back; and your reward will be great, and you will be children of the Most High; for he is kind toward the unthankful and evil.U<Therefore be merciful, even as your Father is also merciful.UtDon't judge, and you won't be judged. Don't condemn, and you won't be condemned. Set free, and you will be set free.U¿"Give, and it will be given to you: good measure, pressed down, shaken together, and running over, will be given to you. For with the same measure you measure it will be measured back to you."U\He spoke a parable to them. "Can the blind guide the blind? Won't they both fall into a pit?UdA disciple is not above his teacher, but everyone when he is fully trained will be like his teacher.UuWhy do you see the speck of chaff that is in your brother's eye, but don't consider the beam that is in your own eye?T1␀␀Or how can you tell your brother, 'Brother, let me remove the speck of chaff that is in your eye,' when you yourself don't see the beam that is in your own eye? You hypocrite! First remove the beam from your own eye, and then you can see clearly to remove the speck of chaff that is in your brother's eye.UoFor there is no good tree that brings forth rotten fruit; nor again a rotten tree that brings forth good fruit.UÅFor each tree is known by its own fruit. For people don't gather figs from thorns, nor do they gather grapes from a bramble bush.U‡The good man out of the good treasure of his heart brings out that which is good, and the evil man out of the evil treasure of his heart brings out that which is evil, for out of the abundance of the heart, his mouth speaks.UG"Why do you call me, 'Lord, Lord,' and don't do the things which I say?U\Everyone who comes to me, and hears my words, and does them, I will show you who he is like.U—He is like a man building a house, who dug and went deep, and laid a foundation on the rock. When a flood arose, the stream broke against that house, and could not shake it, because it was founded on the rock.UƒBut he who hears, and doesn't do, is like a man who built a house on the earth without a foundation, against which the stream broke, and immediately it fell, and the ruin of that house was great."t(NUWAfter he had finished speaking in the hearing of the people, he entered into Capernaum.UWA certain centurion's servant, who was dear to him, was sick and at the point of death.UfWhen he heard about Jesus, he sent to him elders of the Jews, asking him to come and save his servant.UeWhen they came to Jesus, they begged him earnestly, saying, "He is worthy for you to do this for him,U<for he loves our nation, and he built our synagogue for us."U¡Jesus went with them. When he was now not far from the house, the centurion sent friends to him, saying to him, "Lord, don't trouble yourself, for I am not worthy for you to come under my roof.UlTherefore I didn't even think myself worthy to come to you; but say the word, and my servant will be healed.U¬For I also am a man placed under authority, having under myself soldiers. I tell this one, 'Go!' and he goes; and to another, 'Come!' and he comes; and to my servant, 'Do this,' and he does it."U≠When Jesus heard these things, he marveled at him, and turned and said to the multitude who followed him, "I tell you, I have not found such great faith, no, not in Israel."U_Those who were sent, returning to the house, found that the servant who had been sick was well.UÑIt happened soon afterwards, that he went to a city called Nain. Many of his disciples, along with a great multitude, went with him.U∞Now when he drew near to the gate of the city, behold, one who was dead was carried out, the only son of his mother, and she was a widow. Many people of the city were with her.UNWhen the Lord saw her, he had compassion on her, and said to her, "Don't cry."UjHe came near and touched the coffin, and the bearers stood still. He said, "Young man, I tell you, arise!"UJHe who was dead sat up, and began to speak. And he gave him to his mother.UÄFear took hold of all, and they glorified God, saying, "A great prophet has arisen among us!" and, "God has visited his people!"U]This report went out concerning him in the whole of Judea, and in all the surrounding region.U6The disciples of John told him about all these things.UäJohn, calling to himself two of his disciples, sent them to Jesus, saying, "Are you the one who is coming, or should we look for another?"UèWhen the men had come to him, they said, "John the B