nna, the wife of Chuzas, Herod's steward; Susanna; and many others; who served them from their possessions.UkWhen a great multitude came together, and people from every city were coming to him, he spoke by a parable.Uí"The farmer went out to sow his seed. As he sowed, some fell along the road, and it was trampled under foot, and the birds of the sky devoured it.UbOther seed fell on the rock, and as soon as it grew, it withered away, because it had no moisture.UGOther fell amid the thorns, and the thorns grew with it, and choked it.UßOther fell into the good ground, and grew, and brought forth fruit one hundred times." As he said these things, he called out, "He who has ears to hear, let him hear!"U<Then his disciples asked him, "What does this parable mean?"U´He said, "To you it is given to know the mysteries of the Kingdom of God, but to the rest in parables; that 'seeing they may not see, and hearing they may not understand.'U5Now the parable is this: The seed is the word of God.UêThose along the road are those who hear, then the devil comes, and takes away the word from their heart, that they may not believe and be saved.U°Those on the rock are they who, when they hear, receive the word with joy; but these have no root, who believe for a while, then fall away in time of temptation.U∏That which fell among the thorns, these are those who have heard, and as they go on their way they are choked with cares, riches, and pleasures of life, and bring no fruit to maturity.UîThat in the good ground, these are such as in an honest and good heart, having heard the word, hold it tightly, and bring forth fruit with patience.Uó"No one, when he has lit a lamp, covers it with a container, or puts it under a bed; but puts it on a stand, that those who enter in may see the light.UpFor nothing is hidden, that will not be revealed; nor anything secret, that will not be known and come to light.U¢Be careful therefore how you hear. For whoever has, to him will be given; and whoever doesn't have, from him will be taken away even that which he thinks he has."UTHis mother and brothers came to him, and they could not come near him for the crowd.UcIt was told him by some saying, "Your mother and your brothers stand outside, desiring to see you."U`But he answered them, "My mother and my brothers are these who hear the word of God, and do it."U∑Now it happened on one of those days, that he entered into a boat, himself and his disciples, and he said to them, "Let's go over to the other side of the lake." So they launched out.U{But as they sailed, he fell asleep. A wind storm came down on the lake, and they were taking on dangerous amounts of water.U¶They came to him, and awoke him, saying, "Master, master, we are dying!" He awoke, and rebuked the wind and the raging of the water, and they ceased, and it was calm.U±He said to them, "Where is your faith?" Being afraid they marveled, saying one to another, "Who is this, then, that he commands even the winds and the water, and they obey him?"UHThey arrived at the country of the Gadarenes, which is opposite Galilee.U¢When Jesus stepped ashore, a certain man out of the city who had demons for a long time met him. He wore no clothes, and didn't live in a house, but in the tombs.UπWhen he saw Jesus, he cried out, and fell down before him, and with a loud voice said, "What do I have to do with you, Jesus, you Son of the Most High God? I beg you, don't torment me!"UˆFor Jesus was commanding the unclean spirit to come out of the man. For the unclean spirit had often seized the man. He was kept under guard, and bound with chains and fetters. Breaking the bands apart, he was driven by the demon into the desert.U^Jesus asked him, "What is your name?" He said, "Legion," for many demons had entered into him.UDThey begged him that he would not command them to go into the abyss.UìNow there was there a herd of many pigs feeding on the mountain, and they begged him that he would allow them to enter into those. He allowed them.UÖThe demons came out from the man, and entered into the pigs, and the herd rushed down the steep bank into the lake, and were drowned.UeWhen those who fed them saw what had happened, they fled, and told it in the city and in the country.UøPeople went out to see what had happened. They came to Jesus, and found the man from whom the demons had gone out, sitting at Jesus' feet, clothed and in his right mind; and they were afraid.UNThose who saw it told them how he who had been possessed by demons was healed.U°All the people of the surrounding country of the Gadarenes asked him to depart from them, for they were very much afraid. He entered into the boat, and returned.UtBut the man from whom the demons had gone out begged him that he might go with him, but Jesus sent him away, saying,U¨"Return to your house, and declare what great things God has done for you." He went his way, proclaiming throughout the whole city what great things Jesus had done for him.UeIt happened, when Jesus returned, that the multitude welcomed him, for they were all waiting for him.UèBehold, there came a man named Jairus, and he was a ruler of the synagogue. He fell down at Jesus' feet, and begged him to come into his house,U~for he had an only daughter, about twelve years of age, and she was dying. But as he went, the multitudes pressed against him.U}A woman who had a flow of blood for twelve years, who had spent all her living on physicians, and could not be healed by any,Udcame behind him, and touched the fringe of his cloak, and immediately the flow of her blood stopped.UûJesus said, "Who touched me?" When all denied it, Peter and those with him said, "Master, the multitudes press and jostle you, and you say, 'Who touched me?'"UVBut Jesus said, "Someone did touch me, for I perceived that power has gone out of me."U’When the woman saw that she was not hidden, she came trembling, and falling down before him declared to him in the presence of all the people the reason why she had touched him,