UFmen who have risked their lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.UkWe have sent therefore Judas and Silas, who themselves will also tell you the same things by word of mouth.UnFor it seemed good to the Holy Spirit, and to us, to lay no greater burden on you than these necessary things:U∏that you abstain from things sacrificed to idols, from blood, from things strangled, and from sexual immorality, from which if you keep yourselves, it will be well with you. Farewell."UuSo, when they were sent off, they came to Antioch. Having gathered the multitude together, they delivered the letter.U<When they had read it, they rejoiced over the encouragement.UpJudas and Silas, also being prophets themselves, encouraged the brothers with many words, and strengthened them.UkAfter they had spent some time there, they were sent back with greetings from the brothers to the apostles.U␀UlBut Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch, teaching and preaching the word of the Lord, with many others also.U¶After some days Paul said to Barnabas, "Let's return now and visit our brothers in every city in which we proclaimed the word of the Lord, to see how they are doing."UCBarnabas planned to take John, who was called Mark, with them also.UôBut Paul didn't think that it was a good idea to take with them someone who had withdrawn from them in Pamphylia, and didn't go with them to do the work.U~Then the contention grew so sharp that they separated from each other. Barnabas took Mark with him, and sailed away to Cyprus,UXbut Paul chose Silas, and went out, being commended by the brothers to the grace of God.U@He went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the assemblies.t(NUìHe came to Derbe and Lystra: and behold, a certain disciple was there, named Timothy, the son of a Jewess who believed; but his father was a Greek.ULThe brothers who were at Lystra and Iconium gave a good testimony about him.U§Paul wanted to have him go out with him, and he took and circumcised him because of the Jews who were in those parts; for they all knew that his father was a Greek.U¢As they went on their way through the cities, they delivered the decrees to them to keep which had been ordained by the apostles and elders who were at Jerusalem.UPSo the assemblies were strengthened in the faith, and increased in number daily.UWhen they had gone through the region of Phrygia and Galatia, they were forbidden by the Holy Spirit to speak the word in Asia.UdWhen they had come opposite Mysia, they tried to go into Bithynia, but the Spirit didn't allow them.U*Passing by Mysia, they came down to Troas.UèA vision appeared to Paul in the night. There was a man of Macedonia standing, begging him, and saying, "Come over into Macedonia and help us."UíWhen he had seen the vision, immediately we sought to go out to Macedonia, concluding that the Lord had called us to preach the Good News to them.UnSetting sail therefore from Troas, we made a straight course to Samothrace, and the day following to Neapolis;Uèand from there to Philippi, which is a city of Macedonia, the foremost of the district, a Roman colony. We were staying some days in this city.U≤On the Sabbath day we went forth outside of the city by a riverside, where we supposed there was a place of prayer, and we sat down, and spoke to the women who had come together.UπA certain woman named Lydia, a seller of purple, of the city of Thyatira, one who worshiped God, heard us; whose heart the Lord opened to listen to the things which were spoken by Paul.UßWhen she and her household were baptized, she begged us, saying, "If you have judged me to be faithful to the Lord, come into my house, and stay." So she persuaded us.UòIt happened, as we were going to prayer, that a certain girl having a spirit of divination met us, who brought her masters much gain by fortune telling.U{Following Paul and us, she cried out, "These men are servants of the Most High God, who proclaim to us a way of salvation!"U¿She was doing this for many days. But Paul, becoming greatly annoyed, turned and said to the spirit, "I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her!" It came out that very hour.UìBut when her masters saw that the hope of their gain was gone, they seized Paul and Silas, and dragged them into the marketplace before the rulers.UiWhen they had brought them to the magistrates, they said, "These men, being Jews, are agitating our city,U[and set forth customs which it is not lawful for us to accept or to observe, being Romans."UãThe multitude rose up together against them, and the magistrates tore their clothes off of them, and commanded them to be beaten with rods.UnWhen they had laid many stripes on them, they threw them into prison, charging the jailer to keep them safely,Ulwho, having received such a command, threw them into the inner prison, and secured their feet in the stocks.UrBut about midnight Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the prisoners were listening to them.U®Suddenly there was a great earthquake, so that the foundations of the prison were shaken; and immediately all the doors were opened, and everyone's bonds were loosened.UüThe jailer, being roused out of sleep and seeing the prison doors open, drew his sword and was about to kill himself, supposing that the prisoners had escaped.UUBut Paul cried with a loud voice, saying, "Don't harm yourself, for we are all here!"USHe called for lights and sprang in, and, fell down trembling before Paul and Silas,UBand brought them out and said, "Sirs, what must I do to be saved?"U]They said, "Believe in the Lord Jesus Christ, and you will be saved, you and your household."UIThey spoke the word of the Lord to him, and to all who were in his house.UzHe took them the same hour of the night, and washed their stripes, and was immediately baptized, he and all his household.UÇHe brought them up into his house, and set food before them, and rejoiced greatly, with all his household, having believed in God.UTBut when it was day, the magistrates sent the sergeants, saying, "Let those men go."UÑThe jailer reported these words to Paul, saying, "The magistrates have sent to let you go; now therefore come out, and go in peace."U›But Paul said to them, "They have beaten us publicly, without a trial, men who are Romans, and have cast us into prison! Do they now release us secretly? No, most certainly, but let them come themselves and bring us out!"UrThe sergeants reported these words to the magistrates, and they were afraid when they heard that they were Romans,Ugand they came and begged them. When they had brought them out, they asked them to depart from the city.UÅThey went out of the prison, and entered into Lydia's house. When they had seen the brothers, they encouraged them, and departed.t(NUyNow when they had passed through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica, where there was a Jewish synagogue.UlPaul, as was his custom, went in to them, and for three Sabbath days reasoned with them from the Scriptures,Uôexplaining and demonstrating that the Christ had to suffer and rise again from the dead, and saying, "This Jesus, whom I proclaim to you, is the Christ."UÅSome of them were persuaded, and joined Paul and Silas, of the devout Greeks a great multitude, and not a few of the chief women.U«But the unpersuaded Jews took along some wicked men from the marketplace, and gathering a crowd, set the city in an uproar. Assaulting the house of Jason, they sought to bring them out to the people.U¨When they didn't find them, they dragged Jason and certain brothers before the rulers of the city, crying, "These who have turned the world upside down have come here also,Utwhom Jason has received. These all act contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is another king, Jesus!"UTThe multitude and the rulers of the city were troubled when they heard these things.UGWhen they had taken security from Jason and the rest, they let them go.U}The brothers immediately sent Paul and Silas away by night to Beroea. When they arrived, they went into the Jewish synagogue.U∏Now these were more noble than those in Thessalonica, in that they received the word with all readiness of the mind, examining the Scriptures daily to see whether these things were so.UVMany of them therefore believed; also of the prominent Greek women, and not a few men.UüBut when the Jews of Thessalonica had knowledge that the word of God was proclaimed by Paul at Beroea also, they came there likewise, agitating the multitudes.UqThen the brothers immediately sent out Paul to go as far as to the sea, and Silas and Timothy still stayed there.U†But those who escorted Paul brought him as far as Athens. Receiving a commandment to Silas and Timothy that they should come to him very quickly, they departed.UnNow while Paul waited for them at Athens, his spirit was provoked within him as he saw the city full of idols.U~So he reasoned in the synagogue with the Jews and the devout persons, and in the marketplace every day with those who met him.UÊSome of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers also were conversing with him. Some said, "What does this babbler want to say?" Others said, "He seems to be advocating foreign deities," because he preached Jesus and the resurrection.UÄThey took hold of him, and brought him to the Areopagus, saying, "May we know what this new teaching is, which is spoken by you?UdFor you bring certain strange things to our ears. We want to know therefore what these things mean."UÑNow all the Athenians and the strangers living there spent their time in nothing else, but either to tell or to hear some new thing.U~Paul stood in the middle of the Areopagus, and said, "You men of Athens, I perceive that you are very religious in all things.U√For as I passed along, and observed the objects of your worship, I found also an altar with this inscription: 'TO AN UNKNOWN GOD.' What therefore you worship in ignorance, this I announce to you.U~The God who made the world and all things in it, he, being Lord of heaven and earth, doesn't dwell in temples made with hands,UÇneither is he served by men's hands, as though he needed anything, seeing he himself gives to all life and breath, and all things.U†He made from one blood every nation of men to dwell on all the surface of the earth, having determined appointed seasons, and the boundaries of their dwellings,Uthat they should seek the Lord, if perhaps they might reach out for him and find him, though he is not far from each one of us.Uy'For in him we live, and move, and have our being.' As some of your own poets have said, 'For we are also his offspring.'UìBeing then the offspring of God, we ought not to think that the Divine Nature is like gold, or silver, or stone, engraved by art and design of man.UnThe times of ignorance therefore God overlooked. But now he commands that all people everywhere should repent,U«because he has appointed a day in which he will judge the world in righteousness by the man whom he has ordained; of which he has given assurance to all men, in that he has raised him from the dead."UNow when they heard of the resurrection of the dead, some mocked; but others said, "We want to hear you again concerning this."U#Thus Paul went out from among them.UçBut certain men joined with him, and believed, among whom also was Dionysius the Areopagite, and a woman named Damaris, and others with them.t(NUBAfter these things Paul departed from Athens, and came to Corinth.U He found a certain Jew named Aquila, a man of Pontus by race, who had recently come from Italy, with his wife Priscilla, because Claudius had commanded all the Jews to depart from Rome. He came to them,Ukand because he practiced the same trade, he lived with them and worked, for by trade they were tent makers.UJHe reasoned in the synagogue every Sabbath, and persuaded Jews and Greeks.UàBut when Silas and Timothy came down from Macedonia, Paul was compelled by the Spirit, testifying to the Jews that Jesus was the Christ.U®When they opposed him and blasphemed, he shook out his clothing and said to them, "Your blood be on your own heads! I am clean. From now on, I will go to the Gentiles!"UåHe departed there, and went into the house of a certain man named Justus, one who worshiped God, whose house was next door to the synagogue.UìCrispus, the ruler of the synagogue, believed in the Lord with all his house. Many of the Corinthians, when they heard, believed and were baptized.U`The Lord said to Paul in the night by a vision, "Don't be afraid, but speak and don't be silent;U`for I am with you, and no one will attack you to harm you, for I have many people in this city."UJHe lived there a year and six months, teaching the word of God among them.UÄBut when Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one accord rose up against Paul and brought him before the judgment seat,UDsaying, "This man persuades men to worship God contrary to the law."U∫But when Paul was about to open his mouth, Gallio said to the Jews, "If indeed it were a matter of wrong or of wicked crime, you Jews, it would be reasonable that I should bear with you;Uäbut if they are questions about words and names and your own law, look to it yourselves. For I don't want to be a judge of these matters."U%He drove them from the judgment seat.UúThen all the Greeks laid hold on Sosthenes, the ruler of the synagogue, and beat him before the judgment seat. Gallio didn't care about any of these things.U∆Paul, having stayed after this many more days, took his leave of the brothers, and sailed from there for Syria, together with Priscilla and Aquila. He shaved his head in Cenchreae, for he had a vow.UrHe came to Ephesus, and he left them there; but he himself entered into the synagogue, and reasoned with the Jews.UAWhen they asked him to stay with them a longer time, he declined;U´but taking his leave of them, and saying, "I must by all means keep this coming feast in Jerusalem, but I will return again to you if God wills," he set sail from Ephesus.U^When he had landed at Caesarea, he went up and greeted the assembly, and went down to Antioch.UâHaving spent some time there, he departed, and went through the region of Galatia, and Phrygia, in order, establishing all the disciples.U{Now a certain Jew named Apollos, an Alexandrian by race, an eloquent man, came to Ephesus. He was mighty in the Scriptures.U∏This man had been instructed in the way of the Lord; and being fervent in spirit, he spoke and taught accurately the things concerning Jesus, although he knew only the baptism of John.UùHe began to speak boldly in the synagogue. But when Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him aside, and explained to him the way of God more accurately.U¬When he had determined to pass over into Achaia, the brothers encouraged him, and wrote to the disciples to receive him. When he had come, he greatly helped those who had believed through grace;Uafor he powerfully refuted the Jews, publicly showing by the Scriptures that Jesus was the Christ.t(NUåIt happened that, while Apollos was at Corinth, Paul, having passed through the upper country, came to Ephesus, and found certain disciples.UêHe said to them, "Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?" They said to him, "No, we haven't even heard that there is a Holy Spirit."UNHe said, "Into what then were you baptized?" They said, "Into John's baptism."UßPaul said, "John indeed baptized with the baptism of repentance, saying to the people that they should believe in the one who would come after him, that is, in Jesus."UGWhen they heard this, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus.UwWhen Paul had laid his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came on them, and they spoke with other languages and prophesied.U"They were about twelve men in all.UñHe entered into the synagogue, and spoke boldly for a period of three months, reasoning and persuading about the things concerning the Kingdom of God.U∫But when some were hardened and disobedient, speaking evil of the Way before the multitude, he departed from them, and separated the disciples, reasoning daily in the school of Tyrannus.UyThis continued for two years, so that all those who lived in Asia heard the word of the Lord Jesus, both Jews and Greeks.U1God worked special miracles by the hands of Paul,Upso that even handkerchiefs or aprons were carried away from his body to the sick, and the evil spirits went out.UºBut some of the itinerant Jews, exorcists, took on themselves to invoke over those who had the evil spirits the name of the Lord Jesus, saying, "We adjure you by Jesus whom Paul preaches."UHThere were seven sons of one Sceva, a Jewish chief priest, who did this.UKThe evil spirit answered, "Jesus I know, and Paul I know, but who are you?"UúThe man in whom the evil spirit was leaped on them, and overpowered them, and prevailed against them, so that they fled out of that house naked and wounded.UäThis became known to all, both Jews and Greeks, who lived at Ephesus. Fear fell on them all, and the name of the Lord Jesus was magnified.UPMany also of those who had believed came, confessing, and declaring their deeds.UæMany of those who practiced magical arts brought their books together and burned them in the sight of all. They counted the price of them, and found it to be fifty thousand pieces of silver.U8So the word of the Lord was growing and becoming mighty.UæNow after these things had ended, Paul determined in the spirit, when he had passed through Macedonia and Achaia, to go to Jerusalem, saying, "After I have been there, I must also see Rome."UsHaving sent into Macedonia two of those who served him, Timothy and Erastus, he himself stayed in Asia for a while.U=About that time there arose no small stir concerning the Way.UÇFor a certain man named Demetrius, a silversmith, who made silver shrines of Artemis, brought no little business to the craftsmen,UÉwhom he gathered together, with the workmen of like occupation, and said, "Sirs, you know that by this business we have our wealth.UπYou see and hear, that not at Ephesus alone, but almost throughout all Asia, this Paul has persuaded and turned away many people, saying that they are no gods, that are made with hands.U’Not only is there danger that this our trade come into disrepute, but also that the temple of the great goddess Artemis will be counted as nothing, and her majesty destroyed, whom all Asia and the world worships."UmWhen they heard this they were filled with anger, and cried out, saying, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"UØThe whole city was filled with confusion, and they rushed with one accord into the theater, having seized Gaius and Aristarchus, men of Macedonia, Paul's companions in travel.UKWhen Paul wanted to enter in to the people, the disciples didn't allow him.UlCertain also of the Asiarchs, being his friends, sent to him and begged him not to venture into the theater.UâSome therefore cried one thing, and some another, for the assembly was in confusion. Most of them didn't know why they had come together.UôThey brought Alexander out of the multitude, the Jews putting him forward. Alexander beckoned with his hand, and would have made a defense to the people.UãBut when they perceived that he was a Jew, all with one voice for a time of about two hours cried out, "Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!"UÈWhen the town clerk had quieted the multitude, he said, "You men of Ephesus, what man is there who doesn't know that the city of the Ephesians is temple keeper of the great goddess Artemis, and of the image which fell down from Zeus?U]Seeing then that these things can't be denied, you ought to be quiet, and to do nothing rash.UhFor you have brought these men here, who are neither robbers of temples nor blasphemers of your goddess.U≤If therefore Demetrius and the craftsmen who are with him have a matter against anyone, the courts are open, and there are proconsuls. Let them press charges against one another.UYBut if you seek anything about other matters, it will be settled