ame the following day opposite Chios. The next day we touched at Samos and stayed at Trogyllium, and the day after we came to Miletus.U∫For Paul had determined to sail past Ephesus, that he might not have to spend time in Asia; for he was hastening, if it were possible for him, to be in Jerusalem on the day of Pentecost.URFrom Miletus he sent to Ephesus, and called to himself the elders of the assembly.UéWhen they had come to him, he said to them, "You yourselves know, from the first day that I set foot in Asia, how I was with you all the time,Usserving the Lord with all humility, with many tears, and with trials which happened to me by the plots of the Jews;Uvhow I didn't shrink from declaring to you anything that was profitable, teaching you publicly and from house to house,U]testifying both to Jews and to Greeks repentance toward God, and faith toward our Lord Jesus.U]Now, behold, I go bound by the Spirit to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there;Ucexcept that the Holy Spirit testifies in every city, saying that bonds and afflictions wait for me.UÿBut these things don't count; nor do I hold my life dear to myself, so that I may finish my race with joy, and the ministry which I received from the Lord Jesus, to fully testify to the Good News of the grace of God.Ur"Now, behold, I know that you all, among whom I went about preaching the Kingdom of God, will see my face no more.UNTherefore I testify to you this day that I am clean from the blood of all men,UCfor I didn't shrink from declaring to you the whole counsel of God.UøTake heed, therefore, to yourselves, and to all the flock, in which the Holy Spirit has made you overseers, to shepherd the assembly of the Lord and God which he purchased with his own blood.UbFor I know that after my departure, vicious wolves will enter in among you, not sparing the flock.UkMen will arise from among your own selves, speaking perverse things, to draw away the disciples after them.U{Therefore watch, remembering that for a period of three years I didn't cease to admonish everyone night and day with tears.U°Now, brothers, I entrust you to God, and to the word of his grace, which is able to build up, and to give you the inheritance among all those who are sanctified.U0I coveted no one's silver, or gold, or clothing.UWYou yourselves know that these hands served my necessities, and those who were with me.U√In all things I gave you an example, that so laboring you ought to help the weak, and to remember the words of the Lord Jesus, that he himself said, 'It is more blessed to give than to receive.'"UHWhen he had spoken these things, he knelt down and prayed with them all.U<They all wept a lot, and fell on Paul's neck and kissed him,Uãsorrowing most of all because of the word which he had spoken, that they should see his face no more. And they accompanied him to the ship.t(NUúWhen it happened that we had parted from them and had set sail, we came with a straight course to Cos, and the next day to Rhodes, and from there to Patara.UMHaving found a ship crossing over to Phoenicia, we went aboard, and set sail.UïWhen we had come in sight of Cyprus, leaving it on the left hand, we sailed to Syria, and landed at Tyre, for there the ship was to unload her cargo.UÅHaving found disciples, we stayed there seven days. These said to Paul through the Spirit, that he should not go up to Jerusalem.U◊When it happened that we had accomplished the days, we departed and went on our journey. They all, with wives and children, brought us on our way until we were out of the city. Kneeling down on the beach, we prayed.U\After saying goodbye to each other, we went on board the ship, and they returned home again.UzWhen we had finished the voyage from Tyre, we arrived at Ptolemais. We greeted the brothers, and stayed with them one day.U≥On the next day, we, who were Paul's companions, departed, and came to Caesarea. We entered into the house of Philip the evangelist, who was one of the seven, and stayed with him.U6Now this man had four virgin daughters who prophesied.URAs we stayed there some days, a certain prophet named Agabus came down from Judea.U„Coming to us, and taking Paul's belt, he bound his own feet and hands, and said, "Thus says the Holy Spirit: 'So will the Jews at Jerusalem bind the man who owns this belt, and will deliver him into the hands of the Gentiles.'"U`When we heard these things, both we and they of that place begged him not to go up to Jerusalem.U™Then Paul answered, "What are you doing, weeping and breaking my heart? For I am ready not only to be bound, but also to die at Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jesus."UMWhen he would not be persuaded, we ceased, saying, "The Lord's will be done."UAAfter these days we took up our baggage and went up to Jerusalem.UÅSome of the disciples from Caesarea also went with us, bringing one Mnason of Cyprus, an early disciple, with whom we would stay.U?When we had come to Jerusalem, the brothers received us gladly.URThe day following, Paul went in with us to James; and all the elders were present.UyWhen he had greeted them, he reported one by one the things which God had worked among the Gentiles through his ministry.UªThey, when they heard it, glorified God. They said to him, "You see, brother, how many thousands there are among the Jews of those who have believed, and they are all zealous for the law.UºThey have been informed about you, that you teach all the Jews who are among the Gentiles to forsake Moses, telling them not to circumcise their children neither to walk after the customs.USWhat then? The assembly must certainly meet, for they will hear that you have come.UETherefore do what we tell you. We have four men who have taken a vow.U¸Take them, and purify yourself with them, and pay their expenses for them, that they may shave their heads. Then all will know that there is no truth in the things that they have been informed about you, but that you yourself also walk keeping the law.UÒBut concerning the Gentiles who believe, we have written our decision that they should observe no such thing, except that they should keep themselves from food offered to idols, from blood, from strangled things, and from sexual immorality."UÀThen Paul took the men, and the next day, purified himself and went with them into the temple, declaring the fulfillment of the days of purification, until the offering was offered for every one of them.UìWhen the seven days were almost completed, the Jews from Asia, when they saw him in the temple, stirred up all the multitude and laid hands on him,U’crying out, "Men of Israel, help! This is the man who teaches all men everywhere against the people, and the law, and this place. Moreover, he also brought Greeks into the temple, and has defiled this holy place!"U}For they had seen Trophimus, the Ephesian, with him in the city, and they supposed that Paul had brought him into the temple.UâAll the city was moved, and the people ran together. They seized Paul and dragged him out of the temple. Immediately the doors were shut.U|As they were trying to kill him, news came up to the commanding officer of the regiment that all Jerusalem was in an uproar.UêImmediately he took soldiers and centurions, and ran down to them. They, when they saw the chief captain and the soldiers, stopped beating Paul.UçThen the commanding officer came near, arrested him, commanded him to be bound with two chains, and inquired who he was and what he had done.U¶Some shouted one thing, and some another, among the crowd. When he couldn't find out the truth because of the noise, he commanded him to be brought into the barracks.UqWhen he came to the stairs, it happened that he was carried by the soldiers because of the violence of the crowd;ULfor the multitude of the people followed after, crying out, "Away with him!"UÜAs Paul was about to be brought into the barracks, he asked the commanding officer, "May I speak to you?" He said, "Do you know Greek?UìAren't you then the Egyptian, who before these days stirred up to sedition and led out into the wilderness the four thousand men of the Assassins?"UÑBut Paul said, "I am a Jew, from Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no insignificant city. I beg you, allow me to speak to the people."U∂When he had given him permission, Paul, standing on the stairs, beckoned with his hand to the people. When there was a great silence, he spoke to them in the Hebrew language, saying,t(NUF"Brothers and fathers, listen to the defense which I now make to you."UaWhen they heard that he spoke to them in the Hebrew language, they were even more quiet. He said,U›"I am indeed a Jew, born in Tarsus of Cilicia, but brought up in this city at the feet of Gamaliel, instructed according to the strict manner of the law of our fathers, being zealous for God, even as you all are this day.U[I persecuted this Way to the death, binding and delivering into prisons both men and women.U÷As also the high priest and all the council of the elders testify, from whom also I received letters to the brothers, and traveled to Damascus to bring them also who were there to Jerusalem in bonds to be punished.UäIt happened that, as I made my journey, and came close to Damascus, about noon, suddenly there shone from the sky a great light around me.U_I fell to the ground, and heard a voice saying to me, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?'U]I answered, 'Who are you, Lord?' He said to me, 'I am Jesus of Nazareth, whom you persecute.'Uz"Those who were with me indeed saw the light and were afraid, but they didn't understand the voice of him who spoke to me.UüI said, 'What shall I do, Lord?' The Lord said to me, 'Arise, and go into Damascus. There you will be told about all things which are appointed for you to do.'UwWhen I couldn't see for the glory of that light, being led by the hand of those who were with me, I came into Damascus.UgOne Ananias, a devout man according to the law, well reported of by all the Jews who lived in Damascus,Utcame to me, and standing by me said to me, 'Brother Saul, receive your sight!' In that very hour I looked up at him.UÜHe said, 'The God of our fathers has appointed you to know his will, and to see the Righteous One, and to hear a voice from his mouth.UMFor you will be a witness for him to all men of what you have seen and heard.UcNow why do you wait? Arise, be baptized, and wash away your sins, calling on the name of the Lord.'Ul"It happened that, when I had returned to Jerusalem, and while I prayed in the temple, I fell into a trance,UÉand saw him saying to me, 'Hurry and get out of Jerusalem quickly, because they will not receive testimony concerning me from you.'UlI said, 'Lord, they themselves know that I imprisoned and beat in every synagogue those who believed in you.UôWhen the blood of Stephen, your witness, was shed, I also was standing by, and consenting to his death, and guarding the cloaks of those who killed him.'UQ"He said to me, 'Depart, for I will send you out far from here to the Gentiles.'"UçThey listened to him until he said that; then they lifted up their voice, and said, "Rid the earth of this fellow, for he isn't fit to live!"UKAs they cried out, and threw off their cloaks, and threw dust into the air,Uµthe commanding officer commanded him to be brought into the barracks, ordering him to be examined by scourging, that he might know for what crime they shouted against him like that.UõWhen they had tied him up with thongs, Paul asked the centurion who stood by, "Is it lawful for you to scourge a man who is a Roman, and not found guilty?"UáWhen the centurion heard it, he went to the commanding officer and told him, "Watch what you are about to do, for this man is a Roman!"UVThe commanding officer came and asked him, "Tell me, are you a Roman?" He said, "Yes."UrThe commanding officer answered, "I bought my citizenship for a great price." Paul said, "But I was born a Roman."U≠Immediately those who were about to examine him departed from him, and the commanding officer also was afraid when he realized that he was a Roman, because he had bound him.UÁBut on the next day, desiring to know the truth about why he was accused by the Jews, he freed him from the bonds, and commanded the chief priests and all the council to come together, and brought Paul down and set him before them.t(NUzPaul, looking steadfastly at the council, said, "Brothers, I have lived before God in all good conscience until this day."UVThe high priest, Ananias, commanded those who stood by him to strike him on the mouth.U°Then Paul said to him, "God will strike you, you whitewashed wall! Do you sit to judge me according to the law, and command me to be struck contrary to the law?"U;Those who stood by said, "Do you malign God's high priest?"UáPaul said, "I didn't know, brothers, that he was high priest. For it is written, 'You shall not speak evil of a ruler of your people.'"UÎBut when Paul perceived that the one part were Sadducees and the other Pharisees, he cried out in the council, "Men and brothers, I am a Pharisee, a son of Pharisees. Concerning the hope and resurrection of the dead I am being judged!"UkWhen he had said this, an argument arose between the Pharisees and Sadducees, and the assembly was divided.UsFor the Sadducees say that there is no resurrection, nor angel, nor spirit; but the Pharisees confess all of these.UÃA great clamor arose, and some of the scribes of the Pharisees part stood up, and contended, saying, "We find no evil in this man. But if a spirit or angel has spoken to him, let's not fight against God!"U—When a great argument arose, the commanding officer, fearing that Paul would be torn in pieces by them, commanded the soldiers to go down and take him by force from among them, and bring him into the barracks.UöThe following night, the Lord stood by him, and said, "Cheer up, Paul, for as you have testified about me at Jerusalem, so you must testify also at Rome."UüWhen it was day, some of the Jews banded together, and bound themselves under a curse, saying that they would neither eat nor drink until they had killed Paul.U?There were more than forty people who had made this conspiracy.UíThey came to the chief priests and the elders, and said, "We have bound ourselves under a great curse, to taste nothing until we have killed Paul.UŸNow therefore, you with the council inform the commanding officer that he should bring him down to you tomorrow, as though you were going to judge his case more exactly. We are ready to kill him before he comes near."UnBut Paul's sister's son heard of their lying in wait, and he came and entered into the barracks and told Paul.UÇPaul summoned one of the centurions, and said, "Bring this young man to the commanding officer, for he has something to tell him."U≤So he took him, and brought him to the commanding officer, and said, "Paul, the prisoner, summoned me and asked me to bring this young man to you, who has something to tell you."UyThe commanding officer took him by the hand, and going aside, asked him privately, "What is it that you have to tell me?"UùHe said, "The Jews have agreed to ask you to bring Paul down to the council tomorrow, as though intending to inquire somewhat more accurately concerning him.U‚Therefore don't yield to them, for more than forty men lie in wait for him, who have bound themselves under a curse neither to eat nor to drink until they have killed him. Now they are ready, looking for the promise from you."UvSo the commanding officer let the young man go, charging him, "Tell no one that you have revealed these things to me."UÃHe called to himself two of the centurions, and said, "Prepare two hundred soldiers to go as far as Caesarea, with seventy horsemen, and two hundred men armed with spears, at the third hour of the night."UnHe asked them to provide animals, that they might set Paul on one, and bring him safely to Felix the governor.UHe wrote a letter like this:UA"Claudius Lysias to the most excellent governor Felix: Greetings.Uò"This man was seized by the Jews, and was about to be killed by them, when I came with the soldiers and rescued him, having learned that he was a Roman.UUDesiring to know the cause why they accused him, I brought him down to their council.UI found him to be accused about questions of their law, but not to be charged with anything worthy of death or of imprisonment.UÆWhen I was told that the Jews lay in wait for the man, I sent him to you immediately, charging his accusers also to bring their accusations against him before you. Farewell."U]So the soldiers, carrying out their orders, took Paul and brought him by night to Antipatris.UXBut on the next day they left the horsemen to go with him, and returned to the barracks.UeWhen they came to Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, they also presented Paul to him.UxWhen the governor had read it, he asked what province he was from. When he understood that he was from Cilicia, he said,Ug"I will hear you fully when your accusers also arrive." He commanded that he be kept in Herod's palace.t(NUèAfter five days, the high priest, Ananias, came down with certain elders and an orator, one Tertullus. They informed the governor against Paul.UöWhen he was called, Tertullus began to accuse him, saying, "Seeing that by you we enjoy much peace, and that excellent measures are coming to this nation,UXwe accept it in all ways and in all places, most excellent Felix, with all thankfulness.UPBut, that I don't delay you, I entreat you to bear with us and hear a few words.U°For we have found this man to be a plague, an instigator of insurrections among all the Jews throughout the world, and a ringleader of the sect of the Nazarenes.U9He even tried to profane the temple, and we arrested him.U␀UUBy examining him yourself you may ascertain all these things of which we accuse him."UHThe Jews also joined in the attack, affirming that these things were so.U¶When the governor had beckoned to him to speak, Paul answered, "Because I know that you have been a judge of this nation for many years, I cheerfully make my defense,Ukseeing that you can recognize that it is not more than twelve days since I went up to worship at Jerusalem.UyIn the temple they didn't find me disputing with anyone or stirring up a crowd, either in the synagogues, or in the city.UANor can they prove to you the things of which they now accuse me.U≈But this I confess to you, that after the Way, which they call a sect, so I serve the God of our fathers, believing all things which are according to the law, and which are written in the prophets;Uâhaving hope toward God, which these also themselves look for, that there will be a resurrection of the dead, both of the just and unjust.UUHerein I also practice always having a conscience void of offense toward God and men.UVNow after some years, I came to bring gifts for the needy to my nation, and offerings;Udamid which certain Jews from Asia found me purified in the temple, not with a mob, nor with turmoil.UaThey ought to have been here before you, and to make accusation, if they had anything against me.UeOr else let these men themselves say what injustice they found in me when I stood before the council,Uêunless it is for this one thing that I cried standing among them, 'Concerning the resurrection of the dead I am being judged before you today!'"UùBut Felix, having more exact knowledge concerning the Way, deferred them, saying, "When Lysias, the commanding officer, comes down, I will decide your case."U°He ordered the centurion that Paul should be kept in custody, and should have some privileges, and not to forbid any of his friends to serve him or to visit him.UëBut after some days, Felix came with Drusilla, his wife, who was a Jewess, and sent for Paul, and heard him concerning the faith in Christ Jesus.U¿As he reasoned about righteousness, self-control, and the judgment to come, Felix was terrified, and answered, "Go your way for this time, and when it is convenient for me, I will summon you."UùMeanwhile, he also hoped that money would be given to him by Paul, that he might release him. Therefore also he sent for him more often, and talked with him.UçBut when two years were fulfilled, Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus, and desiring to gain favor with the Jews, Felix left Paul in bonds.t(NUeFestus therefore, having come into the province, after three days went up to Jerusalem from Caesarea.UfThen the high priest and the principal men of the Jews informed him against Paul, and they begged him,Ucasking a favor against him, that he would summon him to Jerusalem; plotting to kill him on the way.UyHowever Festus answered that Paul should be kept in custody at Caesarea, and that he himself was about to depart shortly.Uç"Let them therefore," said he, "that are in power among you go down with me, and if there is anything wrong in the man, let them accuse him."UûWhen he had stayed among them more than ten days, he went down to Caesarea, and on the next day he sat on the judgment seat, and commanded Paul to be brought.UòWhen he had come, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him, bringing against him many and grievous charges which they could not prove,UÜwhile he said in his defense, "Neither against the law of the Jews, nor against the temple, nor against Caesar, have I sinned at all."U•But Festus, desiring to gain favor with the Jews, answered Paul and said, "Are you willing to go up to Jerusalem, and be judged by me there concerning these things?"UïBut Paul said, "I am standing before Caesar's judgment seat, where I ought to be tried. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as you also know very well.UÕFor if I have done wrong, and have committed anything worthy of death, I don't refuse to die; but if none of those things is true that they accuse me of, no one can give me up to them. I appeal to Caesar!"UuThen Festus, when he had conferred with the council, answered, "You have appealed to Caesar. To Caesar you shall go."UdNow when some days had passed, Agrippa the King and Bernice arrived at Caesarea, and greeted Festus.UÄAs he stayed there many days, Festus laid Paul's case before the king, saying, "There is a certain man left a prisoner by Felix;UÅabout whom, when I was at Jerusalem, the chief priests and the elders of the Jews informed me, asking for a sentence against him.UÁTo whom I answered that it is not the custom of the Romans to give up any man to destruction, before the accused has met the accusers face to face, and has had opportunity to make his defense concerning the matter laid against him.UéWhen therefore they had come together here, I didn't delay, but on the next day sat on the judgment seat, and commanded the man to be brought.UaConcerning whom, when the accusers stood up, they brought no charge of such things as I supposed;UÇbut had certain questions against him about their own religion, and about one Jesus, who was dead, whom Paul affirmed to be alive.UóBeing perplexed how to inquire concerning these things, I asked whether he was willing to go to Jerusalem and there be judged concerning these matters.UÑBut when Paul had appealed to be kept for the decision of the emperor, I commanded him to be kept until I could send him to Caesar."UnAgrippa said to Festus, "I also would like to hear the man myself." "Tomorrow," he said, "you shall hear him."U‡So on the next day, when Agrippa and Bernice had come with great pomp, and they had entered into the place of hearing with the commanding officers and principal men of the city, at the command of Festus, Paul was brought in.UÿFestus said, "King Agrippa, and all men who are here present with us, you see this man, about whom all the multitude of the Jews petitioned me, both at Jerusalem and here, crying that he ought not to live any longer.UÉBut when I found that he had committed nothing worthy of death, and as he himself appealed to the emperor I determined to send him.UƒOf whom I have no certain thing to write to my lord. Therefore I have brought him forth before you, and especially before you, King Agrippa, that, after examination, I may have something to write.UeFor it seems to me unreasonable, in sending a prisoner, not to also specify the charges against him."t(NUkAgrippa said to Paul, "You may speak for yourself." Then Paul stretched out his hand, and made his defense.Ué"I think myself happy, King Agrippa, that I am to make my defense before you this day concerning all the things that I am accused by the Jews,UÇespecially because you are expert in all customs and questions which are among the Jews. Therefore I beg you to hear me patiently.U~"Indeed, all the Jews know my way of life from my youth up, which was from the beginning among my own nation and at Jerusalem;UÅhaving known me from the first, if they are willing to testify, that after the strictest sect of our religion I lived a Pharisee.UUNow I stand here to be judged for the hope of the promise made by God to our fathers,UÜwhich our twelve tribes, earnestly serving night and day, hope to attain. Concerning this hope I am accused by the Jews, King Agrippa!UAWhy is it judged incredible with you, if God does raise the dead?Uj"I myself most certainly thought that I ought to do many things contrary to the name of Jesus of Nazareth.U∫This I also did in Jerusalem. I both shut up many of the saints in prisons, having received authority from the chief priests, and when they were put to death I gave my vote against them.UùPunishing them often in all the synagogues, I tried to make them blaspheme. Being exceedingly enraged against them, I persecuted them even to foreign cities.U^"Whereupon as I traveled to Damascus with the authority and commission from the chief priests,UÄat noon, O King, I saw on the way a light from the sky, brighter than the sun, shining around me and those who traveled with me.U±When we had all fallen to the earth, I heard a voice saying to me in the Hebrew language, 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? It is hard for you to kick against the goads.'UN"I said, 'Who are you, Lord?' "He said, 'I am Jesus, whom you are persecuting.UÃBut arise, and stand on your feet, for I have appeared to you for this purpose: to appoint you a servant and a witness both of the things which you have seen, and of the things which I will reveal to you;UJdelivering you from the people, and from the Gentiles, to whom I send you,UÃto open their eyes, that they may turn from darkness to light and from the power of Satan to God, that they may receive remission of sins and an inheritance among those who are sanctified by faith in me.'UG"Therefore, King Agrippa, I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision,U√but declared first to them of Damascus, at Jerusalem, and throughout all the country of Judea, and also to the Gentiles, that they should repent and turn to God, doing works worthy of repentance.UGFor this reason the Jews seized me in the temple, and tried to kill me.UÆHaving therefore obtained the help that is from God, I stand to this day testifying both to small and great, saying nothing but what the prophets and Moses said would happen,Uîhow the Christ must suffer, and how, by the resurrection of the dead, he would be first to proclaim light both to these people and to the Gentiles."U}As he thus made his defense, Festus said with a loud voice, "Paul, you are crazy! Your great learning is driving you insane!"UjBut he said, "I am not crazy, most excellent Festus, but boldly declare words of truth and reasonableness.U©For the king knows of these things, to whom also I speak freely. For I am persuaded that none of these things is hidden from him, for this has not been done in a corner.UDKing Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe."UWAgrippa said to Paul, "With a little persuasion are you trying to make me a Christian?"UßPaul said, "I pray to God, that whether with little or with much, not only you, but also all that hear me this day, might become such as I am, except for these bonds."UMThe king rose up with the governor, and Bernice, and those who sat with them.UpWhen they had withdrawn, they spoke one to another, saying, "This man does nothing worthy of death or of bonds."U]Agrippa said to Festus, "This man might have been set free if he had not appealed to Caesar."t(NUòWhen it was determined that we should sail for Italy, they delivered Paul and certain other prisoners to a centurion named Julius, of the Augustan band.U§Embarking in a ship of Adramyttium, which was about to sail to places on the coast of Asia, we put to sea; Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica, being with us.UÄThe next day, we touched at Sidon. Julius treated Paul kindly, and gave him permission to go to his friends and refresh himself.U^Putting to sea from there, we sailed under the lee of Cyprus, because the winds were contrary.UgWhen we had sailed across the sea which is off Cilicia and Pamphylia, we came to Myra, a city of Lycia.UYThere the centurion found a ship of Alexandria sailing for Italy, and he put us on board.U®When we had sailed slowly many days, and had come with difficulty opposite Cnidus, the wind not allowing us further, we sailed under the lee of Crete, opposite Salmone.UgWith difficulty sailing along it we came to a certain place called Fair Havens, near the city of Lasea.U{When much time had passed and the voyage was now dangerous, because the Fast had now already gone by, Paul admonished them,Uíand said to them, "Sirs, I perceive that the voyage will be with injury and much loss, not only of the cargo and the ship, but also of our lives."U{But the centurion gave more heed to the master and to the owner of the ship than to those things which were spoken by Paul.U’Because the haven was not suitable to winter in, the majority advised going to sea from there, if by any means they could reach Phoenix, and winter there, which is a port of Crete, looking northeast and southeast.UåWhen the south wind blew softly, supposing that they had obtained their purpose, they weighed anchor and sailed along Crete, close to shore.UPBut before long, a stormy wind beat down from shore, which is called Euroclydon.U_When the ship was caught, and couldn't face the wind, we gave way to it, and were driven along.UiRunning under the lee of a small island called Clauda, we were able, with difficulty, to secure the boat.UæAfter they had hoisted it up, they used cables to help reinforce the ship. Fearing that they would run aground on the Syrtis sand bars, they lowered the sea anchor, and so were driven along.U\As we labored exceedingly with the storm, the next day they began to throw things overboard.UHOn the third day, they threw out the ship's tackle with their own hands.UãWhen neither sun nor stars shone on us for many days, and no small storm pressed on us, all hope that we would be saved was now taken away.U√When they had been long without food, Paul stood up in the middle of them, and said, "Sirs, you should have listened to me, and not have set sail from Crete, and have gotten this injury and loss.U`Now I exhort you to cheer up, for there will be no loss of life among you, but only of the ship.U\For there stood by me this night an angel, belonging to the God whose I am and whom I serve,Uwsaying, 'Don't be afraid, Paul. You must stand before Caesar. Behold, God has granted you all those who sail with you.'U_Therefore, sirs, cheer up! For I believe God, that it will be just as it has been spoken to me.U-But we must run aground on a certain island."U´But when the fourteenth night had come, as we were driven back and forth in the Adriatic Sea, about midnight the sailors surmised that they were drawing near to some land.UzThey took soundings, and found twenty fathoms. After a little while, they took soundings again, and found fifteen fathoms.UtFearing that we would run aground on rocky ground, they let go four anchors from the stern, and wished for daylight.UìAs the sailors were trying to flee out of the ship, and had lowered the boat into 