nt time are not worthy to be compared with the glory which will be revealed toward us.UUFor the creation waits with eager expectation for the children of God to be revealed.UkFor the creation was subjected to vanity, not of its own will, but because of him who subjected it, in hopeUthat the creation itself also will be delivered from the bondage of decay into the liberty of the glory of the children of God.USFor we know that the whole creation groans and travails in pain together until now.U•Not only so, but ourselves also, who have the first fruits of the Spirit, even we ourselves groan within ourselves, waiting for adoption, the redemption of our body.UcFor we were saved in hope, but hope that is seen is not hope. For who hopes for that which he sees?UIBut if we hope for that which we don't see, we wait for it with patience.UπIn the same way, the Spirit also helps our weaknesses, for we don't know how to pray as we ought. But the Spirit himself makes intercession for us with groanings which can't be uttered.U}He who searches the hearts knows what is on the Spirit's mind, because he makes intercession for the saints according to God.UxWe know that all things work together for good for those who love God, to those who are called according to his purpose.UÜFor whom he foreknew, he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son, that he might be the firstborn among many brothers.UWhom he predestined, those he also called. Whom he called, those he also justified. Whom he justified, those he also glorified.USWhat then shall we say about these things? If God is for us, who can be against us?U{He who didn't spare his own Son, but delivered him up for us all, how would he not also with him freely give us all things?ULWho could bring a charge against God's chosen ones? It is God who justifies.UùWho is he who condemns? It is Christ who died, yes rather, who was raised from the dead, who is at the right hand of God, who also makes intercession for us.UâWho shall separate us from the love of Christ? Could oppression, or anguish, or persecution, or famine, or nakedness, or peril, or sword?UpEven as it is written, "For your sake we are killed all day long. We were accounted as sheep for the slaughter."UNNo, in all these things, we are more than conquerors through him who loved us.UÖFor I am persuaded, that neither death, nor life, nor angels, nor principalities, nor things present, nor things to come, nor powers,Uànor height, nor depth, nor any other created thing, will be able to separate us from the love of God, which is in Christ Jesus our Lord.t(NU`I tell the truth in Christ. I am not lying, my conscience testifying with me in the Holy Spirit,U8that I have great sorrow and unceasing pain in my heart.UtFor I could wish that I myself were accursed from Christ for my brothers' sake, my relatives according to the flesh,Uzwho are Israelites; whose is the adoption, the glory, the covenants, the giving of the law, the service, and the promises;Uvof whom are the fathers, and from whom is Christ as concerning the flesh, who is over all, God, blessed forever. Amen.UmBut it is not as though the word of God has come to nothing. For they are not all Israel, that are of Israel.UjNeither, because they are Abraham's seed, are they all children. But, "In Isaac will your seed be called."U|That is, it is not the children of the flesh who are children of God, but the children of the promise are counted as a seed.U^For this is a word of promise, "At the appointed time I will come, and Sarah will have a son."UDNot only so, but Rebecca also conceived by one, by our father Isaac.U†For being not yet born, neither having done anything good or bad, that the purpose of God according to election might stand, not of works, but of him who calls,U7it was said to her, "The elder will serve the younger."U9Even as it is written, "Jacob I loved, but Esau I hated."UKWhat shall we say then? Is there unrighteousness with God? May it never be!UuFor he said to Moses, "I will have mercy on whom I have mercy, and I will have compassion on whom I have compassion."URSo then it is not of him who wills, nor of him who runs, but of God who has mercy.U≤For the Scripture says to Pharaoh, "For this very purpose I caused you to be raised up, that I might show in you my power, and that my name might be proclaimed in all the earth."UISo then, he has mercy on whom he desires, and he hardens whom he desires.UUYou will say then to me, "Why does he still find fault? For who withstands his will?"UÇBut indeed, O man, who are you to reply against God? Will the thing formed ask him who formed it, "Why did you make me like this?"U}Or hasn't the potter a right over the clay, from the same lump to make one part a vessel for honor, and another for dishonor?UÜWhat if God, willing to show his wrath, and to make his power known, endured with much patience vessels of wrath made for destruction,Uqand that he might make known the riches of his glory on vessels of mercy, which he prepared beforehand for glory,ULus, whom he also called, not from the Jews only, but also from the Gentiles?U{As he says also in Hosea, "I will call them 'my people,' which were not my people; and her 'beloved,' who was not beloved."Uä"It will be that in the place where it was said to them, 'You are not my people,' There they will be called 'children of the living God.'"UâIsaiah cries concerning Israel, "If the number of the children of Israel are as the sand of the sea, it is the remnant who will be saved;Uwfor He will finish the work and cut it short in righteousness, because the LORD will make a short work upon the earth."UìAs Isaiah has said before, "Unless the Lord of Armies had left us a seed, we would have become like Sodom, and would have been made like Gomorrah."UñWhat shall we say then? That the Gentiles, who didn't follow after righteousness, attained to righteousness, even the righteousness which is of faith;U^but Israel, following after a law of righteousness, didn't arrive at the law of righteousness.UvWhy? Because they didn't seek it by faith, but as it were by works of the law. They stumbled over the stumbling stone;Uåeven as it is written, "Behold, I lay in Zion a stumbling stone and a rock of offense; and no one who believes in him will be disappointed."t(NUWBrothers, my heart's desire and my prayer to God is for Israel, that they may be saved.UWFor I testify about them that they have a zeal for God, but not according to knowledge.UòFor being ignorant of God's righteousness, and seeking to establish their own righteousness, they didn't subject themselves to the righteousness of God.UTFor Christ is the fulfillment of the law for righteousness to everyone who believes.U_For Moses writes about the righteousness of the law, "The one who does them will live by them."UåBut the righteousness which is of faith says this, "Don't say in your heart, 'Who will ascend into heaven?' (that is, to bring Christ down);UTor, 'Who will descend into the abyss?' (that is, to bring Christ up from the dead.)"U|But what does it say? "The word is near you, in your mouth, and in your heart;" that is, the word of faith, which we preach:Uåthat if you will confess with your mouth that Jesus is Lord, and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.UjFor with the heart, one believes unto righteousness; and with the mouth confession is made unto salvation.UKFor the Scripture says, "Whoever believes in him will not be disappointed."UxFor there is no distinction between Jew and Greek; for the same Lord is Lord of all, and is rich to all who call on him.U?For, "Whoever will call on the name of the Lord will be saved."UúHow then will they call on him in whom they have not believed? How will they believe in him whom they have not heard? How will they hear without a preacher?U∞And how will they preach unless they are sent? As it is written: "How beautiful are the feet of those who preach the Good News of peace, who bring glad tidings of good things!"UbBut they didn't all listen to the glad news. For Isaiah says, "Lord, who has believed our report?"U:So faith comes by hearing, and hearing by the word of God.UÇBut I say, didn't they hear? Yes, most certainly, "Their sound went out into all the earth, their words to the ends of the world."U™But I ask, didn't Israel know? First Moses says, "I will provoke you to jealousy with that which is no nation, with a nation void of understanding I will make you angry."UxIsaiah is very bold, and says, "I was found by those who didn't seek me. I was revealed to those who didn't ask for me."UgBut as to Israel he says, "All day long I stretched out my hands to a disobedient and contrary people."t(NUÜI ask then, did God reject his people? May it never be! For I also am an Israelite, a descendant of Abraham, of the tribe of Benjamin.UèGod didn't reject his people, which he foreknew. Or don't you know what the Scripture says about Elijah? How he pleads with God against Israel:Uv"Lord, they have killed your prophets, they have broken down your altars; and I am left alone, and they seek my life."UrBut how does God answer him? "I have reserved for myself seven thousand men, who have not bowed the knee to Baal."U]Even so then at this present time also there is a remnant according to the election of grace.U£And if by grace, then it is no longer of works; otherwise grace is no longer grace. But if it is of works, it is no longer grace; otherwise work is no longer work.U{What then? That which Israel seeks for, that he didn't obtain, but the chosen ones obtained it, and the rest were hardened.UîAccording as it is written, "God gave them a spirit of stupor, eyes that they should not see, and ears that they should not hear, to this very day."UgDavid says, "Let their table be made a snare, and a trap, a stumbling block, and a retribution to them.UOLet their eyes be darkened, that they may not see. Bow down their back always."UñI ask then, did they stumble that they might fall? May it never be! But by their fall salvation has come to the Gentiles, to provoke them to jealousy.UvNow if their fall is the riches of the world, and their loss the riches of the Gentiles; how much more their fullness?UfFor I speak to you who are Gentiles. Since then as I am an apostle to Gentiles, I glorify my ministry;U\if by any means I may provoke to jealousy those who are my flesh, and may save some of them.UuFor if the rejection of them is the reconciling of the world, what would their acceptance be, but life from the dead?UUIf the first fruit is holy, so is the lump. If the root is holy, so are the branches.U∂But if some of the branches were broken off, and you, being a wild olive, were grafted in among them, and became partaker with them of the root and of the richness of the olive tree;Uodon't boast over the branches. But if you boast, it is not you who support the root, but the root supports you.UJYou will say then, "Branches were broken off, that I might be grafted in."UhTrue; by their unbelief they were broken off, and you stand by your faith. Don't be conceited, but fear;UHfor if God didn't spare the natural branches, neither will he spare you.U™See then the goodness and severity of God. Toward those who fell, severity; but toward you, goodness, if you continue in his goodness; otherwise you also will be cut off.UpThey also, if they don't continue in their unbelief, will be grafted in, for God is able to graft them in again.U·For if you were cut out of that which is by nature a wild olive tree, and were grafted contrary to nature into a good olive tree, how much more will these, which are the natural branches, be grafted into their own olive tree?U“For I don't desire you to be ignorant, brothers, of this mystery, so that you won't be wise in your own conceits, that a partial hardening has happened to Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in,Uëand so all Israel will be saved. Even as it is written, "There will come out of Zion the Deliverer, and he will turn away ungodliness from Jacob.U?This is my covenant to them, when I will take away their sins."U~Concerning the Good News, they are enemies for your sake. But concerning the election, they are beloved for the fathers' sake.U5For the gifts and the calling of God are irrevocable.UcFor as you in time past were disobedient to God, but now have obtained mercy by their disobedience,Uheven so these also have now been disobedient, that by the mercy shown to you they may also obtain mercy.UIFor God has shut up all to disobedience, that he might have mercy on all.UäOh the depth of the riches both of the wisdom and the knowledge of God! How unsearchable are his judgments, and his ways past tracing out!UH"For who has known the mind of the Lord? Or who has been his counselor?"UD"Or who has first given to him, and it will be repaid to him again?"U\For of him, and through him, and to him, are all things. To him be the glory for ever! Amen.t(NUõTherefore I urge you, brothers, by the mercies of God, to present your bodies a living sacrifice, holy, acceptable to God, which is your spiritual service.U¢Don't be conformed to this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind, so that you may prove what is the good, well-pleasing, and perfect will of God.U›For I say, through the grace that was given me, to every man who is among you, not to think of himself more highly than he ought to think; but to think reasonably, as God has apportioned to each person a measure of faith.U_For even as we have many members in one body, and all the members don't have the same function,UUso we, who are many, are one body in Christ, and individually members one of another.UäHaving gifts differing according to the grace that was given to us, if prophecy, let us prophesy according to the proportion of our faith;UQor service, let us give ourselves to service; or he who teaches, to his teaching;Uñor he who exhorts, to his exhorting: he who gives, let him do it with liberality; he who rules, with diligence; he who shows mercy, with cheerfulness.UULet love be without hypocrisy. Abhor that which is evil. Cling to that which is good.UaIn love of the brothers be tenderly affectionate one to another; in honor preferring one another;U>not lagging in diligence; fervent in spirit; serving the Lord;UJrejoicing in hope; enduring in troubles; continuing steadfastly in prayer;U>contributing to the needs of the saints; given to hospitality.U6Bless those who persecute you; bless, and don't curse.U9Rejoice with those who rejoice. Weep with those who weep.UéBe of the same mind one toward another. Don't set your mind on high things, but associate with the humble. Don't be wise in your own conceits.UNRepay no one evil for evil. Respect what is honorable in the sight of all men.UHIf it is possible, as much as it is up to you, be at peace with all men.UëDon't seek revenge yourselves, beloved, but give place to God's wrath. For it is written, "Vengeance belongs to me; I will repay, says the Lord."UåTherefore "If your enemy is hungry, feed him. If he is thirsty, give him a drink; for in doing so, you will heap coals of fire on his head."U7Don't be overcome by evil, but overcome evil with good.t(NUéLet every soul be in subjection to the higher authorities, for there is no authority except from God, and those who exist are ordained by God.UÖTherefore he who resists the authority, withstands the ordinance of God; and those who withstand will receive to themselves judgment.U≠For rulers are not a terror to the good work, but to the evil. Do you desire to have no fear of the authority? Do that which is good, and you will have praise from the same,U∆for he is a servant of God to you for good. But if you do that which is evil, be afraid, for he doesn't bear the sword in vain; for he is a servant of God, an avenger for wrath to him who does evil.UeTherefore you need to be in subjection, not only because of the wrath, but also for conscience' sake.UuFor this reason you also pay taxes, for they are servants of God's service, attending continually on this very thing.UåGive therefore to everyone what you owe: taxes to whom taxes are due; customs to whom customs; respect to whom respect; honor to whom honor.UeOwe no one anything, except to love one another; for he who loves his neighbor has fulfilled the law.T#␀␀For the commandments, "You shall not commit adultery," "You shall not murder," "You shall not steal," "You shall not give false testimony," "You shall not covet," and whatever other commandments there are, are all summed up in this saying, namely, "You shall love your neighbor as yourself."UKLove doesn't harm a neighbor. Love therefore is the fulfillment of the law.UëDo this, knowing the time, that it is already time for you to awaken out of sleep, for salvation is now nearer to us than when we first believed.UÅThe night is far gone, and the day is near. Let's therefore throw off the works of darkness, and let's put on the armor of light.UëLet us walk properly, as in the day; not in reveling and drunkenness, not in sexual promiscuity and lustful acts, and not in strife and jealousy.UUBut put on the Lord Jesus Christ, and make no provision for the flesh, for its lusts.t(NUHNow accept one who is weak in faith, but not for disputes over opinions.UMOne man has faith to eat all things, but he who is weak eats only vegetables.UDon't let him who eats despise him who doesn't eat. Don't let him who doesn't eat judge him who eats, for God has accepted him.UêWho are you who judge another's servant? To his own lord he stands or falls. Yes, he will be made to stand, for God has power to make him stand.UzOne man esteems one day as more important. Another esteems every day alike. Let each man be fully assured in his own mind.U¯He who observes the day, observes it to the Lord; and he who does not observe the day, to the Lord he does not observe it. He who eats, eats to the Lord, for he gives God thanks. He who doesn't eat, to the Lord he doesn't eat, and gives God thanks.U:For none of us lives to himself, and none dies to himself.UvFor if we live, we live to the Lord. Or if we die, we die to the Lord. If therefore we live or die, we are the Lord's.UjFor to this end Christ died, rose, and lived again, that he might be Lord of both the dead and the living.UêBut you, why do you judge your brother? Or you again, why do you despise your brother? For we will all stand before the judgment seat of Christ.UoFor it is written, "'As I live,' says the Lord, 'to me every knee will bow. Every tongue will confess to God.'"U;So then each one of us will give account of himself to God.UöTherefore let's not judge one another any more, but judge this rather, that no man put a stumbling block in his brother's way, or an occasion for falling.UùI know, and am persuaded in the Lord Jesus, that nothing is unclean of itself; except that to him who considers anything to be unclean, to him it is unclean.UÇYet if because of food your brother is grieved, you walk no longer in love. Don't destroy with your food him for whom Christ died.U&Then don't let your good be slandered,Uhfor the Kingdom of God is not eating and drinking, but righteousness, peace, and joy in the Holy Spirit.URFor he who serves Christ in these things is acceptable to God and approved by men.UjSo then, let us follow after things which make for peace, and things by which we may build one another up.UëDon't overthrow God's work for food's sake. All things indeed are clean, however it is evil for that man who creates a stumbling block by eating.UuIt is good to not eat meat, drink wine, nor do anything by which your brother stumbles, is offended, or is made weak.UsDo you have faith? Have it to yourself before God. Happy is he who doesn't judge himself in that which he approves.T6␀␀But he who doubts is condemned if he eats, because it isn't of faith; and whatever is not of faith is sin. (14:24) Now to him who is able to establish you according to my Good News and the preaching of Jesus Christ, according to the revelation of the mystery which has been kept secret through long ages, (14:25) but now is revealed, and by the Scriptures of the prophets, according to the commandment of the eternal God, is made known for obedience of faith to all the nations; (14:26) to the only wise God, through Jesus Christ, to whom be the glory forever! Amen.t(NU\Now we who are strong ought to bear the weaknesses of the weak, and not to please ourselves.UULet each one of us please his neighbor for that which is good, to be building him up.UvFor even Christ didn't please himself. But, as it is written, "The reproaches of those who reproached you fell on me."UúFor whatever things were written before were written for our learning, that through patience and through encouragement of the Scriptures we might have hope.UyNow the God of patience and of encouragement grant you to be of the same mind one with another according to Christ Jesus,U`that with one accord you may with one mouth glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ.UTTherefore accept one another, even as Christ also accepted you, to the glory of God.UêNow I say that Christ has been made a servant of the circumcision for the truth of God, that he might confirm the promises given to the fathers,Uôand that the Gentiles might glorify God for his mercy. As it is written, "Therefore will I give praise to you among the Gentiles, and sing to your name."U8Again he says, "Rejoice, you Gentiles, with his people."UKAgain, "Praise the Lord, all you Gentiles! Let all the peoples praise him."U~Again, Isaiah says, "There will be the root of Jesse, he who arises to rule over the Gentiles; in him the Gentiles will hope."UÉNow may the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing, that you may abound in hope, in the power of the Holy Spirit.UïI myself am also persuaded about you, my brothers, that you yourselves are full of goodness, filled with all knowledge, able also to admonish others.UoBut I