th glory, so that the children of Israel could not look steadfastly on the face of Moses for the glory of his face; which was passing away:U4won't service of the Spirit be with much more glory?UfFor if the service of condemnation has glory, the service of righteousness exceeds much more in glory.UáFor most certainly that which has been made glorious has not been made glorious in this respect, by reason of the glory that surpasses.UWFor if that which passes away was with glory, much more that which remains is in glory.U>Having therefore such a hope, we use great boldness of speech,Uéand not as Moses, who put a veil on his face, that the children of Israel wouldn't look steadfastly on the end of that which was passing away.UíBut their minds were hardened, for until this very day at the reading of the old covenant the same veil remains, because in Christ it passes away.U@But to this day, when Moses is read, a veil lies on their heart.U;But whenever one turns to the Lord, the veil is taken away.UQNow the Lord is the Spirit and where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is liberty.U™But we all, with unveiled face beholding as in a mirror the glory of the Lord, are transformed into the same image from glory to glory, even as from the Lord, the Spirit.t(NURTherefore seeing we have this ministry, even as we obtained mercy, we don't faint.U‡But we have renounced the hidden things of shame, not walking in craftiness, nor handling the word of God deceitfully; but by the manifestation of the truth commending ourselves to every man's conscience in the sight of God.UBEven if our Good News is veiled, it is veiled in those who perish;U±in whom the god of this world has blinded the minds of the unbelieving, that the light of the Good News of the glory of Christ, who is the image of God, should not dawn on them.UhFor we don't preach ourselves, but Christ Jesus as Lord, and ourselves as your servants for Jesus' sake;UØseeing it is God who said, "Light will shine out of darkness," who has shone in our hearts, to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ.U{But we have this treasure in clay vessels, that the exceeding greatness of the power may be of God, and not from ourselves.UMWe are pressed on every side, yet not crushed; perplexed, yet not to despair;U:pursued, yet not forsaken; struck down, yet not destroyed;U|always carrying in the body the putting to death of the Lord Jesus, that the life of Jesus may also be revealed in our body.UFor we who live are always delivered to death for Jesus' sake, that the life also of Jesus may be revealed in our mortal flesh.U+So then death works in us, but life in you.UõBut having the same spirit of faith, according to that which is written, "I believed, and therefore I spoke." We also believe, and therefore also we speak;Ufknowing that he who raised the Lord Jesus will raise us also with Jesus, and will present us with you.UèFor all things are for your sakes, that the grace, being multiplied through the many, may cause the thanksgiving to abound to the glory of God.UkTherefore we don't faint, but though our outward man is decaying, yet our inward man is renewed day by day.UuFor our light affliction, which is for the moment, works for us more and more exceedingly an eternal weight of glory;U≤while we don't look at the things which are seen, but at the things which are not seen. For the things which are seen are temporal, but the things which are not seen are eternal.t(NUíFor we know that if the earthly house of our tent is dissolved, we have a building from God, a house not made with hands, eternal, in the heavens.UdFor most certainly in this we groan, longing to be clothed with our habitation which is from heaven;U7if so be that being clothed we will not be found naked.U≥For indeed we who are in this tent do groan, being burdened; not that we desire to be unclothed, but that we desire to be clothed, that what is mortal may be swallowed up by life.UbNow he who made us for this very thing is God, who also gave to us the down payment of the Spirit.UoTherefore, we are always confident and know that while we are at home in the body, we are absent from the Lord;U#for we walk by faith, not by sight.UrWe are of good courage, I say, and are willing rather to be absent from the body, and to be at home with the Lord.UYTherefore also we make it our aim, whether at home or absent, to be well pleasing to him.U•For we must all be revealed before the judgment seat of Christ; that each one may receive the things in the body, according to what he has done, whether good or bad.UéKnowing therefore the fear of the Lord, we persuade men, but we are revealed to God; and I hope that we are revealed also in your consciences.UƒFor we are not commending ourselves to you again, but speak as giving you occasion of boasting on our behalf, that you may have something to answer those who boast in appearance, and not in heart.UYFor if we are beside ourselves, it is for God. Or if we are of sober mind, it is for you.UgFor the love of Christ constrains us; because we judge thus, that one died for all, therefore all died.U}He died for all, that those who live should no longer live to themselves, but to him who for their sakes died and rose again.UáTherefore we know no one after the flesh from now on. Even though we have known Christ after the flesh, yet now we know him so no more.U|Therefore if anyone is in Christ, he is a new creation. The old things have passed away. Behold, all things have become new.U|But all things are of God, who reconciled us to himself through Jesus Christ, and gave to us the ministry of reconciliation;Uünamely, that God was in Christ reconciling the world to himself, not reckoning to them their trespasses, and having committed to us the word of reconciliation.UåWe are therefore ambassadors on behalf of Christ, as though God were entreating by us: we beg you on behalf of Christ, be reconciled to God.UqFor him who knew no sin he made to be sin on our behalf; so that in him we might become the righteousness of God.t(NUPWorking together, we entreat also that you not receive the grace of God in vain,U§for he says, "At an acceptable time I listened to you, in a day of salvation I helped you." Behold, now is the acceptable time. Behold, now is the day of salvation.UQWe give no occasion of stumbling in anything, that our service may not be blamed,U|but in everything commending ourselves, as servants of God, in great endurance, in afflictions, in hardships, in distresses,UNin beatings, in imprisonments, in riots, in labors, in watchings, in fastings;UYin pureness, in knowledge, in patience, in kindness, in the Holy Spirit, in sincere love,Ukin the word of truth, in the power of God; by the armor of righteousness on the right hand and on the left,URby glory and dishonor, by evil report and good report; as deceivers, and yet true;U[as unknown, and yet well known; as dying, and behold, we live; as punished, and not killed;Utas sorrowful, yet always rejoicing; as poor, yet making many rich; as having nothing, and yet possessing all things.U=Our mouth is open to you, Corinthians. Our heart is enlarged.ULYou are not restricted by us, but you are restricted by your own affections.U@Now in return, I speak as to my children, you also be open wide.UãDon't be unequally yoked with unbelievers, for what fellowship have righteousness and iniquity? Or what fellowship has light with darkness?UYWhat agreement has Christ with Belial? Or what portion has a believer with an unbeliever?U«What agreement has a temple of God with idols? For you are a temple of the living God. Even as God said, "I will dwell in them, and walk in them; and I will be their God, and they will be my people."UtTherefore, "'Come out from among them, and be separate,' says the Lord. 'Touch no unclean thing. I will receive you.UZI will be to you a Father. You will be to me sons and daughters,' says the Lord Almighty."t(NUìHaving therefore these promises, beloved, let us cleanse ourselves from all defilement of flesh and spirit, perfecting holiness in the fear of God.U\Open your hearts to us. We wronged no one. We corrupted no one. We took advantage of no one.UtI say this not to condemn you, for I have said before, that you are in our hearts to die together and live together.UîGreat is my boldness of speech toward you. Great is my boasting on your behalf. I am filled with comfort. I overflow with joy in all our affliction.UêFor even when we had come into Macedonia, our flesh had no relief, but we were afflicted on every side. Fightings were outside. Fear was inside.URNevertheless, he who comforts the lowly, God, comforted us by the coming of Titus;UΩand not by his coming only, but also by the comfort with which he was comforted in you, while he told us of your longing, your mourning, and your zeal for me; so that I rejoiced still more.UôFor though I made you sorry with my letter, I do not regret it, though I did regret it. For I see that my letter made you sorry, though just for a while.U≠I now rejoice, not that you were made sorry, but that you were made sorry to repentance. For you were made sorry in a godly way, that you might suffer loss by us in nothing.UpFor godly sorrow works repentance to salvation, which brings no regret. But the sorrow of the world works death.UÒFor behold, this same thing, that you were made sorry in a godly way, what earnest care it worked in you. Yes, what defense, indignation, fear, longing, zeal, and vengeance! In everything you demonstrated yourselves to be pure in the matter.UƒSo although I wrote to you, I wrote not for his cause that did the wrong, nor for his cause that suffered the wrong, but that your earnest care for us might be revealed in you in the sight of God.UôTherefore we have been comforted. In our comfort we rejoiced the more exceedingly for the joy of Titus, because his spirit has been refreshed by you all.U¬For if in anything I have boasted to him on your behalf, I was not disappointed. But as we spoke all things to you in truth, so our glorying also which I made before Titus was found to be truth.UÑHis affection is more abundantly toward you, while he remembers all of your obedience, how with fear and trembling you received him.UAI rejoice that in everything I am of good courage concerning you.t(NUnMoreover, brothers, we make known to you the grace of God which has been given in the assemblies of Macedonia;UÇhow that in much proof of affliction the abundance of their joy and their deep poverty abounded to the riches of their liberality.UcFor according to their power, I testify, yes and beyond their power, they gave of their own accord,Udbegging us with much entreaty to receive this grace and the fellowship in the service to the saints.UrThis was not as we had hoped, but first they gave their own selves to the Lord, and to us through the will of God.UcSo we urged Titus, that as he made a beginning before, so he would also complete in you this grace.UëBut as you abound in everything, in faith, utterance, knowledge, all earnestness, and in your love to us, see that you also abound in this grace.UtI speak not by way of commandment, but as proving through the earnestness of others the sincerity also of your love.UùFor you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that, though he was rich, yet for your sakes he became poor, that you through his poverty might become rich.UâI give a judgment in this: for this is expedient for you, who were the first to start a year ago, not only to do, but also to be willing.UàBut now complete the doing also, that as there was the readiness to be willing, so there may be the completion also out of your ability.UqFor if the readiness is there, it is acceptable according to what you have, not according to what you don't have.U<For this is not that others may be eased and you distressed,U£but for equality. Your abundance at this present time supplies their lack, that their abundance also may become a supply for your lack; that there may be equality.UgAs it is written, "He who gathered much had nothing left over, and he who gathered little had no lack."UUBut thanks be to God, who puts the same earnest care for you into the heart of Titus.UmFor he indeed accepted our exhortation, but being himself very earnest, he went out to you of his own accord.UmWe have sent together with him the brother whose praise in the Good News is known through all the assemblies.U≠Not only so, but who was also appointed by the assemblies to travel with us in this grace, which is served by us to the glory of the Lord himself, and to show our readiness.UiWe are avoiding this, that any man should blame us concerning this abundance which is administered by us.UdHaving regard for honorable things, not only in the sight of the Lord, but also in the sight of men.U¨We have sent with them our brother, whom we have many times proved earnest in many things, but now much more earnest, by reason of the great confidence which he has in you.UåAs for Titus, he is my partner and fellow worker for you. As for our brothers, they are the apostles of the assemblies, the glory of Christ.UmTherefore show the proof of your love to them in front of the assemblies, and of our boasting on your behalf.t(NUUIt is indeed unnecessary for me to write to you concerning the service to the saints,U´for I know your readiness, of which I boast on your behalf to them of Macedonia, that Achaia has been prepared for a year past. Your zeal has stirred up very many of them.UåBut I have sent the brothers that our boasting on your behalf may not be in vain in this respect, that, just as I said, you may be prepared,U´so that I won't by any means, if there come with me any of Macedonia and find you unprepared, we (to say nothing of you) should be disappointed in this confident boasting.UÔI thought it necessary therefore to entreat the brothers that they would go before to you, and arrange ahead of time the generous gift that you promised before, that the same might be ready as a matter of generosity, and not of greediness.UrRemember this: he who sows sparingly will also reap sparingly. He who sows bountifully will also reap bountifully.UÉLet each man give according as he has determined in his heart; not grudgingly, or under compulsion; for God loves a cheerful giver.UÜAnd God is able to make all grace abound to you, that you, always having all sufficiency in everything, may abound to every good work.UiAs it is written, "He has scattered abroad, he has given to the poor. His righteousness remains forever."UñNow may he who supplies seed to the sower and bread for food, supply and multiply your seed for sowing, and increase the fruits of your righteousness;U_you being enriched in everything to all liberality, which works through us thanksgiving to God.UêFor this service of giving that you perform not only makes up for lack among the saints, but abounds also through many givings of thanks to God;U∆seeing that through the proof given by this service, they glorify God for the obedience of your confession to the Good News of Christ, and for the liberality of your contribution to them and to all;U{while they themselves also, with supplication on your behalf, yearn for you by reason of the exceeding grace of God in you.U.Now thanks be to God for his unspeakable gift!t(NU§Now I Paul, myself, entreat you by the humility and gentleness of Christ; I who in your presence am lowly among you, but being absent am of good courage toward you.U∞Yes, I beg you that I may not, when present, show courage with the confidence with which I intend to be bold against some, who consider us to be walking according to the flesh.UJFor though we walk in the flesh, we don't wage war according to the flesh;Uofor the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh, but mighty before God to the throwing down of strongholds,U£throwing down imaginations and every high thing that is exalted against the knowledge of God, and bringing every thought into captivity to the obedience of Christ;UYand being in readiness to avenge all disobedience, when your obedience will be made full.U“Do you look at things only as they appear in front of your face? If anyone trusts in himself that he is Christ's, let him consider this again with himself, that, even as he is Christ's, so also we are Christ's.U´For though I should boast somewhat abundantly concerning our authority, (which the Lord gave for building you up, and not for casting you down) I will not be disappointed,U@that I may not seem as if I desire to terrify you by my letters.UtFor, "His letters," they say, "are weighty and strong, but his bodily presence is weak, and his speech is despised."UÜLet such a person consider this, that what we are in word by letters when we are absent, such are we also in deed when we are present.U€For we are not bold to number or compare ourselves with some of those who commend themselves. But they themselves, measuring themselves by themselves, and comparing themselves with themselves, are without understanding.U~But we will not boast beyond proper limits, but within the boundaries with which God appointed to us, which reach even to you.UäFor we don't stretch ourselves too much, as though we didn't reach to you. For we came even as far as to you with the Good News of Christ,U§not boasting beyond proper limits in other men's labors, but having hope that as your faith grows, we will be abundantly enlarged by you in our sphere of influence,Uoso as to preach the Good News even to the parts beyond you, not to boast in what someone else has already done.U/But "he who boasts, let him boast in the Lord."UQFor it isn't he who commends himself who is approved, but whom the Lord commends.t(NU[I wish that you would bear with me in a little foolishness, but indeed you do bear with me.UáFor I am jealous over you with a godly jealousy. For I married you to one husband, that I might present you as a pure virgin to Christ.UîBut I am afraid that somehow, as the serpent deceived Eve in his craftiness, so your minds might be corrupted from the simplicity that is in Christ.U‹For if he who comes preaches another Jesus, whom we did not preach, or if you receive a different spirit, which you did not receive, or a different "good news", which you did not accept, you put up with that well enough.U@For I reckon that I am not at all behind the very best apostles.UÜBut though I am unskilled in speech, yet I am not unskilled in knowledge. No, in every way we have been revealed to you in all things.U}Or did I commit a sin in humbling myself that you might be exalted, because I preached to you God's Good News free of charge?UII robbed other assemblies, taking wages from them that I might serve you.UÛWhen I was present with you and was in need, I wasn't a burden on anyone, for the brothers, when they came from Macedonia, supplied the measure of my need. In everything I kept myself from being burdensome to you, and I will continue to do so.UaAs the truth of Christ is in me, no one will stop me from this boasting in the regions of Achaia.U)Why? Because I don't love you? God knows.UïBut what I do, that I will do, that I may cut off occasion from them that desire an occasion, that in which they boast, they may be found even as we.UVFor such men are false apostles, deceitful workers, masquerading as Christ's apostles.U?And no wonder, for even Satan masquerades as an angel of light.UàIt is no great thing therefore if his servants also masquerade as servants of righteousness, whose end will be according to their works.UoI say again, let no one think me foolish. But if so, yet receive me as foolish, that I also may boast a little.UoThat which I speak, I don't speak according to the Lord, but as in foolishness, in this confidence of boasting.U:Seeing that many boast after the flesh, I will also boast.U1For you bear with the foolish gladly, being wise.UòFor you bear with a man, if he brings you into bondage, if he devours you, if he takes you captive, if he exalts himself, if he strikes you on the face.U~I speak by way of disparagement, as though we had been weak. Yet however any is bold (I speak in foolishness), I am bold also.U_Are they Hebrews? So am I. Are they Israelites? So am I. Are they the seed of Abraham? So am I.U¨Are they servants of Christ? (I speak as one beside himself) I am more so; in labors more abundantly, in prisons more abundantly, in stripes above measure, in deaths often.U<Five times from the Jews I received forty stripes minus one.UÉThree times I was beaten with rods. Once I was stoned. Three times I suffered shipwreck. I have been a night and a day in the deep.U’I have been in travels often, perils of rivers, perils of robbers, perils from my countrymen, perils from the Gentiles, perils in the city, perils in the wilderness, perils in the sea, perils among false brothers;Umin labor and travail, in watchings often, in hunger and thirst, in fastings often, and in cold and nakedness.UoBesides those things that are outside, there is that which presses on me daily, anxiety for all the assemblies.U\Who is weak, and I am not weak? Who is caused to stumble, and I don't burn with indignation?UEIf I must boast, I will boast of the things that concern my weakness.UcThe God and Father of the Lord Jesus Christ, he who is blessed forevermore, knows that I don't lie.UhIn Damascus the governor under Aretas the king guarded the city of the Damascenes desiring to arrest me.UOThrough a window I was let down in a basket by the wall, and escaped his hands.t(NUgIt is doubtless not profitable for me to boast. For I will come to visions and revelations of the Lord.U∞I know a man in Christ, fourteen years ago (whether in the body, I don't know, or whether out of the body, I don't know; God knows), such a one caught up into the third heaven.UYI know such a man (whether in the body, or outside of the body, I don't know; God knows),Ukhow he was caught up into Paradise, and heard unspeakable words, which it is not lawful for a man to utter.UeOn behalf of such a one I will boast, but on my own behalf I will not boast, except in my weaknesses.U∂For if I would desire to boast, I will not be foolish; for I will speak the truth. But I refrain, so that no man may think more of me than that which he sees in me, or hears from me.U‹By reason of the exceeding greatness of the revelations, that I should not be exalted excessively, there was given to me a thorn in the flesh, a messenger of Satan to torment me, that I should not be exalted excessively.URConcerning this thing, I begged the Lord three times that it might depart from me.U√He has said to me, "My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness." Most gladly therefore I will rather glory in my weaknesses, that the power of Christ may rest on me.UûTherefore I take pleasure in weaknesses, in injuries, in necessities, in persecutions, in distresses, for Christ's sake. For when I am weak, then am I strong.U≠I have become foolish in boasting. You compelled me, for I ought to have been commended by you, for in nothing was I inferior to the very best apostles, though I am nothing.UkTruly the signs of an apostle were worked among you in all patience, in signs and wonders and mighty works.UõFor what is there in which you were made inferior to the rest of the assemblies, unless it is that I myself was not a burden to you? Forgive me this wrong.UﬂBehold, this is the third time I am ready to come to you, and I will not be a burden to you; for I seek not your possessions, but you. For the children ought not to save up for the parents, but the parents for the children.UiI will most gladly spend and be spent for your souls. If I love you more abundantly, am I loved the less?UZBut be it so, I did not myself burden you. But, being crafty, I caught you with deception.UFDid I take advantage of you by anyone of them whom I have sent to you?UúI exhorted Titus, and I sent the brother with him. Did Titus take any advantage of you? Didn't we walk in the same spirit? Didn't we walk in the same steps?UíAgain, do you think that we are excusing ourselves to you? In the sight of God we speak in Christ. But all things, beloved, are for your edifying.T␀␀For I am afraid that by any means, when I come, I might find you not the way I want to, and that I might be found by you as you don't desire; that by any means there would be strife, jealousy, outbursts of anger, factions, slander, whisperings, proud thoughts, riots;UŸthat again when I come my God would humble me before you, and I would mourn for many of those who have sinned before now, and not repented of the uncleanness and sexual immorality and lustfulness which they committed.t(NUtThis is the third time I am coming to you. "At the mouth of two or three witnesses shall every word be established."UÿI have said beforehand, and I do say beforehand, as when I was present the second time, so now, being absent, I write to those who have sinned before now, and to all the rest, that, if I come again, I will not spare;Ulseeing that you seek a proof of Christ who speaks in me; who toward you is not weak, but is powerful in you.U©For he was crucified through weakness, yet he lives through the power of God. For we also are weak in him, but we will live with him through the power of God toward you.U¥Test your own selves, whether you are in the faith. Test your own selves. Or don't you know as to your own selves, that Jesus Christ is in you?--unless indeed you are disqualified.U:But I hope that you will know that we aren't disqualified.UêNow I pray to God that you do no evil; not that we may appear approved, but that you may do that which is honorable, though we are as reprobate.U;For we can do nothing against the truth, but for the truth.UdFor we rejoice when we are weak and you are strong. And this we also pray for, even your perfecting.U∏For this cause I write these things while absent, that I may not deal sharply when present, according to 