hat kind of a reception we had from you; and how you turned to God from idols, to serve a living and true God,Uqand to wait for his Son from heaven, whom he raised from the dead--Jesus, who delivers us from the wrath to come.t(NUCFor you yourselves know, brothers, our visit to you wasn't in vain,Uúbut having suffered before and been shamefully treated, as you know, at Philippi, we grew bold in our God to tell you the Good News of God in much conflict.UJFor our exhortation is not of error, nor of uncleanness, nor in deception.UçBut even as we have been approved by God to be entrusted with the Good News, so we speak; not as pleasing men, but God, who tests our hearts.UyFor neither were we at any time found using words of flattery, as you know, nor a cloak of covetousness (God is witness),Uznor seeking glory from men (neither from you nor from others), when we might have claimed authority as apostles of Christ.UOBut we were gentle among you, like a nursing mother cherishes her own children.UÆEven so, affectionately longing for you, we were well pleased to impart to you, not the Good News of God only, but also our own souls, because you had become very dear to us.UõFor you remember, brothers, our labor and travail; for working night and day, that we might not burden any of you, we preached to you the Good News of God.UoYou are witnesses with God, how holy, righteously, and blamelessly we behaved ourselves toward you who believe.UfAs you know, we exhorted, comforted, and implored every one of you, as a father does his own children,U^to the end that you should walk worthily of God, who calls you into his own Kingdom and glory.UÁFor this cause we also thank God without ceasing, that, when you received from us the word of the message of God, you accepted it not as the word of men, but, as it is in truth, the word of God, which also works in you who believe.U¿For you, brothers, became imitators of the assemblies of God which are in Judea in Christ Jesus; for you also suffered the same things from your own countrymen, even as they did from the Jews;U|who killed both the Lord Jesus and their own prophets, and drove us out, and didn't please God, and are contrary to all men;Uâforbidding us to speak to the Gentiles that they may be saved; to fill up their sins always. But wrath has come on them to the uttermost.UåBut we, brothers, being bereaved of you for a short season, in presence, not in heart, tried even harder to see your face with great desire,UYbecause we wanted to come to you--indeed, I, Paul, once and again--but Satan hindered us.UlFor what is our hope, or joy, or crown of rejoicing? Isn't it even you, before our Lord Jesus at his coming?U"For you are our glory and our joy.t(NUfTherefore, when we couldn't stand it any longer, we thought it good to be left behind at Athens alone,Uáand sent Timothy, our brother and God's servant in the Good News of Christ, to establish you, and to comfort you concerning your faith;U[that no one be moved by these afflictions. For you know that we are appointed to this task.UÜFor most certainly, when we were with you, we told you beforehand that we are to suffer affliction, even as it happened, and you know.UΩFor this cause I also, when I couldn't stand it any longer, sent that I might know your faith, for fear that by any means the tempter had tempted you, and our labor would have been in vain.U¡But when Timothy came just now to us from you, and brought us glad news of your faith and love, and that you have good memories of us always, longing to see us, even as we also long to see you;Ukfor this cause, brothers, we were comforted over you in all our distress and affliction through your faith.U/For now we live, if you stand fast in the Lord.U~For what thanksgiving can we render again to God for you, for all the joy with which we rejoice for your sakes before our God;Uqnight and day praying exceedingly that we may see your face, and may perfect that which is lacking in your faith?UUNow may our God and Father himself, and our Lord Jesus Christ, direct our way to you;U{and the Lord make you to increase and abound in love one toward another, and toward all men, even as we also do toward you,Uçto the end he may establish your hearts blameless in holiness before our God and Father, at the coming of our Lord Jesus with all his saints.t(NU•Finally then, brothers, we beg and exhort you in the Lord Jesus, that as you received from us how you ought to walk and to please God, that you abound more and more.UBFor you know what instructions we gave you through the Lord Jesus.UZFor this is the will of God: your sanctification, that you abstain from sexual immorality,U_that each one of you know how to possess himself of his own vessel in sanctification and honor,UDnot in the passion of lust, even as the Gentiles who don't know God;UØthat no one should take advantage of and wrong a brother or sister in this matter; because the Lord is an avenger in all these things, as also we forewarned you and testified.U=For God called us not for uncleanness, but in sanctification.UeTherefore he who rejects this doesn't reject man, but God, who has also given his Holy Spirit to you.UÄBut concerning brotherly love, you have no need that one write to you. For you yourselves are taught by God to love one another,UÇfor indeed you do it toward all the brothers who are in all Macedonia. But we exhort you, brothers, that you abound more and more;Uëand that you make it your ambition to lead a quiet life, and to do your own business, and to work with your own hands, even as we instructed you;UVthat you may walk properly toward those who are outside, and may have need of nothing.UíBut we don't want you to be ignorant, brothers, concerning those who have fallen asleep, so that you don't grieve like the rest, who have no hope.UxFor if we believe that Jesus died and rose again, even so God will bring with him those who have fallen asleep in Jesus.U°For this we tell you by the word of the Lord, that we who