t day.UüTo this end we also pray always for you, that our God may count you worthy of your calling, and fulfill every desire of goodness and work of faith, with power;UÖthat the name of our Lord Jesus may be glorified in you, and you in him, according to the grace of our God and the Lord Jesus Christ.t(NUlNow, brothers, concerning the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ, and our gathering together to him, we ask youUönot to be quickly shaken in your mind, nor yet be troubled, either by spirit, or by word, or by letter as from us, saying that the day of Christ had come.UêLet no one deceive you in any way. For it will not be, unless the departure comes first, and the man of sin is revealed, the son of destruction,Uûhe who opposes and exalts himself against all that is called God or that is worshiped; so that he sits as God in the temple of God, setting himself up as God.ULDon't you remember that, when I was still with you, I told you these things?U[Now you know what is restraining him, to the end that he may be revealed in his own season.UtFor the mystery of lawlessness already works. Only there is one who restrains now, until he is taken out of the way.UåThen the lawless one will be revealed, whom the Lord will kill with the breath of his mouth, and destroy by the manifestation of his coming;Ueeven he whose coming is according to the working of Satan with all power and signs and lying wonders,Uèand with all deception of wickedness for those who are being lost, because they didn't receive the love of the truth, that they might be saved.USBecause of this, God sends them a working of error, that they should believe a lie;U`that they all might be judged who didn't believe the truth, but had pleasure in unrighteousness.U«But we are bound to always give thanks to God for you, brothers loved by the Lord, because God chose you from the beginning for salvation through sanctification of the Spirit and belief in the truth;Ufto which he called you through our Good News, for the obtaining of the glory of our Lord Jesus Christ.UrSo then, brothers, stand firm, and hold the traditions which you were taught by us, whether by word, or by letter.U|Now our Lord Jesus Christ himself, and God our Father, who loved us and gave us eternal comfort and good hope through grace,UBcomfort your hearts and establish you in every good work and word.t(NUuFinally, brothers, pray for us, that the word of the Lord may spread rapidly and be glorified, even as also with you;UTand that we may be delivered from unreasonable and evil men; for not all have faith.URBut the Lord is faithful, who will establish you, and guard you from the evil one.UbWe have confidence in the Lord concerning you, that you both do and will do the things we command.UVMay the Lord direct your hearts into the love of God, and into the patience of Christ.UƒNow we command you, brothers, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ, that you withdraw yourselves from every brother who walks in rebellion, and not after the tradition which they received from us.U`For you know how you ought to imitate us. For we didn't behave ourselves rebelliously among you,Uñneither did we eat bread from anyone's hand without paying for it, but in labor and travail worked night and day, that we might not burden any of you;Uinot because we don't have the right, but to make ourselves an example to you, that you should imitate us.UfFor even when we were with you, we commanded you this: "If anyone will not work, neither let him eat."U_For we hear of some who walk among you in rebellion, who don't work at all, but are busybodies.UÉNow those who are that way, we command and exhort in the Lord Jesus Christ, that with quietness they work, and eat their own bread.U0But you, brothers, don't be weary in doing well.UÖIf any man doesn't obey our word in this letter, note that man, that you have no company with him, to the end that he may be ashamed.U;Don't count him as an enemy, but admonish him as a brother.UdNow may the Lord of peace himself give you peace at all times in all ways. The Lord be with you all.UcThe greeting of me, Paul, with my own hand, which is the sign in every letter: this is how I write.U9The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all. Amen.ttq6(U	1 Timothy(NUkPaul, an apostle of Christ Jesus according to the commandment of God our Savior, and Christ Jesus our hope;Ukto Timothy, my true child in faith: Grace, mercy, and peace, from God our Father and Christ Jesus our Lord.UÖAs I urged you when I was going into Macedonia, stay at Ephesus that you might command certain men not to teach a different doctrine,UÉneither to pay attention to myths and endless genealogies, which cause disputes, rather than God's stewardship, which is in faith--Udbut the goal of this command is love, out of a pure heart and a good conscience and unfeigned faith;URfrom which things some, having missed the mark, have turned aside to vain talking;Uvdesiring to be teachers of the law, though they understand neither what they say, nor about what they strongly affirm.U<But we know that the law is good, if a man uses it lawfully,U›as knowing this, that law is not made for a righteous man, but for the lawless and insubordinate, for the ungodly and sinners, for the unholy and profane, for murderers of fathers and murderers of mothers, for manslayers,Uèfor the sexually immoral, for homosexuals, for slave-traders, for liars, for perjurers, and for any other thing contrary to the sound doctrine;U\according to the Good News of the glory of the blessed God, which was committed to my trust.UpAnd I thank him who enabled me, Christ Jesus our Lord, because he counted me faithful, appointing me to service;UÉalthough I was before a blasphemer, a persecutor, and insolent. However, I obtained mercy, because I did it ignorantly in unbelief.UXThe grace of our Lord abounded exceedingly with faith and love which is in Christ Jesus.UThe saying is faithful and worthy of all acceptance, that Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners; of whom I am chief.U≥However, for this cause I obtained mercy, that in me first, Jesus Christ might display all his patience, for an example of those who were going to believe in him for eternal life.UrNow to the King eternal, immortal, invisible, to God who alone is wise, be honor and glory forever and ever. Amen.UïThis instruction I commit to you, my child Timothy, according to the prophecies which led the way to you, that by them you may wage the good warfare;Uiholding faith and a good conscience; which some having thrust away made a shipwreck concerning the faith;Ujof whom is Hymenaeus and Alexander; whom I delivered to Satan, that they might be taught not to blaspheme.t(NUuI exhort therefore, first of all, that petitions, prayers, intercessions, and givings of thanks, be made for all men:Utfor kings and all who are in high places; that we may lead a tranquil and quiet life in all godliness and reverence.U?For this is good and acceptable in the sight of God our Savior;UKwho desires all people to be saved and come to full knowledge of the truth.UQFor there is one God, and one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus,UEwho gave himself as a ransom for all; the testimony in its own times;Uèto which I was appointed a preacher and an apostle (I am telling the truth in Christ, not lying), a teacher of the Gentiles in faith and truth.UfI desire therefore that the men in every place pray, lifting up holy hands without anger and doubting.U¢In the same way, that women also adorn themselves in decent clothing, with modesty and propriety; not just with braided hair, gold, pearls, or expensive clothing;U?but (which becomes women professing godliness) with good works.U3Let a woman learn in quietness with all subjection.UbBut I don't permit a woman to teach, nor to exercise authority over a man, but to be in quietness.U$For Adam was first formed, then Eve.URAdam wasn't deceived, but the woman, being deceived, has fallen into disobedience;Urbut she will be