ere also once foolish, disobedient, deceived, serving various lusts and pleasures, living in malice and envy, hateful, and hating one another.UMBut when the kindness of God our Savior and his love toward mankind appeared,U§not by works of righteousness, which we did ourselves, but according to his mercy, he saved us, through the washing of regeneration and renewing by the Holy Spirit,UAwhom he poured out on us richly, through Jesus Christ our Savior;Uathat, being justified by his grace, we might be made heirs according to the hope of eternal life.U“This saying is faithful, and concerning these things I desire that you affirm confidently, so that those who have believed God may be careful to maintain good works. These things are good and profitable to men;Usbut shun foolish questionings, genealogies, strife, and disputes about the law; for they are unprofitable and vain.U6Avoid a factious man after a first and second warning;UEknowing that such a one is perverted, and sins, being self-condemned.UwWhen I send Artemas to you, or Tychicus, be diligent to come to me to Nicopolis, for I have determined to winter there.UdSend Zenas, the lawyer, and Apollos on their journey speedily, that nothing may be lacking for them.UeLet our people also learn to maintain good works for necessary uses, that they may not be unfruitful.U]All who are with me greet you. Greet those who love us in faith. Grace be with you all. Amen.ttq9UPhilemon(NUbPaul, a prisoner of Christ Jesus, and Timothy our brother, to Philemon, our beloved fellow worker,U[to the beloved Apphia, to Archippus, our fellow soldier, and to the assembly in your house:UEGrace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.U;I thank my God always, making mention of you in my prayers,Ughearing of your love, and of the faith which you have toward the Lord Jesus, and toward all the saints;U|that the fellowship of your faith may become effective, in the knowledge of every good thing which is in us in Christ Jesus.UyFor we have much joy and comfort in your love, because the hearts of the saints have been refreshed through you, brother.UYTherefore, though I have all boldness in Christ to command you that which is appropriate,Ujyet for love's sake I rather beg, being such a one as Paul, the aged, but also a prisoner of Jesus Christ.UPI beg you for my child, whom I have become the father of in my chains, Onesimus,U@who once was useless to you, but now is useful to you and to me.UDI am sending him back. Therefore receive him, that is, my own heart,Uewhom I desired to keep with me, that on your behalf he might serve me in my chains for the Good News.UxBut I was willing to do nothing without your consent, that your goodness would not be as of necessity, but of free will.U]For perhaps he was therefore separated from you for a while, that you would have him forever,Uêno longer as a slave, but more than a slave, a beloved brother, especially to me, but how much rather to you, both in the flesh and in the Lord.UDIf then you count me a partner, receive him as you would receive me.UOBut if he has wronged you at all, or owes you anything, put that to my account.U|I, Paul, write this with my own hand: I will repay it (not to mention to you that you owe to me even your own self besides).UQYes, brother, let me have joy from you in the Lord. Refresh my heart in the Lord.UeHaving confidence in your obedience, I write to you, knowing that you will do even beyond what I say.UbAlso, prepare a guest room for me, for I hope that through your prayers I will be restored to you.U9Epaphras, my fellow prisoner in Christ Jesus, greets you,U<as do Mark, Aristarchus, Demas, and Luke, my fellow workers.U=The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit. Amen.tÜq:(UHebrews(NUeGod, having in the past spoken to the fathers through the prophets at many times and in various ways,UÅhas at the end of these days spoken to us by his Son, whom he appointed heir of all things, through whom also he made the worlds.U„His Son is the radiance of his glory, the very image of his substance, and upholding all things by the word of his power, when he had by himself made purification for our sins, sat down on the right hand of the Majesty on high;Ughaving become so much better than the angels, as he has inherited a more excellent name than they have.U´For to which of the angels did he say at any time,  "You are my Son. Today have I become your father?" and again,  "I will be to him a Father, and he will be to me a Son?"UgAgain, when he brings in the firstborn into the world he says, "Let all the angels of God worship him."UVOf the angels he says, "Who makes his angels winds, and his servants a flame of fire."U|But of the Son he says, "Your throne, O God, is forever and ever. The scepter of uprightness is the scepter of your Kingdom.UâYou have loved righteousness, and hated iniquity; therefore God, your God, has anointed you with the oil of gladness above your fellows."UmAnd, "You, Lord, in the beginning, laid the foundation of the earth. The heavens are the works of your hands.UOThey will perish, but you continue. They all will grow old like a garment does.UnAs a mantle, you will roll them up, and they will be changed; but you are the same. Your years will not fail."U~But which of the angels has he told at any time, "Sit at my right hand, until I make your enemies the footstool of your feet?"UiAren't they all serving spirits, sent out to do service for the sake of those who will inherit salvation?t(NUfTherefore we ought to pay greater attention to the things that were heard, lest perhaps we drift away.U|For if the word spoken through angels proved steadfast, and every transgression and disobedience received a just recompense;Uñhow will we escape if we neglect so great a salvation--which at the first having been spoken through the Lord, was confirmed to us by those who heard;UêGod also testifying with them, both by signs and wonders, by various works of power, and by gifts of the