rcy, and may find grace for help in time of need.t(NUöFor every high priest, being taken from among men, is appointed for men in things pertaining to God, that he may offer both gifts and sacrifices for sins.UÇThe high priest can deal gently with those who are ignorant and going astray, because he himself is also surrounded with weakness.UZBecause of this, he must offer sacrifices for sins for the people, as well as for himself.UQNobody takes this honor on himself, but he is called by God, just like Aaron was.UëSo also Christ didn't glorify himself to be made a high priest, but it was he who said to him, "You are my Son. Today I have become your father."U]As he says also in another place, "You are a priest forever, after the order of Melchizedek."U∏He, in the days of his flesh, having offered up prayers and petitions with strong crying and tears to him who was able to save him from death, and having been heard for his godly fear,UKthough he was a Son, yet learned obedience by the things which he suffered.UaHaving been made perfect, he became to all of those who obey him the author of eternal salvation,U:named by God a high priest after the order of Melchizedek.UcAbout him we have many words to say, and hard to interpret, seeing you have become dull of hearing.UŒFor when by reason of the time you ought to be teachers, you again need to have someone teach you the rudiments of the first principles of the oracles of God. You have come to need milk, and not solid food.UaFor everyone who lives on milk is not experienced in the word of righteousness, for he is a baby.UzBut solid food is for those who are full grown, who by reason of use have their senses exercised to discern good and evil.t(NU≤Therefore leaving the doctrine of the first principles of Christ, let us press on to perfection--not laying again a foundation of repentance from dead works, of faith toward God,Uiof the teaching of baptisms, of laying on of hands, of resurrection of the dead, and of eternal judgment.U This will we do, if God permits.U{For concerning those who were once enlightened and tasted of the heavenly gift, and were made partakers of the Holy Spirit,UCand tasted the good word of God, and the powers of the age to come,Uõand then fell away, it is impossible to renew them again to repentance; seeing they crucify the Son of God for themselves again, and put him to open shame.U•For the land which has drunk the rain that comes often on it, and brings forth a crop suitable for them for whose sake it is also tilled, receives blessing from God;Uebut if it bears thorns and thistles, it is rejected and near being cursed, whose end is to be burned.U}But, beloved, we are persuaded of better things for you, and things that accompany salvation, even though we speak like this.U•For God is not unrighteous, so as to forget your work and the labor of love which you showed toward his name, in that you served the saints, and still do serve them.UcWe desire that each one of you may show the same diligence to the fullness of hope even to the end,Uithat you won't be sluggish, but imitators of those who through faith and patience inherited the promises.UbFor when God made a promise to Abraham, since he could swear by none greater, he swore by himself,UPsaying, "Surely blessing I will bless you, and multiplying I will multiply you."U8Thus, having patiently endured, he obtained the promise.UiFor men indeed swear by a greater one, and in every dispute of theirs the oath is final for confirmation.UèIn this way God, being determined to show more abundantly to the heirs of the promise the immutability of his counsel, interposed with an oath;U¨that by two immutable things, in which it is impossible for God to lie, we may have a strong encouragement, who have fled for refuge to take hold of the hope set before us.U{This hope we have as an anchor of the soul, a hope both sure and steadfast and entering into that which is within the veil;Uowhere as a forerunner Jesus entered for us, having become a high priest forever after the order of Melchizedek.t(NUàFor this Melchizedek, king of Salem, priest of God Most High, who met Abraham returning from the slaughter of the kings and blessed him,Uùto whom also Abraham divided a tenth part of all (being first, by interpretation, king of righteousness, and then also king of Salem, which is king of peace;U°without father, without mother, without genealogy, having neither beginning of days nor end of life, but made like the Son of God), remains a priest continually.UnNow consider how great this man was, to whom even Abraham, the patriarch, gave a tenth out of the best spoils.U‘They indeed of the sons of Levi who receive the priest's office have a commandment to take tithes of the people according to the law, that is, of their brothers, though these have come out of the body of Abraham,U{but he whose genealogy is not counted from them has accepted tithes from Abraham, and has blessed him who has the promises.U=But without any dispute the lesser is blessed by the greater.UhHere people who die receive tithes, but there one receives tithes of whom it is testified that he lives.UPWe can say that through Abraham even Levi, who receives tithes, has paid tithes,UBfor he was yet in the body of his father when Melchizedek met him.UÒNow if there was perfection through the Levitical priesthood (for under it the people have received the law), what further need was there for another priest to arise after the order of Melchizedek, and not be called after the order of Aaron?UVFor the priesthood being changed, there is of necessity a change made also in the law.UmFor he of whom these things are said belongs to another tribe, from which no one has officiated at the altar.UuFor it is evident that our Lord has sprung out of Judah, about which tribe Moses spoke nothing concerning priesthood.UfThis is yet more abundantly evident, if after the likeness of Melchizedek there arises another priest,Ufwho has been made, not after the law of a fleshly commandment, but after the power of an endless life:UWfor it is testified, "You are a priest forever, according to the order of Melchizedek."U\For there is an annulling of a foregoing commandment because of its weakness and uselessnessUj(for the law made nothing perfect), and a bringing in of a better hope, through which we draw near to God.U@Inasmuch as he was not made priest without the taking of an oathUÿ(for they indeed have been made priests without an oath), but he with an oath by him that says of him, "The Lord swore and will not change his mind, 'You are a priest forever, according to the order of Melchizedek.'"UABy so much, Jesus has become the collateral of a better covenant.UYMany, indeed, have been made priests, because they are hindered from continuing by death.UBBut he, because he lives forever, has his priesthood unchangeable.UñTherefore he is also able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, seeing that he lives forever to make intercession for them.UÄFor such a high priest was fitting for us: holy, guiltless, undefiled, separated from sinners, and made higher than the heavens;Uøwho doesn't need, like those high priests, to offer up sacrifices daily, first for his own sins, and then for the sins of the people. For he did this once for all, when he offered up himself.UúFor the law appoints men as high priests who have weakness, but the word of the oath which came after the law appoints a Son forever who has been perfected.t(NU¶Now in the things which we are saying, the main point is this. We have such a high priest, who sat down on the right hand of the throne of the Majesty in the heavens,UXa servant of the sanctuary, and of the true tabernacle, which the Lord pitched, not man.UîFor every high priest is appointed to offer both gifts and sacrifices. Therefore it is necessary that this high priest also have something to offer.U|For if he were on earth, he would not be a priest at all, seeing there are priests who offer the gifts according to the law;UÎwho serve a copy and shadow of the heavenly things, even as Moses was warned by God when he was about to make the tabernacle, for he said, "See, you shall make everything according to the pattern that was shown to you on the mountain."UûBut now he has obtained a more excellent ministry, by so much as he is also the mediator of a better covenant, which on better promises has been given as law.UaFor if that first covenant had been faultless, then no place would have been sought for a second.U§For finding fault with them, he said, "Behold, the days come," says the Lord, "that I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel and with the house of Judah;U›not according to the covenant that I made with their fathers, in the day that I took them by the hand to lead them out of the land of Egypt; for they didn't continue in my covenant, and I disregarded them," says the Lord.U„"For this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel. After those days," says the Lord; "I will put my laws into their mind, I will also write them on their heart. I will be their God, and they will be my people.U´They will not teach every man his fellow citizen, and every man his brother, saying, 'Know the Lord,' for all will know me, from the least of them to the greatest of them.UgFor I will be merciful to their unrighteousness. I will remember their sins and lawless deeds no more."UÜIn that he says, "A new covenant," he has made the first old. But that which is becoming old and grows aged is near to vanishing away.t(NU^Now indeed even the first covenant had ordinances of divine service, and an earthly sanctuary.UÉFor a tabernacle was prepared. In the first part were the lampstand, the table, and the show bread; which is called the Holy Place.ULAfter the second veil was the tabernacle which is called the Holy of Holies,U≈having a golden altar of incense, and the ark of the covenant overlaid on all sides with gold, in which was a golden pot holding the manna, Aaron's rod that budded, and the tablets of the covenant;Ujand above it cherubim of glory overshadowing the mercy seat, of which things we can't speak now in detail.UÄNow these things having been thus prepared, the priests go in continually into the first tabernacle, accomplishing the services,Uébut into the second the high priest alone, once in the year, not without blood, which he offers for himself, and for the errors of the people.UáThe Holy Spirit is indicating this, that the way into the Holy Place wasn't yet revealed while the first tabernacle was still standing;Uùwhich is a symbol of the present age, where gifts and sacrifices are offered that are incapable, concerning the conscience, of making the worshipper perfect;Upbeing only (with meats and drinks and various washings) fleshly ordinances, imposed until a time of reformation.UÆBut Christ having come as a high priest of the coming good things, through the greater and more perfect tabernacle, not made with hands, that is to say, not of this creation,Uönor yet through the blood of goats and calves, but through his own blood, entered in once for all into the Holy Place, having obtained eternal redemption.UéFor if the blood of goats and bulls, and the ashes of a heifer sprinkling those who have been defiled, sanctify to the cleanness of the flesh:UØhow much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered himself without blemish to God, cleanse your conscience from dead works to serve the living God?UÒFor this reason he is the mediator of a new covenant, since a death has occurred for the redemption of the transgressions that were under the first covenant, that those who have been called may receive the promise of the eternal inheritance.U`For where a last will and testament is, there must of necessity be the death of him who made it.UgFor a will is in force where there has been death, for it is never in force while he who made it lives.UGTherefore even the first covenant has not been dedicated without blood.UÈFor when every commandment had been spoken by Moses to all the people according to the law, he took the blood of the calves and the goats, with water and scarlet wool and hyssop, and sprinkled both the book itself and all the people,UHsaying, "This is the blood of the covenant which God has commanded you."UgMoreover he sprinkled the tabernacle and all the vessels of the ministry in like manner with the blood.UwAccording to the law, nearly everything is cleansed with blood, and apart from shedding of blood there is no remission.U¨It was necessary therefore that the copies of the things in the heavens should be cleansed with these; but the heavenly things themselves with better sacrifices than these.UßFor Christ hasn't entered into holy places made with hands, which are representations of the true, but into heaven itself, now to appear in the presence of God for us;U~nor yet that he should offer himself often, as the high priest enters into the holy place year by year with blood not his own,U≠or else he must have suffered often since the foundation of the world. But now once at the end of the ages, he has been revealed to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself.UJInasmuch as it is appointed for men to die once, and after this, judgment,U¢so Christ also, having been offered once to bear the sins of many, will appear a second time, without sin, to those who are eagerly waiting for him for salvation.t(NUƒFor the law, having a shadow of the good to come, not the very image of the things, can never with the same sacrifices year by year, which they offer continually, make perfect those who draw near.UíOr else wouldn't they have ceased to be offered, because the worshippers, having been once cleansed, would have had no more consciousness of sins?U9But in those sacrifices there is yearly reminder of sins.UMFor it is impossible that the blood of bulls and goats should take away sins.U{Therefore when he comes into the world, he says, "Sacrifice and offering you didn't desire, but you prepared a body for me;UDYou had no pleasure in whole burnt offerings and sacrifices for sin.UkThen I said, 'Behold, I have come (in the scroll of the book it is written of me) to do your will, O God.'"UæPreviously saying, "Sacrifices and offerings and whole burnt offerings and sacrifices for sin you didn't desire, neither had pleasure in them" (those which are offered according to the law),Usthen he has said, "Behold, I have come to do your will." He takes away the first, that he may establish the second,Udby which will we have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.UuEvery priest indeed stands day by day serving and often offering the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins,U^but he, when he had offered one sacrifice for sins forever, sat down on the right hand of God;ULfrom that time waiting until his enemies are made the footstool of his feet.ULFor by one offering he has perfected forever those who are being sanctified.U7The Holy Spirit also testifies to us, for after saying,UÆ"This is the covenant that I will make with them: 'After those days,' says the Lord, 'I will put my laws on their heart, I will also write them on their mind;'" then he says,U:"I will remember their sins and their iniquities no more."UCNow where remission of these is, there is no more offering for sin.UXHaving therefore, brothers, boldness to enter into the holy place by the blood of Jesus,Uhby the way which he dedicated for us, a new and living way, through the veil, that is to say, his flesh;U0and having a great priest over the house of God,Uòlet's draw near with a true heart in fullness of faith, having our hearts sprinkled from an evil conscience, and having our body washed with pure water,U^let us hold fast the confession of our hope without wavering; for he who promised is faithful.UBLet us consider how to provoke one another to love and good works,Uïnot forsaking our own assembling together, as the custom of some is, but exhorting one another; and so much the more, as you see the Day approaching.UvFor if we sin willfully after we have received the knowledge of the truth, there remains no more a sacrifice for sins,Ujbut a certain fearful expectation of judgment, and a fierceness of fire which will devour the adversaries.U^A man who disregards Moses' law dies without compassion on the word of two or three witnesses.UÓHow much worse punishment, do you think, will he be judged worthy of, who has trodden under foot the Son of God, and has counted the blood of the covenant with which he was sanctified an unholy thing, and has insulted the Spirit of grace?U|For we know him who said, "Vengeance belongs to me," says the Lord, "I will repay." Again, "The Lord will judge his people."U?It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God.UqBut remember the former days, in which, after you were enlightened, you endured a great struggle with sufferings;Uxpartly, being exposed to both reproaches and oppressions; and partly, becoming partakers with those who were treated so.U∆For you both had compassion on me in my chains, and joyfully accepted the plundering of your possessions, knowing that you have for yourselves a better possession and an enduring one in the heavens.UCTherefore don't throw away your boldness, which has a great reward.UYFor you need endurance so that, having done the will of God, you may receive the promise.UC"In a very little while, he who comes will come, and will not wait.UZBut the righteous will live by faith. If he shrinks back, my soul has no pleasure in him."UnBut we are not of those who shrink back to destruction, but of those who have faith to the saving of the soul.t(NUENow faith is assurance of things hoped for, proof of things not seen.U+For by this, the elders obtained testimony.UïBy faith, we understand that the universe has been framed by the word of God, so that what is seen has not been made out of things which are visible.U›By faith, Abel offered to God a more excellent sacrifice than Cain, through which he had testimony given to him that he was righteous, God testifying with respect to his gifts; and through it he, being dead, still speaks.U‘By faith, Enoch was taken away, so that he wouldn't see death, and he was not found, because God translated him. For he has had testimony given to him that before his translation he had been well pleasing to God.U†Without faith it is impossible to be well pleasing to him, for he who comes to God must believe that he exists, and that he is a rewarder of those who seek him.U„By faith, Noah, being warned about things not yet seen, moved with godly fear, prepared a ship for the saving of his house, through which he condemned the world, and became heir of the righteousness which is according to faith.UòBy faith, Abraham, when he was called, obeyed to go out to the place which he was to receive for an inheritance. He went out, not knowing where he went.U°By faith, he lived as an alien in the land of promise, as in a land not his own, dwelling in tents, with Isaac and Jacob, the heirs with him of the same promise.UUFor he looked for the city which has the foundations, whose builder and maker is God.UïBy faith, even Sarah herself received power to conceive, and she bore a child when she was past age, since she counted him faithful who had promised.U§Therefore as many as the stars of the sky in multitude, and as innumerable as the sand which is by the sea shore, were fathered by one man, and him as good as dead.UµThese all died in faith, not having received the promises, but having seen them and embraced them from afar, and having confessed that they were strangers and pilgrims on the earth.UYFor those who say such things make it clear that they are seeking a country of their own.UuIf indeed they had been thinking of that country from which they went out, they would have had enough time to return.U°But now they desire a better country, that is, a heavenly one. Therefore God is not ashamed of them, to be called their God, for he has prepared a city for them.UÖBy faith, Abraham, being tested, offered up Isaac. Yes, he who had gladly received the promises was offering up his one and only son;UAeven he to whom it was said, "In Isaac will your seed be called;"U~concluding that God is able to raise up even from the dead. Figuratively speaking, he also did receive him back from the dead.UGBy faith, Isaac blessed Jacob and Esau, even concerning things to come.UwBy faith, Jacob, when he was dying, blessed each of the sons of Joseph, and worshiped, leaning on the top of his staff.UçBy faith, Joseph, when his end was near, made mention of the departure of the children of Israel; and gave instructions concerning his bones.U≤By faith, Moses, when he was born, was hidden for three months by his parents, because they saw that he was a beautiful child, and they were not afraid of the king's commandment.UZBy faith, Moses, when he had grown up, refused to be called the son of Pharaoh's daughter,Uhchoosing rather to share ill treatment with God's people, than to enjoy the pleasures of sin for a time;Ujaccounting the reproach of Christ greater riches than the treasures of Egypt; for he looked to the reward.UkBy faith, he left Egypt, not fearing the wrath of the king; for he endured, as seeing him who is invisible.U{By faith, he kept the Passover, and the sprinkling of the blood, that the destroyer of the firstborn should not touch them.UtBy faith, they passed through the Red Sea as on dry land. When the Egyptians tried to do so, they were swallowed up.UWBy faith, the walls of Jericho fell down, after they had been encircled for seven days.UrBy faith, Rahab the prostitute, didn't perish with those who were disobedient, having received the spies in peace.UÄWhat more shall I say? For the time would fail me if I told of Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, David, Samuel, and the prophets;Unwho, through faith subdued kingdoms, worked out righteousness, obtained promises, stopped the mouths of lions,Uëquenched the power of fire, escaped the edge of the sword, from weakness were made strong, grew mighty in war, and caused foreign armies to flee.UèWomen received their dead by resurrection. Others were tortured, not accepting their deliverance, that they might obtain a better resurrection.UTOthers were tried by mocking and scourging, yes, moreover by bonds and imprisonment.UµThey were stoned. They were sawn apart. They were tempted. They were slain with the sword. They went around in sheep skins and in goat skins; being destitute, afflicted, ill-treatedUg(of whom the world was not worthy), wandering in deserts, mountains, caves, and the holes of the earth.U^These all, having had testimony given to them through their faith, didn't receive the promise,UkGod having provided some better thing concerning us, so that apart from us they should not be made perfect.t(NUœTherefore let us also, seeing we are surrounded by so great a cloud of witnesses, lay aside every weight and the sin which so easily entangles us, and let us run with patience the race that is set before us,UΩlooking to Jesus, the author and perfecter of faith, who for the joy that was set before him endured the cross, despising its shame, and has sat down at the right hand of the throne of God.UÇFor consider him who has endured such contradiction of sinners against himself, that you don't grow weary, fainting in your souls.U9You have not yet resisted to blood, striving against sin;UØand you have forgotten the exhortation which reasons with you as with children, "My son, don't take lightly the chastening of the Lord, nor faint when you are reproved by him;UOFor whom the Lord loves, he chastens, and scourges every son whom he receives."UÑIt is for discipline that you endure. God deals with you as with children, for what son is there whom his father doesn't discipline?UvBut if you are without discipline, of which all have been made partakers, then are you illegitimate, and not children.U£Furthermore, we had the fathers of our flesh to chasten us, and we paid them respect. Shall we not much rather be in subjection to the Father of spirits, and live?UÖFor they indeed, for a few days, punished us as seemed good to them; but he for our profit, that we may be partakers of his holiness.U©All chastening seems for the present to be not joyous but grievous; yet afterward it yields the peaceful fruit of righteousness to those who have been exercised thereby.UATherefore, lift up the hands that hang down and the feeble knees,Uiand make straight paths for your feet, so that which is lame may not be dislocated, but rather be healed.U_Follow after peace with all men, and the sanctification without which no man will see the Lord,Uùlooking carefully lest there be any man who falls short of the grace of God; lest any root of bitterness springing up trouble you, and many be defiled by it;Unlest there be any sexually immoral person, or profane person, like Esau, who sold his birthright for one meal.U∞For you know that even when he afterward desired to inherit the blessing, he was rejected, for he found no place for a change of mind though he sought it diligently with tears.UxFor you have not come to a mountain that might be touched, and that burned with fire, and to blackness, darkness, storm,UÄthe sound of a trumpet, and the voice of words; which those who heard it begged that not one more word should be spoken to them,Upfor they could not stand that which was commanded, "If even an animal touches the mountain, it shall be stoned;"USand so fearful was the appearance, that Moses said, "I am terrified and trembling."UÑBut you have come to Mount Zion, and to the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, and to innumerable multitudes of angels,Uìto the general assembly and assembly of the firstborn who are enrolled in heaven, to God the Judge of all, to the spirits of just men made perfect,Unto Jesus, the mediator of a new covenant, and to the blood of sprinkling that speaks better than that of Abel.U¡See that you don't refuse him who speaks. For if they didn't escape when they refused him who warned on the Earth, how much more will we not escape who turn away from him who warns from heaven,Uâwhose voice shook the earth then, but now he has promised, saying, "Yet once more I will shake not only the earth, but also the heavens."U™This phrase, "Yet once more," signifies the removing of those things that are shaken, as of things that have been made, that those things which are not shaken may remain.UÜTherefore, receiving a Kingdom that can't be shaken, let us have grace, through which we serve God acceptably, with reverence and awe,U for our God is a consuming fire.t(NULet brotherly love continue.UpDon't forget to show hospitality to strangers, for in doing so, some have entertained angels without knowing it.UsRemember those who are in bonds, as bound with them; and those who are ill-treated, since you are also in the body.U~Let marriage be held in honor among all, and let the bed be undefiled: but God will judge the sexually immoral and adulterers.UõBe free from the love of money, content with such things as you have, for he has said, "I will in no way leave you, neither will I in any way forsake you."UbSo that with good courage we say, "The Lord is my helper. I will not fear. What can man do to me?"URemember your leaders, men who spoke to you the word of God, and considering the results of their conduct, imitate their faith.U7Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever.U∏Don't be carried away by various and strange teachings, for it is good that the heart be established by grace, not by food, through which those who were so occupied were not benefited.UUWe have an altar from which those who serve the holy tabernacle have no right to eat.UñFor the bodies of those animals, whose blood is brought into the holy place by the high priest as an offering for sin, are burned outside of 