riesthood, a holy nation, a people for God's own possession, that you may proclaim the excellence of him who called you out of darkness into his marvelous light:Uswho in time past were no people, but now are God's people, who had not obtained mercy, but now have obtained mercy.UiBeloved, I beg you as foreigners and pilgrims, to abstain from fleshly lusts, which war against the soul;U≥having good behavior among the nations, so in that of which they speak against you as evildoers, they may by your good works, which they see, glorify God in the day of visitation.UlTherefore subject yourselves to every ordinance of man for the Lord's sake: whether to the king, as supreme;U_or to governors, as sent by him for vengeance on evildoers and for praise to those who do well.UgFor this is the will of God, that by well-doing you should put to silence the ignorance of foolish men:UZas free, and not using your freedom for a cloak of wickedness, but as bondservants of God.U>Honor all men. Love the brotherhood. Fear God. Honor the king.UrServants, be in subjection to your masters with all fear; not only to the good and gentle, but also to the wicked.UdFor it is commendable if someone endures pain, suffering unjustly, because of conscience toward God.UúFor what glory is it if, when you sin, you patiently endure beating? But if, when you do well, you patiently endure suffering, this is commendable with God.U{For to this you were called, because Christ also suffered for us, leaving you an example, that you should follow his steps,U9who did not sin, "neither was deceit found in his mouth."UÉWho, when he was cursed, didn't curse back. When he suffered, didn't threaten, but committed himself to him who judges righteously;Uîwho his own self bore our sins in his body on the tree, that we, having died to sins, might live to righteousness; by whose stripes you were healed.UgFor you were going astray like sheep; but now have returned to the Shepherd and Overseer of your souls.t(NU¶In like manne